<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Discipline Urged in Nuke Spy Case  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, citing a  
``total breakdown in the system,'' today recommended disciplinary 
action against a senior official and two other employees of the Los 
Alamos nuclear laboratory because of failures in the China 
espionage investigation. Richardson did not identify the three. He 
said their ``responsibilities were clear and they failed to meet 
their responsibilities'' in the investigation of alleged spying by 
a Los Alamos scientist, Wen Ho Lee. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Suspect Charged With Murder  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas today  
revealed a detailed account of the murder of postal worker Joseph 
Santos Ileto shortly after county prosecutors filed new state 
charges against Buford O. Furrow Jr., accused in that killing and a 
bloody attack on a Jewish center. Furrow, a white supremacist, told 
the FBI that he killed a Filipino-American postal worker because he 
was nonwhite and worked for the federal government, authorities 
said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes for Cleaner Fuel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton set a goal today to reduce  
global warming over the next decade by increasing U.S. use of 
technology that converts plants and trees into fuel, chemicals and 
electricity. The president issued an executive order establishing a 
council to coordinate the federal government's effort to develop a 
biomass research program, and setting a goal of tripling use of 
bioenergy and bioproducts by 2010. Biomass energy is currently 
about 3 percent of the total U.S. energy supply. It uses trees, 
crops and waste from agriculture or forestry to make energy that 
can then be used as fuel for cars or power factories. 

</P>
<P>
	Honduras Finds Torture Cells at Base  
</P>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- A U.S.-built military base in  
Honduras contains cramped metal cells apparently used to torture 
and kill political prisoners, a top Honduran official said today. 
The cells -- along with dozens of possible grave sites -- were 
discovered this week at El Aguacate air base in eastern Honduras, 
which the United States built for Nicaraguan Contra rebels in 1983. 
It was also used by Honduran army troops. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Focuses on Islamic Uprising  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Facing criticism that Russia hasn't acted quickly  
enough to quash an Islamic rebellion in the south, President Boris 
Yeltsin promised today that the militants would be wiped out 
steadily but ``without haste.'' Russian lawmakers warned that the 
hostilities in Dagestan resemble those at the onset of Russia's 
botched war in the breakaway republic of Chechnya in 1994-96. 
Russian aircraft again fired on the rebels today, and more troops 
and weapons were sent to southern Russia. The militants maintained 
their hold on several villages. 

</P>
<P>
	Life Found 2.7 Bil. Years Old  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists studying Australian rocks have  
found evidence that primitive forms of life existed 2.7 billion 
years ago -- a billion years earlier than had been previously shown. 
``This age should provide a new calibration point for molecular 
clocks and the universal tree of life,'' researcher Jochen J. 
Brocks and his fellow Australian researchers report tomorrow in the 
journal Science. The finding pushes back evidence of life to the 
Archean era, the period from the beginning of Earth to about 2.5 
billion years ago. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Plans To Reduce Delays  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After being hammered by airline executives for  
flight delays this summer, the Federal Aviation Administration has 
developed a plan to help reduce such inconveniences. The agency, in 
a letter to the airlines, said it will soon have its command center 
start coordinating traffic flows in bad weather, eliminating 
conflicts between local centers spread across the country. The 
agency has also pledged to develop a policy in which airplanes held 
on the ground because of bad weather will be given a specific 
projected departure time. Airline passengers should start changes 
within the next several weeks. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 19.95 Points  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were held to a minuscule gain  
today and broader indicators retreated after a surge in interest 
rates following a disappointing Treasury bond auction. The Dow 
Jones industrial average ended up 19.95 at 10,807.75. Declines led 
advancers on the New York Stock Exchange 1525-1490. The Nasdaq 
Composite Index was down 15.50 at 2,549.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Haas, Weir, Hayes Lead in PGA  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- At the first round of the PGA Championship  
today, the early leaders were Jay Haas, Mike Weir and J.P. Hayes. 
Haas, who hasn't won in six years, took advantage of rain that 
softened the greens of Medinah Country Club to shoot a 4-under-par 
68 for a tie for the clubhouse lead with Weir and Hayes. Tiger 
Woods shot a 2-under 70 to stand two back after one round. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
