<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vanguard Founder Bogle To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --John C. Bogle, the founder of Vanguard Group and  
the public face behind the nation's second-largest family of U.S. 
mutual funds, will resign by year's end from Vanguard's board. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard said today that Bogle must step down under a policy  
that requires board members to resign in December of the year in 
which they reach 70. Bogle turned 70 in May. 
</P>
<P>
	But a report today in The Wall Street Journal said there was a  
dispute over whether the retirement policy was mandatory and also 
said there were policy differences between Bogle and his successor, 
John Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogle founded Vanguard in 1975 and now is senior chairman of the  
firm that manages nearly $500 billion in investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutual fund analysts said the transition between leaders is  
expected to be smooth because Vanguard's day-to-day operations have 
been run by Brennan, a protege of Bogle and the chairman and chief 
executive since 1996. Brennan is 45. 
</P>
<P>
	``Transition isn't the issue because Brennan has been running  
the show their for several years,'' said Dan Wiener, editor of The 
Independent Adviser for Vanguard Investors, a newsletter. ``The 
real loss is that of the Vanguard icon. Bogle is the last of the 
mutual fund icons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wiener said Bogle ``personified Vanguard.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Many of Vanguard's investors trust Bogle to look out for their  
best interests because he's the guy who started the whole thing,'' 
Wiener said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, on the other hand, while well known in the mutual fund  
world, is relatively unknown among consumers, according to Wiener. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported today that Bogle had  
differences with Brennan over Brennan's support for an expansion 
into the discount brokerage business. Bogle has complained that the 
discount business encourages a gambling mentality among investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogle also told the Journal that he felt the board's  
retirement-age policy was not mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard, based in Valley Forge, Pa., was formed in the wake of  
differences between the senior managers of Wellington Management, 
an investment firm founded in 1928. Vanguard is widely regarded as 
the fastest growing mutual fund company, with assets second only to 
Fidelity Investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press uses Vanguard to manage its retirement  
investment plans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
