<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Tired of Talking About Sanders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- Coach Bobby Ross and the rest of  
the Detroit Lions are tired of questions about Barry Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't even talk about Barry anymore,'' wide receiver  
Johnnie Morton said Thursday of the star running back, who 
announced his retirement two weeks ago. ``It's kind of getting 
blown out of proportion. It seems as if he's seen in a supermarket, 
everyone writes about it, and then we're asked about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's retired, just let him be.''  
</P>
<P>
	Added quarterback Charlie Batch: ``We can't stop a season just  
because he stopped playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Ross, he brushed away questions even before they were  
asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to comment on it,'' the coach said. ``I'm not  
going to talk about it. You're wasting your time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders reportedly returned Wednesday night from a European  
vacation that has occupied him since abruptly announcing his 
retirement July 28. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing his retirement, Sanders said his desire to quit  
football outweighed his desire to play -- even for the 1,458 yards 
he needs to break Walter Payton's career rushing record. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders' father has said he would try to arrange a meeting  
between his son and Lions Vice Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. But 
as late as Wednesday, the elder Sanders has said he hasn't heard 
from his son in weeks and was awaiting a call from him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Free Press reported Friday that the Lions have begun  
the process of reclaiming the unearned portion of the $11 million 
signing bonus Sanders received when he signed a six-year contract 
in 1997. The Lions are seeking a $7.3 million repayment. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief operating officer Chuck Schmidt said Thursday that the  
Lions had discussed the payback procedure with Sanders' agents, 
David Ware of Atlanta and Lamont Smith of Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``Early in the week, and then we said we were going to touch  
back with them in a week,'' Schmidt said. ``We didn't set a 
timetable, but we left it open that we're going to talk to each 
other fairly soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left Thursday with Ware were not returned.  
</P>
<P>
	Lions security director Allen Hughes, a family friend, has been  
staying with Wiliam Sanders in Wichita. The elder Sanders has said 
Hughes stay there was more pleasure than business. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said he never pressured the elder Sanders to try to get  
his son to come back to the team. He didn't have to -- Sanders 
already had promised his friend even before the visit that he would 
do anything he could to help. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Hughes said he came to visit the Sanders family in  
response to a long-standing invitation -- not at the Lions' urging. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not down here to try to convince anyone,'' he said. ``I  
came here to relax and have a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders has avoided all contact with the Lions' front  
office and coaching staff since the final game of last season. Ross 
tried to contact him through 13 telephone calls or handwritten 
letters, but Sanders never responded. 
</P>
<P>
	In talking about Friday's opening exhibition with Atlanta, Ross  
never mentioned the team's chances without Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	But he alluded briefly to Atlanta's All-Pro running back, Jamal  
Anderson who ended his contract holdout Wednesday and returned to 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	During the team's drills Thursday, there were unavoidable  
reminders of Sanders' absence. Many fans wore No. 20 jerseys. Near 
the team's practice field, a public-address system blared last 
season's highlights of Sanders, touted by the announcer as ``the 
standard by which all other running backs are measured.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
