<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A former Lutheran minister is about to become  
the first married priest in the Archdiocese of St. Paul and 
Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't be official until ordination, but the Vatican, acting  
under special pastoral provisions, has given the archdiocese 
permission to welcome Lawrence Blake into the ranks of its 500 
priests. 
</P>
<P>
	Blake, now a church administrator in Chanhassen, has worked in  
several parishes since he and his wife, Diane, converted to 
Catholicism in 1993. He's a graduate of Luther Seminary in St. Paul 
and is nearing a theology degree from St. Paul Seminary. 
</P>
<P>
	Blake, 47, of Victoria, will be allowed to perform such  
sacraments as baptism, marriage and communion. He joins more than 
70 married men nationwide, most of them former Episcopalians, who 
converted to Catholicism and became priests. 
</P>
<P>
	His ordination probably will take place before Christmas, said  
the Rev. Kevin McDonough, vicar general of Archdiocese of St. Paul 
and Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to pinch myself a couple of times to make sure it was  
real,'' Blake said. 
</P>
<P>
	He wanted to become a priest because of his heightened awareness  
of the importance of the Eucharist -- the presence of the body and 
blood of Christ in the bread and wine of communion -- celebrated in 
each Mass. McDonough said such devotion was probably the main 
reason the Vatican agreed to the archdiocese's request. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Podvin of Roseville, a priest in the archdiocese until  
he married in 1984, said Blake's situation ``was a very clear 
movement on the part of the church toward allowing men who are 
married and have families to be part of the church. And that only 
can enrich the church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Retreat for pastors of burned churches    	
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Pastors rebuilding from the ashes of arson  
fires will have a chance to receive advice and support at a 
national retreat at the Christian Theological Seminary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime a house of worship burns, whether it's an accident or  
not, it's a traumatic experience,'' said Edward L. Wheeler, 
president of the seminary in Indianapolis. ``Anytime it's arson, 
psychologically it's devastating, because the first question is, 
`Why would anybody do this?' '' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, keeping up a congregation's morale after a  
fire and leading efforts to rebuild are often physically and 
emotionally draining. 
</P>
<P>
	The program was founded in 1996 by the New York-based National  
Council of Churches in response to a number of church burnings 
across the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	During the retreats in November and April, pastors can attend  
classes and chapel services and will have time for reflection, 
relaxation and counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping they can share with each other, learn from each  
other to eliminate their isolation,'' Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Campus Crusade: Wives should 'submit'    	
</P>
<P>
	FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- Campus Crusade for Christ, one of the  
world's largest interdenominational ministries, has joined the 
Southern Baptist Convention in declaring that ``a wife is to submit 
herself graciously to the servant leadership of her husband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both groups say the wife is spiritually equal but ``has the  
God-given responsibility to respect her husband and to serve as his 
helper in managing the household and nurturing the next 
generation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campus Crusade issued its policy statement at a recent biennial  
staff conference attended by 6,900 employees, students and family 
members. The Southern Baptist Convention issued its statement last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both declare that children are a blessing ``from the moment of  
conception'' and that sex should be confined to marriage. They 
define marriage as heterosexual and lifelong, and the family as 
persons related ``by marriage, blood or adoption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campus Crusade expanded its policy to say that couples show  
their love by listening to, valuing and honoring each other ``and 
always seeking to bring benefit, not harm, to one another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campus Crusade, led by Bill Bright and based in Orlando, Fla.,  
operates 50 evangelistic ministries with 20,500 staff members and 
663,000 volunteers worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Locals barred from Navy chapel    	
</P>
<P>
	CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) -- Virginia's two senators have asked the  
Navy to review an order that some local Roman Catholics say 
discriminates against them. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. R.W. Jerome, commander of a small naval security  
installation in Chesapeake, recently barred civilians from 
worshipping at the base chapel. Jerome also limited the number of 
Catholic services at the chapel and revoked permission for the 
Knights of Columbus, a Catholic fraternal organization, to meet on 
base, where a chapter had been founded under his predecessor. 
</P>
<P>
	The chapel is outside the gates of the base, and local Catholics  
had considered it something like a parish. Many complained to Sens. 
John Warner and Charles Robb about the limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner, a Republican, and Robb, a Democrat, have sent separate  
letters to Rear Adm. Norbert Ryan Jr. of the Pentagon's Legislative 
Affairs Office. 
</P>
<P>
	A Navy representative said the legislative affairs office would  
respond but gave no timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *NRB opposes low-power FM stations    	
</P>
<P>
	MANASSAS, Va. (AP) -- National Religious Broadcasters, which  
represents 1,275 radio and TV stations with an evangelical format, 
is urging the Federal Communications Commission to scuttle a 
proposal to add low-power FM radio stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Some religious groups are interested in starting new low-power  
stations. However, ``while it would be advantageous to have more 
stations transmitting the gospel message, we must protect existing 
stations first,'' NRB president Brandt Gustavson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade association contends that the FCC proposal would end  
protection against frequency interference and would overcrowd the 
airwaves. 
  	   	
</P>
