<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Schilling To Miss Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia ace Curt Schilling did not  
throw Thursday and was scratched from his next start in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling has not started since last Saturday against Arizona,  
when he allowed seven earned runs and eight hits in 6 1-3 innings 
of the Phillies' 8-2 loss. The 32-year-old right-hander is 
suffering from biceps tendinitis, mild bursitis and -- the latest 
ailment -- muscle spasms in his neck and shoulder blades. 
</P>
<P>
	His anticipated bullpen session was canceled Wednesday when he  
felt muscle spasms, and team doctor Michael Ciccotti advised him to 
push it back to Saturday in hopes of making his next start Tuesday 
in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am feeling better,'' Schilling said. ``But until it clears  
up, I won't be able to test my arm. I'm following the advice of the 
doctor, trainers and (pitching coach) Galen Cisco. Hopefully I can 
throw at some point this weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From the Phillies' standpoint, that is an understatement.  
Schilling's ability to shake off this string of injuries and finish 
the season has everything to do with their chances in the NL 
playoff race. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Ciccotti said an MRI and a trip to the disabled  
list were considerations if Schilling's next throwing session did 
not go well. It is not to that point yet, partly because Ciccotti's 
examinations have showed nothing structurally wrong with 
Schilling's shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling had a cortisone shot Sunday to ease his tendinitis and  
bursitis, and X-rays showed that no bone spurs had formed. 
Schilling had a torn labrum repaired and a bone spur removed in 
major shoulder surgery in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt it was in everyone's best interest for him not to  
throw on the side today,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said. 
``We'll bump his start back to Tuesday. That way, he'll have the 
weekend to try to iron things out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling led the league with 300 strikeouts, 268 2-3 innings  
and 15 complete games last season. He's dropped to fifth in the NL 
in strikeouts this season, fading in his bid to join Nolan Ryan as 
the only pitchers to strike out 300 batters in three consecutive 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He is second in the majors to Randy Johnson with eight complete  
games, throwing five straight early in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Chad Ogea will start Saturday in Schilling's place  
in a big series against a team that is ahead of the Phillies in the 
NL wild-card standings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
