<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canucks' Sedin Twins Stay in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The Vancouver Canucks will  
have to do without the highly-touted twin-brother combo of Daniel 
and Henrik Sedin, who announced Thursday that they will remain in 
Sweden this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Burke, Canucks president and general manager, was informed  
of the decision by their agent Mike Barnett. 
</P>
<P>
	``The twins were honest about their desire to stay in Sweden  
from the start, and this is news our club expected,'' said Burke. 
``It was important for them to follow through on their commitments 
with MoDo (of the Swedish Elite League) for a number of reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think they'll be improved players with one more year of  
experience. The other factor in their decision was school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burke said the 18-year-old Sedin brothers have yet to decide  
whether to attend the Canucks training camp next month. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Burke who made a number of draft-day trades to obtain the  
second and third picks that enabled the Canucks to select the twins 
last June. Prior to the draft, the Sedins -- voted co-MVPs of the 
Swedish Elite League last season -- had expressed a strong desire to 
play for the same NHL team. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Sedin, a left wing, led MoDo with 21 goals and 42 points  
in 50 games last season. Henrik Sedin, a center, finished third 
among MoDo scorers, with 12 goals and 34 points in 49 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
