<DOCNO> APW19990812.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:56:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers Fire Manager Phil Garner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Nearly eight years ago, Phil Garner and Sal  
Bando joined the Milwaukee Brewers together. It appears they will 
leave that way, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner was fired as the Brewers' manager Wednesday night and  
will be replaced by hitting coach Jim Lefebvre on an interim basis, 
The Associated Press learned. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, general manager Bando will resign, the Milwaukee  
Journal Sentinel and WTMJ-TV reported Thursday, citing unidentified 
sources. Bando hired Garner, his former teammate, shortly after 
becoming the Brewers' GM in October 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee is currently enduring its seventh straight losing  
season, falling to 52-60 after an 8-5 defeat by Colorado on 
Wednesday. The only manager to survive more consecutive losing 
campaigns than Garner is Connie Mack, who did it twice with the 
Philadelphia Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Cox of Atlanta, Cleveland's Mike Hargrove and Tom Kelly of  
Minnesota are the only managers who have been with their teams 
longer than Garner, who is both the winningest and losingest 
manager in Brewers history. 
</P>
<P>
	Lefebvre, the only member of Garner's staff with managing  
experience, was to be appointed interim manager today, a source 
familiar with the hiring told the AP on the condition of anonymity. 
Lefebvre, who managed the Seattle Mariners and the Chicago Cubs 
from 1989-93, was signed as manager only through the remainder of 
the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers, who don't play today, start a road trip Friday at  
Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball commissioner Bud Selig, whose family controls the team,  
said he had no knowledge of any departures and referred questions 
to his daughter, Wendy Selig-Prieb, who succeeded him as club 
president. Selig-Prieb, Bando and Garner could not be reached for 
comment Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Lefebvre was hired as the Brewers' batting coach last August  
during a shakeup of the team's coaching staff. Lefebvre, Garner and 
the rest of Milwaukee's coaches are under contract only through the 
end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers went 4-8 on a 12-game homestand that ended Wednesday  
with the loss to Colorado. Milwaukee reached .500 five times this 
season, but failed each time to get above the mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner told reporters after Wednesday's game that he hadn't  
heard anything about being fired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know a thing,'' he said. ``I just called my wife.  
There's nothing on our messages at home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bando signed a three-year contract extension last October  
despite the team's lack of improvement. Milwaukee was 92-70 during 
the pair's first year in 1992, but hasn't finished above .500 since 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	Bando's biggest free-agent gambles of the last offseason have  
been enormous busts. Pitcher Jim Abbott was ineffective and retired 
from baseball last month, while infielder Sean Berry is hitting 
.232 and has been benched for long periods. 
</P>
<P>
	Lefebvre has ample experience managing mediocre clubs. He had a  
395-414 record as manager of the Seattle Mariners from 1989-91 and 
the Cubs the following two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Selig sent a letter to all teams saying he  
had to be notified of all managerial openings, that minorities must 
be considered before positions are filled and that he wanted an 
advance list of all candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner has managed more games than anyone in Brewers history,  
compiling a 563-617 record. He was hired in October 1991 with no 
previous managing experience, and was runner-up for the AL Manager 
of the Year award in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Brewers haven't finished with a winning record since,  
and this season's promising start has given way to disappointment 
as the team began to slide in July. Milwaukee is 10-16 since the 
All-Star break and has fallen from third place to fifth in the NL 
Central. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the ballclub respects me,'' Garner said. ``I think the  
players have done very, very well under the speculation of what 
might happen to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garner had a 15-year playing career as an infielder for Oakland,  
Pittsburgh, Houston, Los Angeles and San Francisco. He retired in 
1988 and spent three years on Houston manager Art Howe's coaching 
staff before succeeding Tom Trebelhorn in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Given relatively little talent to use, he presided over nearly  
eight seasons of mediocrity in Milwaukee. However, with his 
outgoing personality and soft Texas drawl, Garner was a favorite 
among Brewers fans, and he was active in charity concerns off the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner is still well-respected in baseball and likely will be a  
strong candidate for another managerial job next season. Bando 
co-owns a successful venture capital company in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bando played 16 seasons with the Athletics and the Brewers as a  
third baseman. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller Park, the Brewers' new stadium still under construction,  
was scheduled to open next spring, but a crane accident last month 
that killed three workers has put the opening date in doubt. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
