<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Reno Affirms Gun Control Commitment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno today renewed the  
Clinton administration's commitment to stiffer gun control, and 
then went further. ``I believe we must seriously explore the 
possibility of requiring the licensing of all handguns,'' she said. 
Her comments come after yesterday's shootings at a Jewish community 
center in Los Angeles. Buford O. Furrow, 37, has reportedly 
admitted wounding five and killing a postal worker in the attack. 
Meanwhile, President Clinton is expected to discuss the attack with 
a delegation of American Jewish leaders at the White House this 
afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Crops Predicted Despite Drought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the heat and drought that have plagued  
parts of the country this summer, farmers will harvest bin-busting 
crops of corn, soybeans and rice, the Agriculture Department said 
today. The department said it expects a modest increase in prices 
for some commodities because of tightening world supplies or rising 
exports. The higher prices could save the government as much as $1 
billion in crop subsidies, but many farmers still wouldn't recover 
their cost of production. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Plans Push Against Rebels  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian jets and helicopters attacked  
Islamic rebels in southern Russia for a sixth day today, and a 
general said a ``massive operation'' would be launched soon. The 
Russian forces have been using their superior firepower to hammer 
away at the militants in the Caucasus Mountain region of Dagestan. 
But ground troops have been reluctant to fight the separatist 
rebels, who are holding several villages. Acting Prime Minister 
Vladimir Putin, who was appointed to the job Monday, has promised 
swift action, saying the insurgents will be crushed within two 
weeks. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Increases Border Patrols  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Seeking to avoid further escalation  
of tensions with India, Pakistan has increased border patrols with 
F-16 fighters to prevent Indian intrusions. Pakistani Foreign 
Minister Sartaj Aziz said today the aircraft were deployed at 
Pakistan's southern border with India. Meanwhile, the nuclear 
rivals remained on high alert after two days of air clashes. 
Tensions soared Tuesday when an Indian jet downed a Pakistani naval 
patrol plane. Pakistan responded the next day, firing a missile at 
Indian fighters and helicopters. 

</P>
<P>
	Wiretapping Bill Approved in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Parliament today gave Japanese police new powers to  
use wiretaps against organized crime. The vote gives Japanese 
police surveillance powers similar to those enjoyed by 
investigators in other countries. The provision is to take effect 
within a year. The wiretapping law is similar to those in other 
countries. But many Japanese, remembering secret police brutality 
during World War II and crackdowns on radical students and labor 
unions in the 1950s and 1960s, have long been reluctant to hand 
police greater powers. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Tries Cutting Smoking, Drinking  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese government panel today proposed a  
campaign to cut the nation's tobacco consumption in half by 2010, a 
Health Ministry official said. The plan is part of a 10-year 
national project to improve the nation's health, ministry official 
Hiroshi Saito said. The panel also said the recommended limit for 
individual alcohol consumption should be reduced to 5.4 ounces a 
day from 16.2 ounces. In Japan, heavy drinking is common and 35 
percent of the adult population smokes. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Eyes Westchester NY Home  
</P>
<P>
	EDGEMONT, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's spokeswoman says  
the first lady has settled on Westchester County as her future 
home. Mrs. Clinton, who is considering a run for the U.S. Senate in 
New York, checked out a house near Scarsdale that carries a $1.7 
million price tag and annual taxes of $25,000. She must move to the 
state by Election Day 2000 to be eligible to run for the Senate. 
Some say she should move as soon as possible to deflate any 
carpetbagging charge. 

</P>
<P>
	Wall Street Stocks Open Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 66.18 at 10,853.98, adding to yesterday's 
132.65-point gain. Advancers led decliners 1,447 to 1,184. The 
Nasdaq Composite Index was up 7.75 at 2572.73. 

</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee Brewers Fire Manager  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Phil Garner was fired as the Brewers' manager  
last night and will be replaced by hitting coach Jim Lefebvre on an 
interim basis, The Associated Press learned. In addition, general 
manager Sal Bando will resign, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel and 
WTMJ-TV reported today, citing unidentified sources. Bando hired 
Garner, his former teammate, shortly after becoming the Brewers' GM 
in October 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
