<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea Lashes Out at Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- North Korea on Thursday threatened to ``make  
Japan pay a high price'' for what it described as a century of 
hostilities, and repeated its insistence that it has the right to 
test-fire rockets at will. 
</P>
<P>
	Ri Gi-pom, a counselor at the North Korean Embassy in Beijing,  
said North Korea wants Japan to apologize and make reparations for 
colonizing Korea early this century and killing about 1 million 
people, enslaving millions more and forcing 200,000 Korean women to 
work as sex slaves for the military. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea also blames Japan for backing the United States and  
rival South Korea during the 1950-1953 Korean War. 
</P>
<P>
	If Japan does not make amends, North Korea will retaliate,  
``make Japan pay a high price for the bloodshed'' and ``give vent 
to its century-old wrath,'' Ri said, reading a government statement 
timed in advance of North Korea's national day on Sunday. The 
holiday marks Korea's liberation from Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ri declined to specify what kind of retaliation he meant.  
</P>
<P>
	He also said North Korea planned to launch a rocket as ``a  
matter of sovereignty'' and ``when it is necessary.'' He would not 
elaborate or pinpoint a date. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea is reportedly preparing to test-fire a new  
long-range missile with the capacity to reach Alaska or Hawaii. The 
United States, Japan and South Korea have told the North to call 
off the firing or face economic and diplomatic sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Relations between North Korea and Japan have deteriorated since  
North Korea sent a rocket sailing over Japan and into the Pacific 
Ocean a year ago. The test demonstrated that Japan is well within 
reach of North Korean missiles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
