<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Wants Tougher Hate Crime Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT DODGE, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore called for both  
tougher hate crime laws and new gun controls Thursday in the wake 
of a deadly shooting at a Jewish center in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also issued a veiled message ``to all those who would seek  
to lead this nation,'' a slap at a GOP presidential field where 
candidates have generally resisted the measures he pushed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really amazes me how some people can pretend that hate  
crimes are not different from all other crimes,'' said Gore. ``Hate 
crimes wound all of America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his proposals ``would help prevent these tragedies from  
happening in the first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His comments came as Buford O. Furrow Jr. was charged in the  
latest deadly shooting episode. 
</P>
<P>
	``After all the painful gun violence we have seen in America, I  
say to all those who would seek to lead this nation `stop trying to 
pass special protections for the gun manufacturers.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore did not spell out details of his hate crime or gun  
proposals. But on the gun issue, he said he wants to make it harder 
for felons and children to obtain guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments came during a speech in which Gore fleshed out  
education proposals he said would be central to his campaign for 
the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans criticized Gore for referring to the community  
center shooting in his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's truly sad to see the vice president use this horrible act  
of violence in a cynical attempt to help his struggling campaign,'' 
said Mike Collins, spokesman for the Republican National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In his package. Gore said he would offer incentives to states  
which raise the compulsory education age to 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``As president I will urge every state in America to require  
students to stay in school until the age of 18 or until they 
graduate from high school,'' said Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Gore's plan would provide grants and other incentives  
for states which put in place dropout prevention programs that have 
an impact on keeping youngsters in school. 
</P>
<P>
	``More and more the opportunity gap in America has become an  
education gap,'' said Gore. He placed no pricetag on the proposal, 
which was part of a larger education package he unveiled during a 
campaign swing through Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	He also called for tax credits of up to $6,000 per worker for  
companies which put in place worker retraining programs, doubling 
the current level. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
