<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 14:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 1.59  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were held to a minuscule gain  
today and broader indicators retreated. A surge in interest rates 
following a disappointing Treasury bond auction deflated a bid to 
extend yesterday's broad stock market rally. The Dow Jones 
industrial average was up 1.59 at 10,789.39. The Dow rose as much 
as 113 points earlier. Broader indicators gave up early gains to 
finish lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.77 to 1,298.16 and 
the Nasdaq composite index fell 15.49 to 2,549.49. 

</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close Thursday:  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans snapped up cars and light trucks  
last month at a brisk clip that helped push overall retail sales up 
by a bigger-than-expected 0.7 percent. The Commerce Department 
reported today that total retail sales, which represent about a 
third of the nation's economic output, rose last month to a 
seasonally adjusted $248.7 billion. Sales were 9.1 percent higher 
than July of last year. Many economists continue to believe the 
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates again on Aug. 24, to keep 
the economy from overheating and hold inflation under control. The 
Fed nudged interest rates a quarter of a point on June 30. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Crops Projected Despite Drought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While farmers' fields parch in the East, much  
of America's heartland has had sufficient rain and that means 
bumper crops and little help for depressed commodity prices. This 
year's soybean crop is shaping up to be the biggest on record, and 
the corn harvest would be the third largest, the Agriculture 
Department reported Wednesday. Big crops of cotton and rice are 
expected across the South. Because of tighter world supplies and 
improved exports, USDA expects a modest increase in prices for some 
commodities -- 20 cents a bushel for soybeans and 5 cents a bushel 
for corn -- from what was forecast a month ago. 

</P>
<P>
	BET Launches Web Site for Blacks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The owner of the leading black cable TV network  
is launching an ambitious Web site aimed at luring more black 
Americans online, a move to narrow the ``digital divide'' that has 
left use of the Internet among blacks well below whites. BET.com, 
which will be launched in November by BET Holdings, is getting $35 
million in backing from Microsoft Corp. and three major media 
companies, as well as cooperation from the NAACP and the United 
Negro College Fund. BET Holdings will control a majority of the new 
venture, and the rest will be held by Microsoft, Rupert Murdoch's 
News Corp., USA Networks Inc., and AT&AMP;T's Liberty Media Corp. 

</P>
<P>
	Military Engine Plant Leaving Fla.  
</P>
<P>
	EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Jet engine maker Pratt &AMP; Whitney  
will move its military engine operations from Florida to 
Connecticut and relocate other operations, cutting about 1,500 
jobs. In addition to moving the military business from West Palm 
Beach, Fla., to its headquarters here, Pratt, a subsidiary of 
United Technologies Corp., said today that it would move its 
manufacturing operation from North Haven, Conn., to the East 
Hartford plant. Pratt has been hit hard by the decline in demand 
for its military engines, including powerplants for the F-15 and 
F-16 fighters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Mutual To Cut 1,500 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Liberty Mutual Group plans to cut 1,500 jobs and  
reduce expenses by more than $150 million by the first quarter in 
2000 as it realigns its commercial insurance operation. Liberty 
Mutual president and chief executive officer Edmund F. Kelly blamed 
the cuts on industrywide stagnation. The reorganization will create 
a single account business unit from the Wausau Insurance Companies, 
which Liberty owns, and Liberty Mutual. 

</P>
<P>
	Vanguard Founder To Retire in Dec.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John C. Bogle, the public face of the nation's  
second-largest family of U.S. mutual funds, will resign by year's 
end from the board of Vanguard Group. Vanguard said today that its 
founder must step down under a policy that requires board members 
to resign in December of the year in which they reach 70. Bogle 
turned 70 in May. Vanguard dismissed the contention that 
controversy surrounds Bogle's retirement. Vanguard spokesman John 
Demming said Vanguard has a ``long-standing policy'' established by 
the board regarding the retirement policies of its board members. 

</P>
<P>
	BOT Closes Early on Power Outage  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade closed an hour early  
today after a power outage affecting the downtown Loop area 
threatened to expand. CBOT chief executive officer Thomas R. 
Donovan made the decision to close the markets at 2 p.m. after 
speaking to Commonwealth Edison CEO John Rowe, a CBOT spokesman 
said. The problems were blamed on the failures of two power 
transmission cables, which left 2,300 customers in the heart of 
downtown Chicago in the dark. The Chicago Mercantile Exchange 
remained open. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Moves To Cut Smoking  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese government panel today proposed a  
campaign to cut the nation's tobacco consumption in half by 2010, a 
Health Ministry official said. The Council on Public Health 
unveiled the plan as part of a 10-year national project to improve 
the nation's health, dubbed ``Healthy Japan 21,'' ministry official 
Hiroshi Saito said. The ministry will begin implementing the 
project next year, and the council currently is setting numerical 
goals in nine categories, including tobacco and alcohol. 

</P>
<P>
	Code Cracker Worries Cryptographers  
</P>
<P>
	WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- A developer of one of the most  
widespread computer encryption systems said today he has designed a 
computer that could crack open a file encoded using the most common 
form of data encryption in only a few days. If built -- at a cost of 
about $2 million -- such a computer could jeopardize the privacy of 
the bulk of electronic commerce as practiced today, according to 
cryptographers at the conference where the design was shown. Most 
highly sensitive military and banking data are protected by 
stronger encryption keys beyond its reach. The commonly used weaker 
keys, though, would become ``easy to break for large 
organizations,'' said cryptographer Adi Shamir of the Weizmann 
Institute of Science in Rehovot, Israel. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 4,000 to 284,000  
</P>
<P>
	Retail sales: up 0.7 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Business inventories  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Producer prices  



  	   	
</P>
