<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Suspect May Face Death Penalty  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A white supremacist charged with shooting  
five people at a Jewish community center told investigators he also 
killed a Filipino-American postal worker because he was not white 
and worked for the federal government, a prosecutor said today. The 
account, based on an alleged confession by Buford O. Furrow Jr., 
came after Los Angeles County prosecutors charged him with murder 
and five counts of attempted murder -- all filed as hate crimes. 
Federal prosecutors already had charged Furrow in the postman's 
slaying. The murder charges could bring the death penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	Power Outage Hits Downtown Chicago  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Confusion descended on downtown today when a  
series of mechanical problems darkened hundreds of office 
buildings, snarled traffic and skidded the Chicago Board of Trade 
to a halt. Thousands of commuters left early for the day when power 
was lost, pushing the rush hour forward by hours. Police struggled 
to keep cars moving through darkened intersections. Extra buses 
were called in to handle the crush and generators were set up in 
Union Station, which handles Amtrak and suburban commuter trains. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Spy Case Discipline Sought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, citing a  
``total breakdown in the system,'' today recommended disciplinary 
action against a senior official and two other employees of the Los 
Alamos nuclear laboratory because of failures in the China 
espionage investigation. An internal investigation found ``systemic 
problems in the Energy Department's management of 
counterintelligence matters.'' But no action was taken against any 
department headquarters officials. Nor were any former senior DOE 
officials singled out by name for criticism. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Vows To End Islamic Uprising  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin, facing criticism that  
Russia hasn't acted quickly enough to quash an Islamic rebellion in 
the south, promised Thursday that the militants would be wiped out 
steadily but ``without haste.'' Yeltsin's acting prime minister, 
Vladimir Putin, was chastised by members of Russia's upper house of 
parliament, who said Russia should act more resolutely to stamp out 
the rebels who invaded several villages in the Caucasus region of 
Dagestan last week. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Army Chief Criticizes Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia has reached ``a virtual  
dead end'' under President Slobodan Milosevic, his former army 
chief said Thursday and pledged to work to oust him. The former 
army chief, Gen. Momcilo Perisic, was sacked by Milosevic last 
November after he opposed the president's defiant policies toward 
the West. Perisic said he is forming the Movement for Democratic 
Serbia, whose prime goal would be to remove Milosevic. Showing no 
sign he's willing to step down peacefully, Milosevic tightened his 
ranks by reshuffling his government and naming several 
ultranationalists as Cabinet ministers. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Seeks To Speed Up Peacemaking  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak made a new  
pitch Thursday for speeding up peacemaking with the Palestinians, 
telling Secretary of State Madeleine Albright through an envoy that 
haggling over interim measures wasted time. Precious time would be 
spent better by opening negotiations on a final settlement, Barak 
said through Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, the envoy told Israeli 
reporters afterward. 

</P>
<P>
	`Spanish-Only' in Texas Town  
</P>
<P>
	EL CENIZO, Texas (AP) -- A community on the Mexican border has  
declared itself a ``safe haven'' for undocumented immigrants and 
passed an ordinance making Spanish the town's official language. 
Any city worker who helps the U.S. Border Patrol uncover 
undocumented immigrants will be fired, Mayor Rafael Rodriguez said. 
El Cenizo, incorporated in 1989, is an impoverished town with a 
high population of first-generation immigrants, both documented and 
undocumented. It sits alongside the Rio Grande about 10 miles south 
of Laredo. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Are Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell moderately Friday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average shed 91.80 points to 17,332.17 in early 
trading. On Wall Street, the Dow gained 1.59 points to 10,789.39 at 
Thursday's close. 

</P>
<P>
	Tigers Defeat Rangers 3-1  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Aaron Sele struck out a career-high 13,  
the most by a Rangers pitcher in seven years, but Tony Clark 
homered as the Detroit Tigers beat Texas 3-1 tonight. Dave Mlicki 
(7-10) allowed four hits in 5 2-3 innings. He helped Detroit end 
its five-game losing streak against Texas. Reliever Francisco 
Cordero struck out four straight Rangers in the sixth and seventh, 
and Todd Jones pitched the ninth for his 18th save. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
