<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake Tornado Injures 79  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee Corradini said  
this morning that 79 were injured yesterday when a tornado tore 
through the heart of the city. About a dozen were in serious to 
critical condition, she said. ``It's been a tragedy for us, but 
we've been very, very lucky -- it could have been much worse,'' the 
mayor said. Corradini said crews had worked through the night 
clearing debris and, ``We are open for business in downtown Salt 
Lake City this morning.'' Gov. Mike Leavitt, in an interview today 
with ABC, said, ``There was virtually no way in which to warn 
people.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Shooting Suspect Had Neo-Nazi Ties  
</P>
<P>
	NISQUALLY, Wash. (AP) -- People in this rural area outside  
Olympia where Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr. grew up describe him as a 
bespectacled, beefy kid who was teased about his allergies. 
Authorities say the overweight kid grew up to become an overwrought 
adult who once predicted a deadly outburst. Furrow turned himself 
in to the FBI in Las Vegas yesterday, saying he had ``killed the 
kids in Los Angeles.'' None of those shot Tuesday at the Jewish 
community center died, but postal worker Joseph Ileto, 39, was 
killed about an hour later. Furrow, 37, is charged with his murder. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan OKs New Wiretapping Bill  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Parliament today gave Japanese police new powers to  
use wiretaps against organized crime. The vote gives Japanese 
police surveillance powers similar to those enjoyed by 
investigators in other countries. The provision is to take effect 
within a year. The wiretapping law is similar to those in other 
countries. But many Japanese, remembering secret police brutality 
during World War II and crackdowns on radical students and labor 
unions in the 1950s and 1960s, have long been reluctant to hand 
police greater powers. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Moves To Cut Smoking  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese government panel today proposed a  
campaign to cut the nation's tobacco consumption in half by 2010, a 
Health Ministry official said. The plan is part of a 10-year 
national project to improve the nation's health, ministry official 
Hiroshi Saito said. The panel also said the recommended limit for 
individual alcohol consumption should be reduced to 5.4 ounces a 
day from 16.2 ounces. In Japan, heavy drinking is common and 35 
percent of the adult population smokes. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Crackdown Victims Reburied  
</P>
<P>
	VELIKA KRUSA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Weeping friends and relatives  
today reburied dozens of men, women and children killed and dumped 
in mass graves during the Serb crackdown on Kosovo Albanians. This 
southwestern Kosovo village was an apparent target of revenge 
killings and other atrocities as the Serb campaign against Kosovo's 
Albanians peaked earlier this year. Human rights investigators 
believe about 10,000 ethnic Albanians died in the crackdown, which 
ended after the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia led President 
Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw his forces from the province and let 
in NATO-led peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	1st Lady Wants Westchester NY Home  
</P>
<P>
	EDGEMONT, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's spokeswoman says  
the first lady has settled on Westchester County as her future 
home. Mrs. Clinton, who is considering a run for the U.S. Senate in 
New York, checked out a house near Scarsdale that carries a $1.7 
million price tag and annual taxes of $25,000. She must move to the 
state by Election Day 2000 to be eligible to run for the Senate. 
Some say she should move as soon as possible to deflate any 
carpetbagging charge. 

</P>
<P>
	Wall Street Stocks Open Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today, with the blue-chips  
making the most aggressive push to extend yesterday's rally. Just 
before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow was up 6.97 to 10794.77 and advancers 
led decliners 1,333 to 1,056. The Nasdaq Composite Index was down 
8.37 at 2556.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Brewers Fire Manager Phil Garner  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Phil Garner was fired as the Brewers' manager  
last night and will be replaced by hitting coach Jim Lefebvre on an 
interim basis, The Associated Press learned. In addition, general 
manager Sal Bando will resign, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel and 
WTMJ-TV reported today, citing unidentified sources. Bando hired 
Garner, his former teammate, shortly after becoming the Brewers' GM 
in October 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
