<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Spy Case Discipline Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recommending disciplinary action today against  
a senior official and two other employees of the Los Alamos nuclear 
laboratory because of failures in the China espionage 
investigation, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, cited a ``total 
breakdown in the system.'' While the internal investigation also 
cited ``systemic problems in the Energy Department's management of 
counterintelligence matters,'' no action was taken against any 
department headquarters officials. Nor were any former senior DOE 
officials singled out by name for criticism. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspected L.A. Shooter Is Charged  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A prosecutor said today that a white  
supremacist charged with shooting five people at a Los Angeles 
Jewish community center admitted he also killed a Filipino-American 
postal worker because he was not white and worked for the federal 
government. The alleged confession by Buford O. Furrow Jr. came 
after Los Angeles County prosecutors charged him with murder and 
five counts of attempted murder -- all hate crimes. Federal 
prosecutors already had charged Furrow in the postman's slaying. 

</P>
<P>
	Power Outage Hits Downtown Chicago  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Hundreds of downtown businesses, the Chicago  
Board of Trade and the federal courthouse were left without power 
for over an hour today after a series of mechanical problems shut 
down several transformers. Power was restored about 3 p.m. local 
time Commonwealth Edison said cables leading from two big 
transformers had failed at a substation just south of downtown, 
leaving 2,300 customers without electricity. A third transformer at 
the station had failed Aug. 5. 

</P>
<P>
	Evolution Vote May Have Small Effect  
</P>
<P>
	TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- Some local Kansas officials are not planning  
to change what their schools teach about evolution, even though the 
State Board of Education's new testing standards de-emphasize its 
importance, especially the theory that man descended from apes. 
Local school districts will continue to decide what subjects are 
taught in their classrooms. Both critics and supporters of the 
standards approved yesterday said they could influence some lesson 
plans. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Says Parents Key to Schools  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hollywood, Washington and the heartland all  
have roles in keeping schools and students safe, but the spotlight 
belongs to parents, President Clinton said today. ``No influence on 
a child is more important,'' Clinton said in videotaped remarks 
prepared for parents attending an Education Department forum, 
according to a White House transcript. The national forum, by 
satellite, was intended to focus on parents. The event comes amid 
months of debates on gun control and violence in popular culture. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Challenges Gore on Abortion  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley  
challenged Vice President Al Gore today to clarify his position on 
federally funding abortions for poor women in light of conflicting 
statements by Gore's staff this week. ``I think it is time for him 
to answer what his position is,'' Bradley said in an interview 
today with The Associated Press. ``On this issue in particular 
you've got to say what you believe.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Army Chief Criticizes Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia has reached ``a virtual  
dead end'' under President Slobodan Milosevic, his former army 
chief said today and pledged to work to oust him. But Milosevic, 
showing no sign he's willing to step down peacefully, tightened his 
ranks today by reshuffling his government and naming several 
ultranationalists as Cabinet ministers. The former army chief, Gen. 
Momcilo Perisic, was sacked by Milosevic last November after he 
opposed the president's defiant policies toward the West. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 1.59 Points  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were held to a minuscule gain  
today and broader indicators retreated after a surge in interest 
rates followed a disappointing Treasury bond auction. The Dow Jones 
industrial average ended up 1.59 at 10,789.39. Declines led 
advancers on the New York Stock Exchange 1,525-1,490. The Nasdaq 
Composite Index was down 15.50 at 2,549.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Players Lead PGA Championship  
</P>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Golfers Jay Haas, Mike Weir and J.P. Hayes  
shared the lead in today's first round of the PGA Championship. The 
three players took advantage of rain that softened the greens of 
Medinah Country Club to shoot a 4-under-par 68 for the early 
clubhouse lead. Tiger Woods shot a 2-under 70 to stand two back. 

</P>
