<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Suspect Charged With Murder  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Buford O. Furrow Jr. has been charged with  
murder and attempted murder in the killing of a postal worker and 
the shooting at a Jewish community center Tuesday near Los Angeles. 
Furrow told the FBI that he killed a Filipino-American postal 
worker because he was nonwhite and worked for the federal 
government, authorities said. U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas 
revealed a detailed account of the murder of postal worker Joseph 
Santos Ileto shortly after county prosecutors filed state charges 
against Furrow today. 

</P>
<P>
	Life on Earth Traced Earlier  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists studying Australian rocks have  
found evidence that primitive forms of life existed 2.7 billion 
years ago -- a billion years earlier than had been previously shown. 
``This age should provide a new calibration point for molecular 
clocks and the universal tree of life,'' researcher Jochen J. 
Brocks and his fellow Australian researchers report tomorrow in the 
journal Science. The finding pushes back evidence of life to the 
Archean era, the period from the beginning of Earth to about 2.5 
billion years ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Eichmann Papers Found in Germany  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Adolf Eichmann, mastermind of the Holocaust,  
complains about an unfairly strict upbringing, describes his 
inability to disobey an order and ponders the meaning of life in an 
apparent first draft of his prison memoir released today. The 127 
handwritten pages, with the heading ``My Memoirs,'' were discovered 
in prosecution files brought to Germany after the Nazi war 
criminal's 1962 execution, said prosecutor Willi Dressen. The pages 
published today were released two days after Israel announced it 
would hand over a 1,300-page memoir Eichmann wrote while in prison 
there in 1961 and 1962. 

</P>
<P>
	Rare Tadpoles Stolen in Denmark  
</P>
<P>
	COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Detectives in central Denmark are  
investigating the theft of 195 rare fire-bellied toad tadpoles from 
a pond where they had been put for breeding. Police in Svendborg, 
100 miles southwest of Copenhagen, said today they fear the robbers 
could get a ``considerable price'' for the tadpoles on the black 
market. Nearly extinct in most of Europe, the toads cannot be sold 
legally without special permits. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientists Create `Super Batteries'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new generation of batteries may be on the  
horizon: They last 50 percent longer than today's batteries, thanks 
to a ``super-iron'' component that promises to be easy and 
affordable to manufacture. They're still under development, so 
don't look for them in local stores soon. But researchers at the 
Israel Institute of Technology invented super batteries that could 
run CD players and flashlights -- and say the new batteries also 
could come in the rechargeable forms needed to power camcorders, 
laptop computers, even electric cars. 

</P>
<P>
	Mortgage Rates Hit 8.15 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages soared to 8.15 percent this week, reaching its 
highest rate in more than two years. The average was up from 7.89 
percent last week, according to a weekly survey released today by 
Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. This week's average rate on 
30-year mortgages was the highest since early April 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Power Outage Closes Chicago Board of Trade  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade closed an hour early  
today after a power outage affecting the downtown Loop area 
threatened to expand. The Chicago Board Options Exchange planned to 
halt trading at 2:40 p.m. EDT until they could switch over to 
backup generators, a spokeswoman said. But CBOT chief executive 
officer Thomas R. Donovan made the decision to close the markets at 
2 p.m. after speaking to Commonwealth Edison CEO John Rowe, said 
CBOT spokesman Bret Gallaway. 

</P>
