<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Suspected L.A. Gunman in Custody  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The white supremacist wanted in the shooting of  
five people at a Los Angeles Jewish community center fled to Las 
Vegas in taxis, walked into an FBI office and confessed Wednesday, 
saying he wanted his act to be ``a wake-up call to America to kill 
Jews,'' authorities said. Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., 37, was charged 
by federal prosecutors in the slaying of a postal worker shot 
Tuesday near the community center. California authorities expect to 
charge him in the community center shooting Thursday. At his 
federal court appearance Wednesday, Furrow said little and waived 
extradition to Los Angeles. After the hearing, he was put on a 
helicopter and arrived in Los Angeles 1 1/2 hours later. 

</P>
<P>
	Survivor of Bataan Death March Sues  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A survivor of the Bataan Death March has sued  
a Japanese company, saying he was beaten by employees of Mitsui &AMP; 
Co. Ltd. and forced to work as a slave after being captured during 
World War II. The lawsuit brought by Lester Tenney, 79, of San 
Diego is the first filed under a new California law that allows 
victims of slave labor to sue multinational corporations in state 
courts. ``I want them to apologize. I want them to say to the 
world, 'We're sorry for what we did,''' said Tenney, a retired 
Arizona State University finance professor. Mitsui forced American 
POWs to work in a coal mine considered too unsafe for Japanese 
workers, Tenney said outside the Superior Court building where the 
suit was filed Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Declines Internet Review  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the Federal Communications  
Commission has declined to open a formal review of access to 
high-speed Internet connections, saying it would slow down the 
process of making those services available to consumers. FCC 
Chairman Bill Kennard, in a letter to state and local officials 
that advise the agency, once again defended the FCC's hands-off 
approach to regulating high-speed Internet services, also known as 
broadband, and particularly those offered over cable lines. He said 
by rejecting intervention, the FCC has fostered growth in the 
marketplace with ``impressive results across the country.'' 

</P>
<P>
	One Killed in Salt Lake City Twister  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A rare tornado swept through downtown on  
Wednesday, tossing trucks and trees around and shredding tents set 
up for a convention. At least one person was killed and more than 
100 were injured. ``It couldn't have picked a worse place,'' said 
National Weather Service meteorologist David Hogan. ``The chance of 
it hitting a city right smack where it did today is pretty slim.'' 
Power lines were ripped down, roofs torn off, windows blown out and 
shards of glass were everywhere. Helicopters landed in the streets 
to ferry the injured to hospitals and all major roads leading 
downtown were closed. 

</P>
<P>
	Navajo Nation Sues Tobacco Industry  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Mirroring successful claims made by numerous  
states, the nation's largest Indian tribe sued the tobacco industry 
Wednesday to recover the cost of caring for sick smokers. The 
complaint filed in Navajo court alleges tobacco companies deceived 
Navajo Nation consumers, illegally targeted minors and burdened 
their healthcare system. The claim seeks unspecified damages from 
eight tobacco companies, including Phillip Morris and R.J. 
Reynolds. Twice as many American Indians smoke in comparison to 
other groups, according to the surgeon general. 

</P>
<P>
	Sale of `Mein Kampf' Probed  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Bavarian officials said Wednesday  
they're looking into possible legal steps to stop U.S. Internet 
companies from selling Hitler's ``Mein Kampf,'' which is banned 
along with other Nazi propaganda in Germany. In an interview on 
Hesse state radio in Frankfurt, Bavarian finance ministry spokesman 
Horst Wolff said the western allies gave Bavaria, a southeast 
German state, all rights to ``Mein Kampf'' after World War II. He 
said Bavaria intends to protect those rights. Germany's foreign 
ministry has been asked to check what legal action Bavaria could 
take against U.S. booksellers that offer the book in Germany, Wolff 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately Thursday as  
investor sentiment was buoyed by rises in New York and Chicago. The 
Nikkei Stock Average rose 130.27 points to 17,341.43 in early 
trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
closed up 132.65 points at 10,787.80. 

</P>
