<DOCNO> APW19990812.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 14:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Plans Live Ads for Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is betting that 64 live  
commercials will give its new line of Focus subcompact cars an edgy 
and topical twist that will appeal to teen-age and 20-something 
viewers of MTV and other youth-oriented television programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercials featuring comedian and actress Annabelle  
Gurwitch will begin Sept. 9, during the MTV Video Music Awards 
show, and continue through March, primarily on prime-time network 
programs popular with ``echo-boomers,'' the children of baby 
boomers. There will be simultaneous live promotions on the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ford Focus campaign also will include conventional taped  
commercials, print advertising, billboards and radio ads. 
</P>
<P>
	To generate additional ``buzz'' among young people, Ford will  
loan customized Focus cars to what the automaker describes as ``120 
trendy people'' -- club DJs, concert promoters and such -- in New 
York, Los Angeles, San Francisco, Miami and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 2 automaker did not disclose the cost of the campaign as  
it outlined the plans Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Live commercials were standard fare during television's infancy  
in the 1950s, before recorded programming took over. They still 
surface. The Prodigy online service ran more than 100 live ads in a 
1993-94 campaign, and live contests have become a halftime fixture 
of major sports championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem with live ads is they can go wrong.  
</P>
<P>
	There was the time in 1958 when John Cameron Swayze put a Timex  
watch on a motorboat propeller in a big tank of water and it fell 
off. He couldn't retrieve it to report his famous line: ``It takes 
a licking and keeps on ticking,'' although the watch, still 
running, was later recovered. In another '50s-era commercial, an 
actress couldn't open the refrigerator she was showing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford marketers say the risk of live commercials is a lure to  
reach the youth market. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's precisely why we're doing it,'' said Jan Klug, the  
Ford's marketing communications manager. ``It's all about taking 
risks and living in the moment, which is really what the brand is 
all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 Focus is Ford's latest attempt at a ``world car.'' On  
sale in Europe for about a year, the Focus recently began arriving 
at dealerships in the United States and Canada in advance of its 
formal launch Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The Focus was styled in Ford's ``new edge'' school of design,  
with sharp creases and angles. It stands much taller than most 
small cars, a trend that automakers are adopting as car drivers 
increasingly find themselves in a sea of big sport utility 
vehicles, minivans and pickups that block their view. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford will offer the Focus with several optional packages aimed  
at young drivers' interests. The ``pet package,'' for example, will 
include a dog safety harness, an insulated, tip-resistent water 
bowl and a ``doggie bag'' to pack pet supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The car will be sold alongside the venerable Escort, which ranks  
fifth in U.S. sales. Ford will produce the 2000 Escort in fewer 
variations as a low-budget model and industry analysts expect the 
model to disappear from Ford's lineup at the end of the 2002 model 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The commercials with Gurwitch, who hosts Turner Broadcasting  
System's ``Dinner &AMP; a Movie'' program on cable, will be scripted 
and rehearsed. But Ford hopes to make them topical and 
improvisational enough to appear spontaneous. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to find some bloopers, and I think that's going  
to build a cult following around this,'' said Bruce Rooke, creative 
director at the J. Walter Thompson agency. 
</P>
<P>
	About 30 minutes before each commercial is broadcast, computer  
users can log on a special Web site to watch the crew set up. The 
view will be from a hand-held camera and will include brief 
interviews with cast and crew in a live documentary format. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertising experts said Ford's novel approach could succeed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Younger consumers have built up a tremendous amount of  
skepticism against polished ads,'' said advertising Professor 
Roland Rust at Vanderbilt University. ``This is a way to break out 
of that. It's new, off the wall and risky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marketing consultant Jack Trout of Trout &AMP; Partners said Ford  
needs to make sure the ads get across a message about the car. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want all jokes,'' he said. ``A lot of car  
manufacturers get so cute you don't learn too much about the car. 
You don't want to get so involved in the production values of this 
live, behind-the-scenes stuff that you lose the message.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
