<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Campaign Retracts Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Presidential candidate Bill Bradley is  
questioning Al Gore's commitment to abortion rights, citing a 
statement by a vice presidential aide who now says he was mistaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``I respect a woman's right to choose, and that includes women  
who are poor,'' the former New Jersey senator told supporters 
Wednesday night when asked to outline his differences with Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was referring to a recent story in The Des Moines  
Register about the abortion positions of Gore and Bradley, the sole 
combatants in the 2000 Democratic presidential contest. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Gore spokesman Roger Salazar said the vice  
president has long felt federal money should not be used to pay for 
abortions, except to save the life of the mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``Government should not be involved in those decisions,''  
Salazar told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Informed of Bradley's remark, Salazar said the information he  
gave the newspaper was wrong. He said Gore opposes restrictions on 
abortion funding. ``I gave the wrong answer. I didn't do my 
research,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign has had its share of miscues, including the time  
Gore appeared to take credit for inventing the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Bradley and Gore are courting the votes of female  
Democrats, a majority of whom tell pollsters they oppose abortion 
restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vice president opposes any attempt to restrict Medicaid  
funding for abortions,'' Salazar said Wednesday. ``He has fought to 
guarantee that Medicaid recipients who are victims of rape or 
incest should have access to abortion, in addition to those whose 
lives are endangered. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vice President Gore has fought repeated Republican attempts to  
restrict Medicaid funding and, as president, Gore will continue 
that fight,'' Salazar said. ``If Congress passes a bill to extend 
Medicaid funding for abortions, as president, Gore will sign it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, federal law has prohibited the use of federal funds,  
including Medicaid, to pay for abortions except in cases of rape, 
incest or instances where the mother's life is endangered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
