<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Group Rushing on Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- With several deadlines approaching, Mario  
Lemieux's advisers are rushing to preserve the retired star's 
purchase of the bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins and are considering 
adding more investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux twice failed to meet deadlines set by a federal  
bankruptcy judge to close on the sale, apparently because he does 
not yet have signed agreements from all his investors. An Allegheny 
County commissioner also balked at freeing the Penguins from debt 
owed for Civic Arena improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's aides insist they have raised the $55 million in cash  
needed to complete the purchase, which was approved by U.S. 
Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz on June 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the investors are solid and are ready to close next  
week,'' Lemieux spokesman John Brabender said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Team Lemieux has spent part of this week talking to  
additional investors, creating speculation that more cash must be 
raised. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lemieux advisers say they are merely exploring whether to  
raise additional capital so they can field a competitive team once 
Lemieux takes over. 
</P>
<P>
	That search led the Lemieux group to again talk with Mark Cuban,  
a Pittsburgh native and the Broadcast.com Web site founder who 
originally discussed an investment last spring but could not 
formalize an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban is a lifelong Penguins fan who attended several playoff  
games last season wearing a team jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban, who fears Pittsburgh will lose the Penguins if the  
Lemieux bid fails, is believed to be willing to sink as much as $40 
million into the team. That stake would be worth twice as much as 
Lemieux's own $20 million share and theoretically would make Cuban 
the majority owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``But what any additional investor's role might be and the  
percentage of ownership is so far down the road, it isn't even 
worth discussing,'' Brabender said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Cuban does make such a large investment -- before or after the  
sale -- he would clearly have much more say in the team's 
operations. The operations plan drawn up by Team Lemieux puts 
nearly all of the control in the hands of Lemieux and his advisers, 
which may have led Cuban to fail to join the group initially. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mario needs money and that's what we have,'' said Harry L.  
Manion III, Cuban's lawyer, on Thursday. ``Mark wants to do 
whatever is reasonable to make sure the team is viable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Cuban joins, it is possible that Beverly Hills billionaire  
Ron Burkle may pull out his $20 million stake if and when the sale 
is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're always looking for new investors,'' said Doug Campbell,  
Lemieux's lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	It is believed that Lemieux's group now believes that $55  
million is not enough to buy the team and operate it long term, 
especially at a time when one player -- Jaromir Jagr -- will make 
$10.4 million next season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins ran up $120 million in debt from 1991-98, a period  
when Howard Baldwin and, later, Roger Marino were the owners. 
Marino sank about $40 million into the team over the last two 
years, but recently decided not to invest in the Lemieux group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Penguins have been undercapitalized for eight years,''  
Manion said. 
</P>
<P>
	This week is an especially important one for Lemieux because the  
Penguins' line of credit with the French bank Societe Generale runs 
out Aug. 20. The team is collecting money from season ticket sales, 
but those funds are in an escrow account that the Penguins cannot 
touch. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, training camp begins three weeks from Saturday. Because  
the NHL ceded to the bankruptcy court any rights it had to seize 
the franchise and operate it on its own, it is possible the 
Penguins might go out of business if the sale isn't completed by 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	``The delays in closing have created the real possibility that  
this team is going to fold because it is out of money,'' Manion 
told the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. ``As a result of that, Mark Cuban 
has expressed a willingness to work with Team Lemieux to provide 
them with whatever they need to ensure that the Penguins will 
survive in Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Lemieux aides say an agreement on the Civic Arena  
debt issue may be near. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegheny County Commissioner Bob Cranmer last week objected to  
a deal bartered by city and county negotiators that would have 
freed the Penguins from absorbing any debt for past arena 
improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Cranmer said he doesn't want taxpayers' money to fund debts  
accumulated by the Penguins' prior ownership. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
