<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Markets Close Mostly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed higher Thursday,  
following overnight gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, shares rose 1.23 percent, as the U.S. dollar continued  
its climb against the Japanese yen. The dollar bought 115.68 yen 
late in the afternoon, up 0.98 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and 
also above its late New York level of 115.35 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 211.81  
points to close at 17,422.97. On Wednesday, the average rose 0.05 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were encouraged by Wednesday's trading in New York,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares surged 2.7 percent after five straight  
sessions of losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index rose 341.95 points to 12,779.75. On  
Wednesday, the index had dropped 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors remain concerned, however, over a possible U.S.  
interest rate hike. Hong Kong interest rates usually follow rate 
movements in the United States since the Hong Kong dollar is pegged 
to the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	That was keeping many players out of the market, said Terry  
Cheung of Core Pacific-Yamaichi International (HK) Ltd in Hong 
Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, prices were boosted by news reports of heightened  
U.S. military presence in the region. The Weighted Price Index rose 
101.56 points, or 1.40 percent, to 7,330.24. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were encouraged by reports that the aircraft carrier  
USS Constellation was in Singapore while the USS Kitty Hawk was on 
its way to Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have become tired of China's military threats, so  
when there's good news, the market rebounds,'' said Su Kun-mao of 
Masterlink Securities Corp. in Taipei. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices have fallen sharply in Taipei over the past month  
as China and Taiwan squared off over Taiwan President Lee 
Teng-hui's recent claim of statehood. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares rose 2 percent on a rebound in selected blue  
chips. The JSX Composite Index rose 10.955 points to 565.218. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares surged 5.9 percent on hopes that Malaysia  
will be reinstated into the Morgan Stanley Capital International 
indexes. The Composite Index rose 40.46 points at 728.96. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares rose on a technical recovery after five sessions  
of losses. The PSE Index rose 29.68 points, or 1.4 percent, at 
2,187.57. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares rose as local interest rates fell. The Kospi rose  
5.27 points, or 0.55 percent, at 949.35. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on gains by Singapore Telecommunications.  
The STI rose 25.28 points, or 1.27 percent, to 2,012.81. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on broad gains across most industry groups.  
The All Ordinaries Index rose 9.1 points, or 0.3 percent, to close 
at 2,944.0. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on Wall Street's rally. The NZSE-40  
Capital Index rose 14.52 points, or 0.67 percent, to 2,164.80. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai markets were closed for a holiday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
