<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson To Review Pipelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Congress out of town, Energy Secretary  
Bill Richardson plans to visit Nigeria and the Caspian Sea region 
to review giant pipeline projects, the Energy Department said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson was to depart late Thursday for a three-day visit to  
Nigeria, where he will meet with recently inaugurated Nigerian 
President Olesegun Obasanjo. Their discussions will include energy 
policy, regulatory reforms and removing barriers to trade 
investment, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria is the world's fifth largest supplier of oil to the  
United States and has the world's 10th largest reserves of natural 
gas. A consortium led by Chevron is building a $400 million 
pipeline that will ship Nigerian gas to neighboring Benin, Ghana 
and Togo. 
</P>
<P>
	The pipeline ``is a strong example of (Obasanjo's) commitment to  
economic integration and encouraging investment in the region,'' 
Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	From Nigeria, Richardson will travel to the Caspian Sea areas  
for a week of discussions with private and government officials 
about progress toward building an oil pipeline from the Caspian to 
the Turkish port of Ceyhan. 
</P>
<P>
	The $3.8 billion, 1,400-mile pipeline has been a top priority of  
the Clinton administration, which sees it as the key to 
establishing an east-west transportation route for Caspian oil that 
avoids Russia and Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	But a consortium of 11 oil companies, led by several major U.S.  
producers, have been reluctant to proceed with such a huge capital 
investment because of recent low oil prices and uncertainties over 
Caspian oil reserves. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
