<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 12:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales Push Up July Retail Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans snapped up cars and light trucks  
last month at a brisk clip that helped push overall retail sales up 
by a bigger-than-expected 0.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported Thursday that total retail  
sales, which represent about a third of the nation's economic 
output, rose last month to a seasonally adjusted $248.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were 9.1 percent higher than July of last year.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was Christmas in July,'' said economist Richard Yamarone  
with Argus Research Corp. Record heat in many parts of the country 
drove people into air-conditioned showrooms and stores, where they 
made purchases, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	New car and light trucks sales increased by 2.3 percent in July,  
compared with an 0.8 percent drop in June. The auto industry 
predicts record sales this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the reasons cited by Paul Taylor, chief economist with the  
National Automobile Dealers Association, were strong demand for 
mid-sized luxury sedans and sport utility vehicles; manufacturers' 
rebates; and a strong economy that makes people feel comfortable 
about spending money. 
</P>
<P>
	William Mulholland, a 29-year-old information technology  
specialist from Virginia who bought a new Jeep Wrangler two weeks 
ago, said he did not get a ``great deal'' but could afford the 
convertible model he longed for. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists continue to believe the Federal Reserve will  
raise interest rates again on Aug. 24, to keep the economy from 
overheating and hold inflation under control. The Fed nudged 
interest rates a quarter of a point on June 30, the first rate 
increase in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economists said the retail sales report gives the Fed  
additional ammunition to justify a second increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``Continued solid consumer demand just adds to the belief that  
the Fed is going to raise rates again,'' said economist Joel Naroff 
of Naroff Economic Advisors. 
</P>
<P>
	But others economists took heart in another number in the  
report: Excluding auto sales, retail sales rose just 0.3 percent in 
July, slightly less than many analysts' expectations of a 0.4 
percent rise, and a possible sign that overall retail sales may be 
moderating, said economist David Levy of the Levy Institute 
Forecasting Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets have been worried about the prospects of  
another rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The gain in overall retail sales followed a revised 0.2 percent  
decline in June. Last month, the government estimated retail sales 
actually rose 0.1 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second quarter of this year, consumer spending grew by 4  
percent, compared with 6.7 percent for January-March. 
</P>
<P>
	With unemployment near a three-decade low, growth in wages and  
benefits and a strong stock market, consumers are continuing to 
feel confident. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no stopping the urge to splurge among U.S.  
consumers,'' said First Union's chief economist David Orr. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of durable goods -- items expected to last at least three  
years -- rose 1.6 percent in July, compared with a 0.9 percent drop 
in June. Sales at furniture stores remained flat. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, sales of nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, went up  
0.2 percent in July, down from a 0.4 percent gain in June. At 
gasoline stations, sales rose 1.2 percent in July reflecting a jump 
in gas prices at the time. Gas sales fell by 0.5 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, sales at general merchandise stores, the category  
that includes department stores, increased 1 percent in July, 
compared with a gain of 0.6 percent in June. Sales at food stores 
rose 0.1 percent in July, after having dropped the month before. 
But sales at grocery stores held steady for the second month in a 
row. 
</P>
<P>
	At apparel and accessory shops, sales fell 0.4 percent in July,  
matching the 0.4 percent drop in June. Sales at bar and restaurants 
also fell by 0.4 percent in July, following a 0.2 percent gain in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, most chain stores reported that their retail sales  
topped expectations in July. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Labor Department said that the number  
of Americans filing for unemployment benefits last week rose by 
4,000 to 284,000. But the four-week moving average, which smoothes 
out week-to-week volatility, fell to 288,250, its lowest point in 
over a decade. Economists consider any claims level below 300,000 
to be an indication of an extremely tight labor market. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
