<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bills' Fisher Waiting To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- Bryce Fisher knows how to wait. He also  
knows how to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force graduate and Buffalo rookie is in a familiar  
holding pattern: waiting to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher sat two seasons before getting a shot in high school and  
waited another two years for a starting job at Air Force. 
</P>
<P>
	The top defensive player in the Mountain Division of the Western  
Athletic Conference sat beside the telephone on NFL draft day while 
239 players were chosen ahead of him. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll wait two more years for an opportunity to play for the  
Bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher will return to the Air Force Academy after playing in  
Buffalo's exhibition opener in his native Seattle on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills, who chose Fisher with the second of two picks in the  
seventh round of the draft, are willing to wait for him to meet his 
military obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he has a bright future ahead of him,'' veteran  
defensive end Bruce Smith said in training camp Thursday. ``It's 
unfortunate he has to leave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher's 70 tackles and six sacks as a defensive tackle last  
season helped Air Force to a 12-1 record and lead the WAC in 
scoring defense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills will take one last good look at Fisher at defensive  
end before saying goodbye. ``We're going to give him a nice little 
homecoming,'' said Buffalo's defensive coordinator Ted Cottrell, 
who likes the 6-foot-3, 260-pound player for his smarts and 
quickness but says he has to gain strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher was on his way to anonymity at Washington after  
graduating from Seattle Prep, when Air Force swooped in with an 
offer late in the recruiting season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was ready to take a partial academic scholarship at  
Washington,'' Fisher said. ``I was just going to be a student and 
not play. I was disappointed when nobody came around because I 
thought I was going to get a scholarship out of high school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher helped boost Air Force to its first outright conference  
title and a 45-25 romp over Washington in the Oahu Bowl. The only 
blemish was a one-point loss at TCU. 
</P>
<P>
	The bowl victory was particularly sweet.  
</P>
<P>
	``The University of Washington said I wasn't going to develop  
into a Division I athlete,'' Fisher said. ``They said I was just 
too small. Go figure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even now, Fisher hears some of the same old stuff, that he must  
bulk up and gain strength. 
</P>
<P>
	``To play at this level he'll have to get in the weight room,''  
said Dwight Adams, Buffalo's director of player personnel. ``He 
gets bounced around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Technique counts too, says Smith, and Fisher has that.  
</P>
<P>
	``It depends on how he can handle himself on the field at the  
weight that he's at,'' Smith said. ``If he's 260 pounds and he's 
lower than an offensive tackle who's 300, he's going to win that 
battle. It's just a matter of how much he matures mentally and how 
much he learns about the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher is looking forward to going home. His father, Richard,  
will be watching his son play -- on television. 
</P>
<P>
	``My dad doesn't like the tickets the team gets,'' Fisher said.  
``He'd rather watch it on television. That way when his son makes a 
good play he can see it twice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A transportation officer, Fisher will work as a recruiter and  
assistant coach. He's fortunate that his Air Force commitment is 
only two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I didn't have a chance to play at the professional level,  
it would be five years,'' Fisher said. ``You can't pay for the kind 
of recruiting you can get from a professional athlete. They see 
that as more beneficial than me sitting around pushing pencils.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
