<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israel May Move Early on Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel may agree to implement some provisions  
of the U.S.-brokered Wye agreement early if progress is made in 
current negotiations with the Palestinians, a senior Israeli 
official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Yatom, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's chief political  
adviser, told Israel radio the government would consider faster 
implementation of Wye if talks between the two sides ``mark up any 
achievements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peace negotiators have said they are determined to end the  
deadlock over implementing the Wye land-for-security agreement, 
under which Israel must withdraw from another 11 percent of the 
West Bank in two stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if no agreement is reached, Yatom said, Israel will start  
implementing the agreement on Sept. 1, and the next phase, during 
which Israel will withdraw from 5 percent of the West Bank, will 
begin on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides disagree on the schedule for the withdrawals. The  
Israelis want to spread them into next year and the Palestinians 
say they should be concluded by mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat today denied Israeli media  
reports that he was open to some delays, provided that Israel set 
exact dates for carrying out each of the provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about such a tradeoff, Arafat said: ``No, until now, we  
didn't accept it ... We are accepting what has been mentioned in 
the Wye River agreement and signed at the White House under the 
supervision of President Clinton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians reject Barak's proposal that the last stage of  
withdrawal be integrated with the permanent settlement, which the 
two sides have not yet negotiated. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting Barak's envoy Gilead Sher on Wednesday, the chief  
Palestinian negotiator, Saeb Erekat, said: ``We will not change the 
Wye agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Erekat and Sher are to meet again Sunday. If they reach an  
agreement, there will be a summit meeting between Barak and Arafat, 
Erekat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Wye agreement, Israel undertook the release of  
Palestinian prisoners and pledged to allow the Palestinians to open 
a seaport in Gaza. The Palestinians agreed to take action against 
militant groups, including confiscation of their weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the shooting of a Jewish settler in the West Bank,  
Israeli soldiers today continued to blockade a Palestinian town. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli army's chief of staff, Lieut. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, told  
Israel radio the settler was attacked by a cell of the Islamic 
Hamas group, and the blockade of Arabe, which has 30,000 
inhabitants, will continue until the Palestinian Authority arrests 
its members. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabe was sealed off on Tuesday night after the settler's car  
was ambushed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians are bitterly opposed to Jewish settlement in  
the West Bank and regard the settlements as an obstacle to peace. 
After the signing of the Wye agreement, settlers began seizing hill 
tops with the declared aim of making it more difficult for the 
government to hand over territory to the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli army's judge advocate general has written a report  
that 30 of the 42 small outposts established by the Jewish settlers 
before the Barak government took office are illegal and cannot be 
defended if they are challenged in court, the newspaper Haaretz 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	In most cases, the settlers claim the outposts are within the  
municipal boundaries of existing settlements, but the judge 
advocate general, Brig. Gen. Uri Shoham, wrote that the Supreme 
Court would probably reject this, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The army spokesman had no immediate response to the report.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
