<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 21:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Building-Size Ads in Hollywood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In Hollywood, where getting noticed is  
practically a mantra, advertisers are taking the idea to the 
heights. Like the Silver Tab clothing woman with the two-story-high 
hips, planting her feet near Hollywood and Vine. Or the 150-foot 
bottle of Pepsi offering to quench the thirst of a sweltering 
Highland Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to cut through the visual clutter of billboards,  
advertisers are turning whole sides of buildings into murals. There 
is a booming market for what have been dubbed tall walls or 
supergraphics, which can cost advertisers as much as $60,000 a 
month and cover 5,000 to 20,000 square feet of space. 
</P>
<P>
	Some literally can be seen a mile away.  
</P>
<P>
	``Advertisers love 'em. They're cool,'' said Rick Robinson,  
creative director in Los Angeles for Phoenix-based Outdoor Systems, 
which creates some of the ads. ``It's a giant canvas. It's an urban 
gallery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although nobody keeps accurate figures, Robinson said there  
could be as many as 200 of the ads around the country. Southern 
California, with perhaps 40, is something of a supergraphics 
heartland. 
</P>
<P>
	The area is used to big advertising. After all, the famous  
Hollywood sign originally promoted a housing development. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Sunset Strip, reviews were mixed.  
</P>
<P>
	Mark Brian Smith, 30, of West Hollywood, said he loves the  
creativity of the images but also worries about their sheer size in 
an already ad-saturated culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``When everything is kind of like in your face ... you don't  
have to see it 100 feet tall driving down the Strip,'' he said. 
``There's a limit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that is exactly why the ads flourish here. Unlike vertical  
Eastern cities, the Los Angeles area is mostly low-rise buildings 
that make the murals on the select high-rise buildings stand out. 
Also, the car culture means advertisers must pitch to a moving 
target. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll see the ad from 200 feet away in your little bubble of  
glass and steel,'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The building-sized ad trend started about four or five years ago  
on the Sunset Strip, a glitzy area just outside Los Angeles 
boundaries that already was jammed with ads and giant billboards 
advertising movies, records and chic clothing. A growth plan 
legalized the 10-story ads, Robinson said, and when advertisers saw 
the result they ``went crazy for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New technology contributed. Lightweight, fire-resistant vinyl  
materials can be used as giant ``peel and stick'' signs or, as a 
mesh, can be placed over windows and still allow office workers to 
see out. Old-fashioned painting can take two weeks; the new 
materials can reduce that to a week or even a day, said Sean 
Robertson, Outdoor Systems' creative director in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the tall walls are much more expensive than standard  
billboards, they are cheaper than TV commercials or magazine ads 
and potentially can reach millions of people. 
</P>
<P>
	Which is exactly why the city wants to regulate them. The city  
has sign and billboard laws, but no existing ordinance to limit 
where the monster ads are placed, how long they can remain or how 
they are constructed. Some ads, with limited text, have been 
approved as cultural murals. 
</P>
<P>
	A Supergraphics Task Force is developing regulations and will  
present its recommendations to the City Council by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Without careful planning, the giant ads can become a ``visual  
blight'' and a traffic problem, said Daniel Hinerfeld, a deputy for 
City Councilman Mike Feuer. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're huge,'' he said. ``These things are designed to  
distract people. That's their whole purpose ... and there are 
certain places in the city where you don't want to be distracting 
hundreds and thousands of motorists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such problems could get worse as next generation technology  
makes giant moving ads affordable, Hinerfeld speculated. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a 10-story banner for ``Armageddon,'' showing a  
flaming meteorite flying through the side of a glass office 
building, was pulled after a few days when officials said it backed 
up rush hour traffic on nearby freeways for miles. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ads also can be business-enhancing landmarks.  
</P>
<P>
	In Hollywood, a 108-by-198-foot vinyl mural for Apple Computers  
features John Lennon and Yoko Ono, holding flowers and peering 
benevolently over a nearby Mobil gas station. 
</P>
<P>
	The sign is good for business, said Sam Farraji, the station's  
general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tourists come ... and they take photographs, like it's  
something famous,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
