<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Increases Border Patrols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan wants to avoid a further  
escalation of tensions with India and has increased border patrols 
with F-16 fighters to prevent Indian intrusions, Pakistan's foreign 
minister said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-line aircraft were deployed at Pakistan's southern  
border with India, Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said, as the 
nuclear rivals remained on high alert after two days of air clashes 
in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions soared Tuesday when an Indian jet downed a Pakistani  
naval patrol plane, and Pakistan responded the following day, 
firing a missile at an Indian fighter it says entered Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The downing of the Pakistani aircraft was an example of India's  
``trigger happy attitude, which is not conducive to peace and 
stability in this area,'' Aziz said in an exclusive interview with 
The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that Pakistan ``would certainly not like to initiate  
any (incidents) and we hope India won't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to a U.S. appeal Wednesday for both sides to exercise  
restraint, India today accused Pakistan of violating a 1991 
agreement that bans combat aircraft from coming within six miles of 
the border. 
</P>
<P>
	India said the Pakistani naval plane flew into its territory and  
returned to Pakistan after it was hit. Most of the wreckage was 
found in Pakistan, but parts of the plane were scattered along the 
border, India said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan accused India of stealing pieces of the wreckage. ``It  
was such a cruel attempt to prove the Indian viewpoint,'' said 
Aziz, who argued the plane was just inside Pakistan when it was 
attacked. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing whether the Pakistani aircraft violated Indian  
airspace during its flight, Aziz said, ``Suppose it did. ... How 
can a propeller plane like this threaten a jet?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aziz has accused India of violating the 1991 agreement but did  
not specifically say whether Pakistani aircraft were abiding by it. 
He did not discuss the U.S. statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Indian capital of New Delhi, Foreign Office spokesman  
Raminder Jassal told reporters that India wanted peace talks with 
Pakistan but the alleged air incursion was ``not conducive to the 
normalization of relations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aziz agreed that both sides want peace, but he said that a  
lasting peace can only come once both sides have solved their 
dispute over Kashmir, a Himalayan territory claimed by India and 
Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The two nations came to the brink of war this summer during an  
11-week confrontation in the mountains of Kashmir. India said 
Pakistani troops had infiltrated its territory, but Pakistan denied 
that its soldiers were involved and said all the fighters were 
local Islamic militants. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan have fought three wars since they gained  
independence from Britain in 1947; two of the conflicts were over 
Kashmir. This week's aerial clash was the first since they went to 
war in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kashmir today, suspected separatist guerrillas triggered a  
mine, killing two Indian commandos and injuring three others, 
Indian military officials said. The blast was near northern 
Bandipora, 40 miles north of Srinagar, Kashmir's summer capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan claims that Indian forces fighting the Islamic  
insurgents in Kashmir routinely abuse civilians in the 
overwhelmingly Muslim territory, two-thirds of which is controlled 
by India. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pakistan cannot be a silent spectator to such brutal  
repression,'' Sartaj said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee has acknowledged what  
he has called isolated incidents of rights violations by security 
forces in Kashmir, but he has said his government was committed to 
rooting out abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan frequently has called for international mediation of  
the Kashmir dispute, which India has rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, Pakistan's top civilian and military leaders  
gathered for a memorial service for the 16 servicemen killed when 
the naval plane was shot down. 
</P>
<P>
	Offering brief prayers, Pakistani leaders stood before the  
coffins, covered with flowers and draped in green and white 
Pakistani flags. 
</P>
<P>
	At the service, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif warned India that  
``Pakistan is capable of safeguarding itself. We will do everything 
to safeguard our sovereignty and national interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the downing of the aircraft ``further complicated the  
matter of normalization'' between Pakistan and India. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
