<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portland WNBA Team Hires Native </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Portland's WNBA expansion team has  
essentially acquired its first player for the 2000 season, naming 
Oregon native Katy Steding to a front-office job Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Steding, who will be community liaison for the Portland team,  
said she expects the job will lead to a spot on the roster when the 
WNBA's fourth season begins next summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first logical step in that progression of  
things,'' the former ABL player said. 
</P>
<P>
	The still-unnammed Portland team, along with the other new teams  
in Miami, Seattle and Indianapolis, won't officially get new 
players until the league holds its expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Steding, 31, still can play. The 6-foot forward averaged 8.4  
points and 3.9 rebounds a game during two seasons with the Portland 
Power of the now-defunct ABL. 
</P>
<P>
	Steding, who grew up in Lake Oswego, was a three-time All-Pac-10  
selection at Stanford. She was named to the all-Final Four team in 
1990 when the Cardinal won the national title. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the first player assigned to Portland when the ABL  
opened for business in 1996, and she remained with the team until 
the league shut down last December. 
</P>
<P>
	Steding decided against trying to catch on with any of the 12  
teams in the WNBA this season. Instead she stayed in Portland to 
run youth basketball camps. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
