<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Games Win Battle With Band </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Sydney Olympic organizers won the first  
stage of a court battle with an American-based band company in the 
Supreme Court on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice John Bryson refused an injunction sought by World  
Projects Corp. which would have prevented SOCOG from holding the 
opening ceremony of next year's Games without the involvement of 
the international band. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not prepared to vary the arrangements I made for an  
expedited hearing on Monday,'' Justice Bryson said. 
</P>
<P>
	WPC president Bill Lutt is negotiating with SOCOG to have an  
international marching band in the Games opening ceremony involving 
student musicians from 20 nations. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president Michael Knight says the organizers have offered  
an extra $520,000 to put together the band. He said WPC was asking 
for $780,000. 
</P>
<P>
	If the matter is not settled out of court, the sides are due  
back in the Supreme Court on Monday. WPC is suing SOCOG and Knight, 
seeking damages or the reinstatement of the foreign musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG remains keen to have the matter resolved in the next  
couple days so further expensive legal action can be averted. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG vetoed ceremonies director Ric Birch's plan for a  
2,000-member band, including 1,300 American and 200 Japanese 
students, in June because of a public backlash against the lack of 
Australians. 
</P>
<P>
	WPC and SOCOG then agreed on a band including members from six  
continents, with about 900 Australians making up the largest 
component. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
