<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 10:04:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia OKs Genocide Trials Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Ignoring U.N. criticism, parliament  
voted overwhelmingly Thursday to allow genocide and war crimes 
trials to be delayed by up to three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Assembly had passed a main article of the proposed  
law Wednesday. It passed the entire package Thursday by a vote of 
86-8. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law lets courts extend a six-month pretrial detention  
limit by up to three years for charges of genocide, war crimes or 
crimes against humanity. It will likely delay the trial of the 
architects of the Khmer Rouge genocide between 1975 to 1979, when 
some 1.7 million Cambodians died. 
</P>
<P>
	A letter from the office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Human  
Rights circulated through parliament during the debate Thursday, 
adding fuel to fierce argument by the opposition that the bill was 
deeply flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the letter to parliament speaker and FUNCINPEC party leader  
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, U.N. human rights official Rosemary 
McCreery warned that the new law violates several international 
legal conventions. 
</P>
<P>
	She also said it is ``legally unsound to extend pretrial  
detention periods for crimes which do not yet exist in Cambodia 
law.'' Cambodia's legislature has never ratified the 1948 
international convention against genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law was conceived by Prime Minister Hun Sen's Cambodian  
People's Party as a Sept. 9 trial deadline for Khmer Rouge general 
Ta Mok approached. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Ta Mok and one other senior Khmer Rouge figure are in  
custody. Several others are living freely in Cambodia under deals 
reached with the government that ended the civil war they fought 
after losing power. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Hun Sen has said he intends to bring Khmer Rouge leaders  
to justice, critics fear he will influence the trial process to 
ensure no current national leaders are embarrassed by past 
associations with the Khmer Rouge. Hun Sen's Cambodian People's 
Party is led by former Khmer Rouge who escaped bloody purges and 
returned to topple their former comrades in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law comes as Cambodia and the United Nations are  
negotiating the formation of a joint genocide tribunal for Khmer 
Rouge leaders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
