<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DC To Enforce Juvenile Curfew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Beginning the day after Labor Day, anyone 16  
or younger will have to be off the streets of the nation's capital 
by 11 p.m. on most nights -- midnight on Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the curfew will curb crime. Opponents say it  
violates constitutional rights and discriminates against minors. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia lifted an  
injunction against the law, clearing the way for the city to put it 
into effect, Executive Assistant Police Chief Terrance Gainer said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers who pick up curfew violators will take them home, not  
to a detention center, Gainer said. That way, if there is a problem 
at home, the officer can muster other city services to try to help 
the family, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several members of the D.C. Council have said the curfew,  
combined with recreational, work and other programs for young 
people, can protect juveniles from becoming either victims or 
perpetrators of crime. 
</P>
<P>
	But the American Civil Liberties Union has opposed the law in  
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a free country,'' said Arthur B. Spitzer, legal  
director for the ACLU in the nation's capital. ``We don't put 
people under house arrest for their own protection.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
