<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Lady Wants Westchester NY Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGEMONT, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton has settled on  
Westchester County as her future home, her spokeswoman says, and 
the first lady checked out a house near Scarsdale that carries a 
$1.7 million price tag and annual taxes of $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton rolled up in a limousine Wednesday morning to see  
the house in Edgemont, a hamlet in the Town of Greenburgh. Secret 
Service agents had other potential customers wait outside as the 
first lady took a tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, would not say whether  
she made a bid on the house. But she said President Clinton and the 
first lady ``have narrowed their search to Westchester. They're 
actively considering several options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who is considering a run for the U.S. Senate in  
New York, must move to the state by Election Day 2000 to be 
eligible. Some say she should move as soon as possible to deflate 
any carpetbagging charge. 
</P>
<P>
	A woman who answered the door at the Edgemont house Wednesday  
night and said she was a friend of the owners said in French that 
Mrs. Clinton ``doesn't like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If that's true -- rather than just bargaining strategy -- it may  
be a relief to other agents. One who was kept outside the house 
while Mrs. Clinton inspected it said her own client had been ready 
to make an offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were negotiating and obviously we're dead in the water.  
Would you want to bid against the first lady?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The house is a turn-of-the-century colonial on three acres, a  
large spread for southern Westchester. It has 12 rooms, including 
seven bedrooms and two dining rooms, plus 6 1/2 bathrooms. It is white 
with black shutters and a pillared portico. There is an elevator 
inside and a barn outside. 
</P>
<P>
	President and Mrs. Clinton earned $504,109 last year, including  
more than $275,000 in capital gains and business income, and paid 
$89,951 in federal taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the president's salary and Mrs. Clinton's income  
from a book she wrote entitled ``It Takes A Village'', The first 
family received $53,462 in short-term capital gains and $146,856 in 
long-term capital gains -- both from the Pell Rudman Trust Co., 
which holds a private trust for the Clintons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
