<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Crops Projected Despite Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While farmers' fields parch in the East, much  
of America's heartland has had sufficient rain and that means 
bumper crops and little help for depressed commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's soybean crop is shaping up to be the biggest on  
record, and the corn harvest would be the third largest, the 
Agriculture Department reported Wednesday. Big crops of cotton and 
rice are expected across the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of tighter world supplies and improved exports, USDA  
expects a modest increase in prices for some commodities -- 20 cents 
a bushel for soybeans and 5 cents a bushel for corn -- from what was 
forecast a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher prices could save the government as much as $1  
billion in crop subsidies, but many farmers still wouldn't recover 
their cost of production, so the rosier projections are unlikely to 
slow a drive in Congress to pass a major bailout of the 
agricultural economy. The Senate last week approved a $7.4 billion 
package of farm assistance; the House has yet to act. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a time where there is nowhere to hide,'' said Doug  
Wilson, who grows corn and soybeans in north-central Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought is most acute in the Northeast -- the entire states  
of New Jersey, Connecticut and West Virginia as well as most of 
Maryland -- have been declared disaster areas. But Ohio and parts of 
Indiana and Illinois have been short of water, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson's soybeans are healthy, but his corn was hurt by July's  
heat wave, he said. ``What scared me the most was where it looks 
like we are, a mediocre crop with a mediocre to poor price,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest impact of the drought could be on dairy farmers.  
Milk prices are expected to rise as much as 50 cents per hundred 
pounds because of strong demand for cheese and declining milk 
production in the parched Northeast. Cows make less milk when it's 
hot, and pastures are drying up from the lack of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern peach crops have been largely untouched by the drought,  
although the fruit is smaller than normal. Pennsylvania is expected 
to produce 68 million pounds, 3 million more than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA's production forecasts reflect field conditions Aug. 1.  
Even as they were released Wednesday, rain fell from the northern 
Plains across the Midwest, which could increase crop yields and 
depress prices, especially for late-developing soybeans. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we're sitting here, the soybean plants out back have gained  
another bushel or two,'' said Joe Victor, a commodity analyst with 
Allendale Inc. of McHenry, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The soybean harvest is forecast at 2.9 billion bushels, up 4  
percent from last year. Corn production is expected to dip 2 
percent this year to 9.6 billion bushels, but that is 4 percent 
above 1997's harvest. Most corn and soybeans are used for animal 
feed. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA said it expected the average price of corn to range from  
$1.70 to $2.10 this year. Soybean prices should average $4.10 to 
$4.90 per bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton production is expected to be up by a third from last year  
when there was a severe drought across the South. 
</P>
<P>
	The rice crop is expected to be a record 21 billion pounds, up  
12 percent from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat production is down 9 percent, as many farmers switched to  
other crops they thought would be more lucrative this year. But 
world wheat stocks are rising because of a big crop in China this 
year, so USDA doesn't expect prices to increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see much of anything that would change our net farm  
income,'' said USDA economist Larry Salathe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
