<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sega of America President Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The president of Sega of America Inc. has  
been replaced just as the video-game maker is about to launch a 
high-powered console designed to revive flagging sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Stolar's departure, effective immediately, was announced  
Wednesday, three weeks before launch of the Dreamcast game system. 
Sega did not say whether Stolar, who has been a marketing force for 
Dreamcast, was fired or resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Toshiro Kezuka is replacing him, becoming vice chairman and  
chief operating officer. Kezuka joined Sega of America this year as 
deputy chairman. He was head of domestic sales and distribution for 
Sega Enterprises Ltd., the Japanese parent company and previously 
served as president at Honda France. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Svensson, editor in chief of MCV, a video-game trade  
magazine, said the timing of the change in leadership was 
``extremely bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dreamcast has been gaining support over the past six  
months and presales are stronger than Sega expected,'' he said. 
``But this is going to confuse people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kezuka predicted that the change will not affect the Dreamcast  
launch, scheduled for 15,000 stores on Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-powered, Internet-ready Dreamcast system is Sega's  
comeback attempt. Sega posted $375 million in losses for the fiscal 
year ending in March and is forecasting a loss of $99 million for 
the next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sega says 200,000 consoles have already been pre-sold in the  
United States, the strongest launch ever for a video game console. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival consoles Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64 do not offer  
built-in Internet connections, which allow players in compete 
against one another online. The Dreamcast console is also faster 
and more powerful. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
