<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Agent Wants Others Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA, Switzerland (AP) -- The agent of disgraced track star Ben  
Johnson has some tough words for sprinter Ato Boldon and others who 
have criticized his client. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview from Toronto, Morris Chrobotek told The  
Associated Press on Thursday that he believes 99.9 percent of track 
athletes are taking banned drugs, but said Johnson was no longer 
among them. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrobotek's comments came after Boldon said earlier Thursday  
that the sport was at its lowest point since Johnson tested 
positive for steroids at the 1988 Seoul Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would welcome him to run against Ben Johnson and to be  
tested against Ben and all the rest to be tested and let's see 
who's clean,'' Chrobotek said. ``If they think that athletics is 
going through the worst since Ben Johnson, after the testing it 
will be much lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was banned for life in 1993 after a second positive drug  
test, but is appealing the decision and hopes to be reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrobotek said athletes should prove they are clean before they  
point the finger at anyone else, and said British sprinter Linford 
Christie, who recently tested positive for a banned drug, was one 
of the biggest critics of Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	He also attacked Boldon for pulling out of the world  
championships in Spain because of a hamstring injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``He says that Ben Johnson didn't do any justice to athletics.  
What kind of justice is he doing by dropping out of the worlds for 
no apparent reason?'' Chrobotek said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
