<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Aug. 12, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Tornado Destroys Millions in Property  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The mayor's office estimated that  
yesterday's tornado destroyed about $150 million in property, 
excluding damage to the Outdoor Retailers Market, a trade show held 
twice annually in Salt Lake City. One person was killed and dozens 
were injured. Fifteen people remained hospitalized, two in critical 
condition and four in serious condition. Officials were still 
assessing the destruction, but at least 121 homes were damaged, 
with 34 left uninhabitable. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes for Cleaner Fuel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Aiming to reduce U.S. oil demand and protect  
the environment, President Clinton today created an interagency 
council to promote technologies that turn trees, plants and even 
animal waste into energy. Clinton cast the initiative as both a 
security issue and a crucial stroke against global warming. ``If we 
can make the raw material of tomorrow's economy living, renewable 
resources instead of fossil fuels, which pollute the atmosphere and 
warm the planet, the future of our children and our grandchildren, 
the likelihood that there will be more prosperity and peace -- all 
that will be far greater,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuke Spy Case Discipline Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recommending disciplinary action today against  
a senior official and two other employees of the Los Alamos nuclear 
laboratory because of failures in the China espionage 
investigation, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, cited a ``total 
breakdown in the system.'' While the internal investigation also 
cited ``systemic problems in the Energy Department's management of 
counterintelligence matters,'' no action was taken against any 
department headquarters officials. Nor were any former senior DOE 
officials singled out by name for criticism. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspected L.A. Shooter Is Charged  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A prosecutor said today that a white  
supremacist charged with shooting five people at a Los Angeles 
Jewish community center admitted he also killed a Filipino-American 
postal worker because he was not white and worked for the federal 
government. The alleged confession by Buford O. Furrow Jr. came 
after Los Angeles County prosecutors charged him with murder and 
five counts of attempted murder -- all hate crimes. Federal 
prosecutors already had charged Furrow in the postman's slaying. 

</P>
