<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hunter Still Conscious, but Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter remained  
conscious and in critical condition Thursday, four days after the 
Hall of Famer pitcher fell and hit his head on concrete steps at 
his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter, 53, suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease since last fall,  
was under treatment in the intensive care unit of Pitt County 
Memorial Hospital. Spokesman Doug Boyd said Hunter's condition was 
unchanged from Wednesday, when he awakened after lapsing into 
unconsciousness for a day. 
</P>
<P>
	His long-range prognosis was unclear, said a doctor treating  
Hunter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still in our monitoring phase, and it's too early to  
predict Mr. Hunter's needs'' in terms of future treatment, said Dr. 
Paul Cunningham. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital officials said Wednesday that Hunter suffered brain  
bruising. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter retired to his farm in Hertford from the New York Yankees  
in 1979 after a 15-year pitching career during which he won the Cy 
Young Award and collected five World Series rings. He was 
baseball's first multimillion-dollar player. 
</P>
<P>
	A diabetic who requires three injections daily, Hunter was  
diagnosed last year with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis -- a gradual, 
irreversible deterioration of the muscles. He likely will require 
rehabilitation because he already was weakened by ALS, Cunningham 
said Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
