<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Appeals for Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton urged the nation on Thursday  
to embrace ``our common humanity'' in the aftermath of the latest 
shootings linked to ethnic hatred. He appealed to Congress to pass 
``common-sense'' laws tightening gun control and banning hate 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said hatred apparently was a motive in the  
shootings at a Jewish community center in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Acts of hate against individuals are acts of hate against our  
values and our entire nation. So let us all speak clearly and with 
one voice: Our nation will not stand for such acts,'' Clinton said 
in remarks videotaped for a ``safe schools'' conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the president took advantage of a previously scheduled  
meeting at the White House with about 30 American Jewish leaders to 
discuss his hopes for hate crimes legislation. During the nearly 
two-hour meeting, Clinton advocated that minority groups unite 
behind the push for hate crimes legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive director of the Anti-Defamation League said the  
leaders pressed Clinton to use his presidency to push for broader 
anti-hate efforts. Abraham Foxman also referred to a statement an 
FBI source said was made by Buford O. Furrow Jr., who has been 
charged in the Los Angeles shootings, 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Furrow talked about, `This is a wake-up call to kill  
Jews,' perhaps this is a wake-up call to unite America,'' Abraham 
Foxman said. ``There needs to be attention given to it beyond the 
crisis, beyond the tragedy. What happens is it passes from the 
pages of the newspaper and the hate continues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rabbi Eric Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew  
Congregations, said Clinton ``expressed his disbelief and his grave 
concern'' over the Los Angeles shootings and spoke passionately 
about the need for tighter gun restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said the members of Congress just don't seem to care, and  
the American people need to send a message that we're going to hold 
them responsible for their actions,'' Yoffie said. ``He said we're 
not talking about disturbed teen-agers here, but the re-emergence 
of militia groups and militant groups and extremist groups, and 
this really required some strong action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yoffie said the leaders also urged Clinton to step up  
surveillance ``and even infiltration'' of known hate groups, and 
Clinton promised ``to look into this personally ... and he will do 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said Clinton agreed that more  
should be done, but that care also must be taken to avoid violating 
constitutional freedoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton addressed the subject in at least three appearances  
during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the shootings presented ``another compelling argument,  
in my judgment, for this country to renew its commitment to our 
common community, our common humanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It now appears that they were motivated by racial and ethnic  
hatred,'' Clinton said. He noted they followed a July shooting 
spree in Illinois and Indiana in which two people were killed and 
nine wounded -- all of them black, Jewish or Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	``Acts of hate must strengthen our resolve and deepen our  
determination that Americans will come together and stand together 
and work together against violence, intolerance and hatred,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Days before the latest shootings, Clinton had reiterated his  
appeal to Congress to pass a hate crimes bill that would make it 
easier for the Justice Department to investigate and prosecute such 
offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved the measure last month and added it to a  
still pending spending bill. The House Judiciary Committee held a 
hearing on the measure last week. Critics say a federal law is 
unnecessary since states prosecute hate crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
