<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Child Death Rate Doubles in 90s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The death rate for small children has  
doubled this decade across most of Iraq, according to a U.N. survey 
released Thursday that's likely to inflame debate over continuing 
sanctions against Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said the survey -- the  
first of child deaths in Iraq since shortly after the 1991 Persian 
Gulf War -- reveals an ongoing humanitarian emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF officials say a host of factors have influenced the child  
mortality rate, including the sanctions, two wars, a collapsed 
economy and Baghdad's own response. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey will undoubtedly add to the ongoing U.N. Security  
Council debate over whether to ease the economic sanctions -- 
regardless of whether Iraq has fully complied with U.N. demands to 
eliminate its weapons of mass destruction. The sanctions were 
imposed after Baghdad's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not calling for a lifting of sanctions as such, because  
we cannot. That is not in our jurisdiction,'' Bellamy said in an 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF recognizes that sanctions are used by the international  
community to promote peace and security, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when they're used they need to be implemented in a way to  
avoid serious human impact,'' especially on vulnerable children, 
she added. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, which opposes lifting sanctions until Iraq is  
disarmed, blamed President Saddam Hussein for the malnutrition and 
deaths of Iraqi children in government-controlled areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is that if Saddam Hussein would not continue  
to hoard medicines and capabilities to assist the children of Iraq, 
they wouldn't have this problem,'' said State Department spokesman 
James P. Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to help ordinary Iraqis cope with the sanctions,  
the United Nations has allowed Iraq to sell limited amounts of oil 
to buy food, medicine, and other humanitarian aid since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. runs the oil-for-food program in northern Iraq. But it  
relies on the Iraqi government to implement the program in the 
government-controlled central and southern regions, home to 85 
percent of the country's population. 
</P>
<P>
	The UNICEF findings back a trend that U.N. officials identified  
in an April report: U.N. humanitarian relief operations were more 
effective in the areas outside Saddam's control. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey found that in government-controlled central and  
southern Iraq, there were 131 deaths of children under 5 per 1,000 
live births from 1994 to 1999. That's compared to 56 deaths per 
1,000 live births from 1984 to 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The new, higher rate puts child mortality in most of Iraq on par  
with rates in Haiti and Pakistan, UNICEF said. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, in the autonomous northern region, the mortality  
rate of children under 5 fell to 72 deaths per 1,000 live births 
from 1994-1999 from 80 deaths per 1,000 live births from 1984-89. 
</P>
<P>
	Bellamy noted that Iraq's child mortality rate was on the  
decline in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF urged the international community to provide more money  
for humanitarian efforts in Iraq and called on the U.N. committee 
overseeing sanctions and the Iraqi government to give priority to 
directly improving the well-being of children. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey also said the Iraqi government should implement  
nutrition programs, adopt a national policy promoting 
breast-feeding and replace the baby formula in the current food 
rations with additional food for nursing mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	UNICEF surveyed nearly 24,000 randomly selected households in  
south and central Iraq between February and May, in cooperation 
with the Iraqi government, and 16,000 households in the north, in 
cooperation with local authorities. The margin of error was less 
than 5 percentage points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
