<HEADLINE> Defendant in Starr Case Loses Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former defendant in one of Independent  
Counsel Kenneth Starr's prosecutions has lost a legal battle to 
have the government pay her attorneys' fees. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton rejected the arguments of  
Julie Hiatt Steele that Starr's case was ``vexatious, frivolous and 
in bad faith.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an Aug. 3 ruling, Hilton said the government won't have to  
pay costs and attorneys fees for Ms. Steele because ``the evidence 
was sufficient for a reasonable trier of fact to find the defendant 
guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury on May 7 deadlocked 9-3 in favor of convicting  
Ms. Steele on charges that she obstructed Starr's investigation of 
allegations by Kathleen Willey that President Clinton made an 
unwanted sexual advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr decided not to retry Ms. Steele, who denied Mrs. Willey's  
assertion that she confided the alleged advance to her friend hours 
after it happened. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
