<HEADLINE> La Russa Hopes To Return in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- It's starting to look like Tony La Russa might  
return to the St. Louis Cardinals next season, after all. 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa was offered a two-year contract extension in spring  
training but hasn't accepted the deal. That has led to speculation 
that he might leave for another job after this season. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, La Russa told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch that  
barring a huge slide in the final seven weeks, he would like to 
stay in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa thinks Cardinals' owners should have the right to  
change their minds about keeping him. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't prove yourself in spring training,'' he said. ``You  
have to have the confidence of your owners at the end of the each 
season. It's something you have to earn. I've believed that for 20 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa, 54, ranks 11th on baseball's career list for victories  
(1,622) by a manager and leads active managers. His Oakland 
Athletics won three pennants and a World Series title from 1988-90. 
He led the Cardinals to the NL Central title in 1996, his first 
season in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Cardinals have not made the playoffs since, despite the  
heroics of home run king Mark McGwire. The Cardinals are 58-58 this 
year, 11 games behind first-place Houston. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
