estimated the company would earn 39 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
 *Lands End, up 3 13/16 at 46    	
</P>
<P>
	The catalog retailer earned 14 cents per share in the second  
quarter, compared to break-even results in the second quarter of 
1998. Lands End attributed the growth to soaring online sales and 
cost-cutting efforts. 

</P>
<P>
 *Veba AG, down 2 at 59 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Veba's first-half earnings more than tripled, driven by the sale  
of telecommunications assets, but its core utility operations were 
hit by competition. Sales and earnings in the power-generation 
division slipped 5 percent after the electricity market was opened 
in January. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Red Hat Inc., up 20 9/16 at 72 5/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The operating software company continued to rise in its second  
day of trading. Red Hat more than tripled its offering price 
Wednesday, bucking a recent trend of weak initial public offerings. 

</P>
<P>
 *Alliance Gaming Corp., up 1 3/8 at 6    	
</P>
<P>
	Alliance earned 16 cents per share in its recently ended fourth  
quarter, while analysts had anticipated earnings of 1 cent per 
share. Alliance, a maker of slot machines, said results in the 
coming quarter should be roughly in line with the fourth-quarter 
results. 

</P>
<P>
 *Nextel Communications Inc., up 5 1/8 at 53 1/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The Reston, Va., wireless communications company received  
approval from the U.S. Justice Department and the Federal 
Communications Commission for its plan to obtain licenses from 
NextWave Personal Communications Inc. NextWave filed for bankruptcy 
protection from creditors in June 1998. 

</P>
<P>
 *Iridium World Communications Ltd., down 1 11/16 at 4 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The satellite-phone venture, which is backed by Motorola Inc.,  
said it is in default on an $800 million syndicated loan, and on a 
second syndicated loan for an additional $750 million. 



  	   	
