<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Crops Predicted Despite Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers will harvest bin-busting crops of  
corn, soybeans, rice and other crops despite the drought and heat 
that have plagued parts of the country this summer, the Agriculture 
Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA said it expects a modest increase in prices for some  
commodities -- 20 cents a bushel for soybeans and 5 cents a bushel 
for corn -- because of tightening world supplies or rising exports. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher prices could save the government as much as $1  
billion in crop subsidies, but many farmers still wouldn't recover 
their cost of production, so the rosier projections are unlikely to 
slow a drive in Congress to pass a major bailout of the 
agricultural economy. The Senate last week approved a $7.4 billion 
package of farm assistance; the House has yet to act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see much of anything that would change our net farm  
income,'' said USDA economist Larry Salathe. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest impact of the drought could be on dairy farmers.  
Milk prices are expected to rise as much as 50 cents per hundred 
pounds because of strong demand for cheese and declining production 
in the parched Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean production is forecast at a record high 2.9 billion  
bushels, up 4 percent from last year, although the drought has 
ruined crops from Ohio through the mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the nation's heartland has received plenty of rain this  
summer and a Midwest heat wave eased in time to spare most crops. 
</P>
<P>
	The corn harvest is expected to be the third largest on record  
at 9.6 billion bushels. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA said it expected the average price of corn to range from  
$1.70 to $2.10 this year. Soybean prices should average $4.10 to 
$4.90 per bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton production is expected to be up by a third from last year  
when there was a severe drought across the South. 
</P>
<P>
	The rice crop is expected to be a record 21 billion pounds, up  
12 percent from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat production is down 9 percent, as many farmers switched to  
other crops they thought would be more lucrative this year. But 
world wheat stocks are rising because of a big crop in China this 
year, so USDA doesn't expect prices to increase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 18:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers' Jones Hurt on Punt Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- San Diego receiver Charlie Jones dislocated  
his left hip Thursday night when he was tackled near the sideline 
at the end of a punt return and fell hard on his side. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury occurred early in the second quarter of an exhibition  
game against the San Francisco 49ers. The game was delayed several 
minutes while medical personnel attended to Jones, who was starting 
his fourth season in San Diego after being drafted in the fourth 
round out of Fresno State in 1996. He had 46 catches for 699 yards 
and three touchdowns last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones fielded the punt, started up the middle and cut to the  
right sideline, where he was met by the 49ers' Zack Bronson and 
ridden down at San Francisco's 45. 
</P>
<P>
	An inflatable cast was placed around his damaged leg and he was  
lifted onto a gurney. Jones, visibly in pain, clutched his head 
with both hands as the gurney was moved off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	An inflatable cast was placed around his damaged leg and he was  
lifted onto a gurney. Jones was in visible pain, clutching his head 
with both hands as the gurney was moved off the field. 
  	   	
</P>
