<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Freeman Signs 1-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers have signed All-Pro  
wide receiver Antonio Freeman to a one-year tender offer, the team 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal means Freeman will be able to report to training camp  
and play for the Packers while the team and Freeman's agent, Joel 
Segal, continue to work on a long-term contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Antonio wants to be here,'' coach Ray Rhodes said. ``I'm just  
happy they worked something out. We're going to take our time 
getting him ready to play and go from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman will be in camp Friday as the Packers prepare for their  
Saturday preseason opener against the New York Jets. Freeman won't 
be ready to play in that game but could see preseason action, 
Rhodes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased and excited to have Antonio in training camp,''  
general manager Ron Wolf said in a statement. ``Meanwhile, the 
parties will continue to negotiate on a long-term contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman held out through the first two weeks of training camp  
while reportedly seeking a contract worth more than $6 million 
annually, which could have made him the game's highest-paid 
receiver. Talks reportedly stalled over the amount of Freeman's 
signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, he also signed to play for the Packers' tender  
offer of $1.153 million. Freeman then set career-highs with 84 
catches for 14 touchdowns and a league-best 1,424 yards despite 
suffering a broken jaw late in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Green Bay placed its franchise player tag on Freeman after the  
season, meaning the team had the right to match any offer made to 
him. Added urgency was placed on the negotiations last week when 
Robert Brooks, the Packers' starting flanker last season, announced 
his retirement after seven injury-plagued seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want him in here before training camp,'' Rhodes said. ``It  
gives him enough time to get him ready for the season opener.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers have been auditioning wide receivers to play  
alongside Freeman. Veterans Bill Schroeder, Derrick Mayes and Corey 
Bradford are all expected to make the team, while Jahine Arnold and 
rookie Donald Driver are among the leading candidates for a final 
roster spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Green Bay players have not criticized Freeman for his holdout,  
and last month Rhodes said he understood and supported his wide 
receiver's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Herman Moore received a five-year contract extension from the  
Lions last month that pays him $5.6 million annually. Freeman's 
contract is expected to include a signing bonus of more than $10 
million. Moore got a signing bonus between $8 million and $9 
million from Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman, who said he only wanted to play in Green Bay, never  
seemed comfortable with his holdout. He visited his teammates 
during minicamps during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's my family, man,'' he said at a June minicamp. ``I'm not  
going to turn my back on my teammates.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
