</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to thank Michael for trusting me to get this thing  
done,'' Holmgren said. ``We had kind of an agreement, call it a 
handshake, that we were going to work very, very hard to make this 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 270-pound Sinclair, a sixth-round draft choice  
from Eastern New Mexico, is a four-year starter who plays on 
Seattle's defensive line with tackles Cortez Kennedy and Sam Adams 
and end Phillip Daniels. 
</P>
<P>
	He ranks third on the Seahawks' career-sacks list with 60 1/2  
behind Jacob Green's 116 and Jeff Bryant's 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair hopes to become a better player with his contract  
worries now behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you come to training camp and have it on the back of your  
mind, sometimes it's a load,'' he said. ``I'm glad that we got it 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair phoned Holmgren from Hawaii, where he was preparing for  
last season's Pro Bowl, when he heard reports that the Seahawks 
were going to trade him to Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `No, that's not going to happen,''' Sinclair said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair said his contract extension will allow him to finish  
his career in Seattle. He had a chance to leave the Seahawks as a 
restricted free agent, but chose to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything that Michael Sinclair is all about is in Seattle,''  
he said. ``There's no other team that I want to play for. This is 
where I started. Seattle is home for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sinclair said his contract was important for him -- and for the  
Seahawks, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what's missing in professional sports is loyalty,'' he  
said. ``So I think this definitely sends a message to the players 
to what kind of organization that the Seahawks have become, 
definitely to the young players. If you go out and play, you will 
be taken care of. That's a huge message.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
