<DOCNO> APW19990812.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 13:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vanguard Founder To Retire in Dec. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John C. Bogle, the public face behind the  
nation's second-largest family of U.S. mutual funds, will resign by 
year's end from the board of Vanguard Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard said today that its founder must step down under a  
policy that requires board members to resign in December of the 
year in which they reach 70. Bogle turned 70 in May. 
</P>
<P>
	But a report Thursday in The Wall Street Journal said there was  
a dispute over whether the retirement policy was mandatory and said 
there were policy differences between Bogle and his successor, John 
Brennan. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogle did not immediately return a call seeking comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard dismissed the contention that controversy surrounds  
Bogle's retirement. Vanguard spokesman John Demming said Vanguard 
has a ``long-standing policy'' established by the board regarding 
the retirement policies of its board members. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Vanguard now appears to have a public relations problem  
on its hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogle's name is synonymous with Vanguard. He founded the company  
in 1975 and now is senior chairman of a firm that manages nearly 
$500 billion in investments. 
</P>
<P>
	But many longtime Vanguard watchers believe Bogle's role with  
the company will change little whether he remains on the board or 
retires. For several years, Bogle's role has been primarily as an 
educator and lecturer on issues affecting the mutual fund industry. 
He is a staunch supporter of low-cost funds and long-term 
investing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vanguard spokesman said it's unknown whether the board may  
ask Bogle to remain in some unofficial capacity or as a consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Merriman, a Seattle-based money manager who also edits an  
online mutual fund guide, said Bogle's retirement won't have much 
impact unless Vanguard changes its policies and starts raising its 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The public's perception of the company is likely to change  
somewhat because Bogle is so closely identified with Vanguard, 
``but I don't think that matters,'' Merriman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutual fund analysts said the transition between leaders is  
expected to be smooth because Vanguard's day-to-day operations have 
been run by Brennan, a protege of Bogle and the chief executive 
since 1996. Brennan, 45, was named chairman in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Transition isn't the issue because Brennan has been running  
the show their for several years,'' said Dan Wiener, editor of The 
Independent Adviser for Vanguard Investors, a newsletter. ``The 
real loss is that of the Vanguard icon. Bogle is the last of the 
mutual fund icons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wiener said Bogle ``personified Vanguard.''  
</P>
<P>
	``Many of Vanguard's investors trust Bogle to look out for their  
best interests because he's the guy who started the whole thing,'' 
Wiener said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, on the other hand, while well known in the mutual fund  
world, is relatively unknown among consumers, according to Wiener. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported that Bogle had differences with  
Brennan over Brennan's support for an expansion into the discount 
brokerage business. Bogle has complained that the discount business 
encourages a gambling mentality among investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanguard, based in Valley Forge, Pa., was formed in the wake of  
differences between the senior managers of Wellington Management, 
an investment firm founded in 1928. Vanguard is widely regarded as 
the fastest growing mutual fund company, with assets second only to 
Fidelity Investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press uses Vanguard to manage its retirement  
investment plans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
