<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Airline Orders Airbus Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Taiwan's China Airlines has agreed to buy seven  
Airbus A340-300 long-range planes and has taken options on five 
more jets in a deal worth up to $1.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with state-controlled China Airlines includes options  
for an eighth A340-300 as well as four twin engine A330-300, the 
European consortium Airbus Industrie said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Airbus sale comes after Seattle-based Boeing Co. lost out on  
a deal to sell China Airlines a dozen Boeing 777 aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, however, Boeing signed a $2.5 billion order to  
supply the airline with 13 747-400 cargo jets. 
</P>
<P>
	China Airlines signed a letter of intent with Boeing in 1995 to  
acquire the 777 passenger jets, but switched the order to Airbus in 
another letter of intent signed in June, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is locked in a fierce competition with Airbus over orders  
for A340s and the slightly smaller 777s. 
</P>
<P>
	China Airlines said at a news conference Thursday in Taipei that  
the A340s will be delivered between 2001 and 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The China Airlines deal took on political overtones this month  
when accusations surfaced that Taiwan was snubbing Boeing in the 
passenger plane sale to retaliate against U.S. government policies 
seen as unfavorable to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	China Airlines officials have denied the accusations.  
</P>
<P>
	Chiang Hung-yi, China Airlines chairman, said Thursday that  
Airbus was selected because the standardized design of the A340 and 
A330 will help reduce maintenance and pilot training costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline can put the four-engine A340s into service right  
away, Chiang said, noting that it would take the carrier about a 
year to gain approval for using the two-engine Boeing 777s on its 
transoceanic routes. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus Industrie, which groups France's Aerospatiale, British  
Aerospace, Spain's Construcciones Aeronauticas and DaimlerChrysler 
Aerospace, is Boeing's main competitor. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
