<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Chip Stocks Rise / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today, although a  
disappointing auction of Treasury bonds sapped some of the market's 
strength in the push to extend Wednesday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 48.13 at 10,835.93, adding to Wednesday's 132.65-point gain. The 
Dow rose as much as 113 points earlier in today's session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index  
was up 3.98 at 1,305.91, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 
0.45 at 2,564.53. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Wednesday, bargain-hunters went shopping for stocks  
that have been pounded down from the record heights reached in 
mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	But worries about higher interest rates, which have held the  
market down, continued to rattle investors today. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell following the Treasury's afternoon auction of $10  
billion in 30-year bonds. Traders said demand for the bonds fell 
short of expectations, driving the price down and the yield up. 
Yields on 30-year bonds hit 6.27 percent in the open market, a 
level unseen since October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise in bond yields this summer has hurt stocks in two ways.  
For one thing, rising interest rates raise the cost of business 
borrowing, cutting into profitability. In addition, with rates 
above 6 percent, bonds are presenting an attractive alternative to 
investing in volatile stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest evidence that the Federal Reserve may raise rates in  
an effort to stave off inflation came from a stronger-than-expected 
report on retail sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that retail sales rose 0.7  
percent in July, boosted by a big gain in automotive sales. Strong 
consumer spending could suggest to the Fed that the booming economy 
is overheating, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	But without automobiles and seasonal goods like air  
conditioners, the retail sales increase was quite modest, noted 
Robert G. Smith, chief executive officer of Smith Affiliated 
Capital in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really kind of a bland number,'' he said. ``But there's  
a lot of anxiety right now about every new domestic economic 
indicator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts believe the Fed will be more interested in the  
producer price index, due for release on Friday. That index is a 
measure of inflation pressures at the wholesale level, or before 
reaching consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Caterpillar rose 2 11/16 to 61 15/16, helping buoy the Dow after  
Goldman Sachs added the company to its list of recommended stocks. 
An analyst said Caterpillar should benefit from the improving 
global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online extended its gains from the previous session,  
rising 1 5/8 to 94. AOL shares rose 7 3/8 on Wednesday after company 
executives held an upbeat conference call with analysts and major 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	But most major computer makers slipped today after a Merrill  
Lynch analyst said in a report that a trend toward low-priced 
computers could eventually cut into profits. Hewlett Packard 
plunged 5 3/8 to 104, the biggest decliner in the Dow. 
</P>
<P>
	Renewed rumors that Merrill Lynch will seek a partner in the  
financial-services industry pushed its shares up 4 1/8 to 71 1/8. 
Brokerage officials declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues barely outnumbered decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 599.78 million shares at late 
afternoon, slightly behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.82 at 613.04, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.83 at 779.20. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.37 to 428.56.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
