<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workers' Families Sue in Van Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- The families of 13 tomato pickers killed  
when their van slammed into a tractor-trailer filed a lawsuit 
Thursday accusing the truck driver and two trucking companies of 
negligence. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Highway Patrol is still investigating the  
accident and has not assigned blame. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed in Fresno County Superior Court, names truck  
driver Adrian Erazo; Raul H. Oropeza, sole proprietor of Oropeza 
Trucking; and Hoffman Bros. Harvesting Inc. of Tracy, Calif., owner 
of the trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	It does not name the owner of the van.  
</P>
<P>
	The families' attorney, Robert Perez, and Fernando F. Chavez,  
the oldest son of United Farm Workers founder Cesar Chavez, hope to 
use the lawsuit to address farmworker transportation problems in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``This accident has brought the issue to the conscience of the  
community,'' Perez said. 
</P>
<P>
	A message left for Hoffman Bros. was not immediately returned.  
There is no listing for Oropeza Trucking in the Fresno area. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
