<DOCNO> APW19990812.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talking Fish Boosts Sega's New Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The mysterious fish with a human face pops onto the  
TV monitor, swims up lazily and asks for your birthday. Answer late 
July, and it drawls: ``Leo, huh? The type who likes to play 
leader?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The verbose smart aleck is ``Seaman,'' the new Japanese hit  
video game for the Sega Enterprises Dreamcast machine arriving at 
U.S. stores Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo manufacturer is counting on solid Dreamcast sales in  
the United States to hold its ground against Sony Computer 
Entertainment and Nintendo Co. in the heated competition over the 
world game-machine market. 
</P>
<P>
	Popular games are key to boosting machine sales. And ``Seaman''  
appears to be the hit Sega has been desperately waiting for. It has 
already sold out in some stores in Japan with about 120,000 copies 
moved since July 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mistake to assume that it's enough to have a great  
machine. That's only the beginning,'' said Toshiyuki Fukuda, 
manager for game store Laox. ``Without hit games, the Dreamcast is 
just a box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up to now, the scant repertoire of Dreamcast games was hurting  
sales. Titles for the machine total about 60 in Japan, compared to 
more than 2,000 for Sony's Playstation. There will be at least 16 
games by the time Dreamcast goes on sale in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seaman'' has a voice recognition system that allows the fish  
to understand -- at least most of the time -- up to 100 words at a 
time, depending on the question it asks. The game creates the 
illusion of an offbeat dialogue with an unorthodox pet. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many games, there is no real plot in ``Seaman,'' which is  
also being planned for the U.S. market. The player takes care of 
the fish for 25 days until it evolves into a frog. 
</P>
<P>
	The debut this month of another popular title, fighting game  
``Soul Calibur'' which highlights the dazzling, smooth visuals of 
Dreamcast, also has helped machine sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Before ``Seaman,'' Dreamcast sales in Japan had not been  
promising, hitting only about a million since going on sale last 
November, about 10 percent below company forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't stack up well against the competitors. Some 16  
million Playstations have been sold in Japan and more than 21 
million in North America. Nintendo 64 sales total 4 million in 
Japan, and 14 million in North America. Advance U.S. orders for the 
Dreamcast total 200,000 so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Sega has not released any recent figures. But the new games are  
pushing up machine sales, said Yoshitsugu Sato, manager of 
Hakuhinkan Toy Park in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	More powerful than the Playstation or Nintendo 64, the Dreamcast  
also comes with a modem, allowing users to play games with other 
Dreamcast players on the Internet, as well as download game 
characters and other information. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the Playstation nor the Nintendo offers Internet access,  
although the rivals are expected to catch up soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the splash ``Seaman'' is making, Sega needs a string of  
hot-selling games if it hopes to stay in the home game-machine 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is in dire trouble. Sega posted $375 million in  
losses for the fiscal year ending in March and is forecasting a 
loss of $99 million for the next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid the gamemakers's financial woes, former vice-chairman and  
chief operating officer Bernard Stolar left Sega of America Inc. to 
be replaced by Toshiro Kezuka, the company said Wednesday. No 
reason was given for the personnel change. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors appear skeptical about a Sega comeback.  
</P>
<P>
	Sega share prices at one point plunged about 45 percent on the  
Tokyo Stock Exchange from the beginning of this year, to as low as 
$12 in June, though they have since recovered somewhat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's life or death for Sega,'' said Mitsuko Morita, an analyst  
with Morgan Stanley Japan in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Sega slashed Dreamcast prices in Japan 35 percent, to  
$170, to lure buyers. The Dreamcast will sell at $199 in the United 
States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
