<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Cup Uproar Overshadows PGA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- As David Duval left the 15th tee at Medinah  
Country Club, he crossed paths with Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw, 
who was on his way to the adjacent 12th tee box. 
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw saw that Duval was 3-under for the first round of the  
PGA Championship, smiled and waved two fingers. Duval grinned and 
nodded back. 
</P>
<P>
	Between the ropes, one would never know the Ryder Cup  
controversy is still alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Off the course is another story.  
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw opened fresh wounds on the eve of the PGA, saying he  
was disappointed by the viewpoints of a couple of players on 
revenue generated by the Ryder Cup. Those players later were 
identified as Duval, Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara and Phil Mickelson. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval and Woods played their rounds, then stood their ground.  
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like a pretty large corporate outing,'' Duval said  
when asked if he still thought the matches were nothing more than 
an exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods also refused to back down.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's an exhibition. It always has been,'' Woods added. ``It's  
not meant to be played as a war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It sure sounds like a Civil War.  
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw apologized for keeping the topic in the headlines, but  
not for the way he feels about the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm from a different generation where the Ryder Cup means a  
lot to us,'' Crenshaw said. ``I'm upset people aren't jumping over 
the moon about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most players would jump over the moon to make the team that  
tries to regain the cup next month. But four top players already on 
the team have talked more about how the money is divided than how 
they can win the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	That may say something about team unity with a little more than  
a month before the United States plays Europe at The Country Club 
at Brookline outside of Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want 12 committed players going to Boston,'' Crenshaw said  
after shooting a 77 in the opening round of the PGA. ``I want our 
players to be unified. To be honest, I haven't seen that in the 
last four teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't get commitment from them two days after a team meeting  
in which everyone left saying they were on the same page. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought there were 13 people in agreement,'' Duval said.  
``Apparently, there's only 12.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval said he watched Crenshaw's finger-pointing on television  
Wednesday night, never thinking that his captain might be referring 
to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he was,'' Duval said.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara didn't talk to Crenshaw. He said he only got a message  
from the captain on his phone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was a dead issue,'' O'Meara said. ``I'm  
disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was equally disappointed in how he has been portrayed.  
</P>
<P>
	``The media keeps saying it's pay-for-play, and I don't see it  
that way,'' O'Meara said. ``I take offense to the fact that 
somebody might call me unpatriotic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval spent much of his time after the opening round of the PGA  
defending his position on the issue. No, he never asked for money 
to play. Yes, it is an honor to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	And yes, he strongly believes a portion of the money should go  
to charities designated by the players. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods issued a stronger statement, especially when asked why he  
keeps referring to the Ryder Cup as an exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is there a winner's check?'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Further evidence that there is division among the Americans  
comes from Davis Love III, who lashed out at the media for 
continuing to bring it up. And from Tom Lehman, who has said he 
would pay to play in the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman likely would give a handsome sum to have the firestorm  
put out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should all be ashamed of ourselves in a way,'' Lehman said.  
``This is an issue that could have been resolved quietly behind 
closed doors, and it wasn't. We don't need this.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
