<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women Plans To Swim Tennessee River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRING CITY, Tenn. (AP) -- After swimming 125 miles of the  
Tennessee River, Mimi Hughes has a unique understanding of what 
happens to the herbicides, pesticides and litter of our lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything ends up in the river. Everything,'' the 43-year-old  
mother of four said Wednesday on arriving at Watts Bar Dam, marking 
the end of the first leg of her five-year quest to swim the 
652-mile Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Swimming to promote a cleaner river, Hughes set out Aug. 2 at  
the Tennessee headwaters above Knoxville. She plans to swim another 
125 miles each August until she reaches the river's end at Paducah, 
Ky., in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, who swam from Alcatraz to San Francisco in 1996 and from  
Alaska to Russia across the Bering Strait in 1997, at first feared 
a Tennessee River swim because of pollution, then made it her 
mission. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more I thought about it, the more I realized it was an  
athletic endeavor with a lot of purpose behind it,'' said Hughes, 
who lives in Taft and is a developmental reading teacher and 
adjunct professor at Motlow State Community College in Tullahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tennessee Valley Authority, which manages the river system  
and provides teams to help communities solve pollution problems, 
provided Hughes with an escort boat and accommodations. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, Hughes said she found the shoreline gorgeous,  
but the water tainted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can turn my head to take a breath and the beauty is so  
spectacular,'' she said. ``And then I put my face into the water 
and I might smell a septic tank that is not working correctly or 
some fertilizer that is runoff from the green, green grass that I 
just passed in someone's yard.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
