<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BET Plans Web Site Aimed at Blacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hoping to draw more black Americans to the  
Internet, cable network operator BET Holdings announced an 
ambitious new Web site today with backing from four major media and 
technology companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The new site, to be called BET.com, is the latest effort to  
narrow the ``digital divide'' between whites and minority groups, 
who have lagged behind others in their access to and usage of the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	BET Holdings, which operates the Black Entertainment Television  
network and three other cable channels as well as several 
magazines, intends to make the new site a leading online 
destination for blacks, a ``portal'' that Web surfers can use as 
their home base to jump to other Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture will receive $35 million in backing from its four  
partners, including Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	There are three major media players involved: USA Networks Inc.,  
the American arm of Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., and AT&AMP;T Corp.'s 
Liberty Digital, the online media company run by cable magnate John 
Malone. Liberty owns a minority stake in BET. 
</P>
<P>
	BET's chairman and founder, Robert Johnson, called the new  
venture a ``unique social and economic opportunity for African 
Americans.'' He said he believed it was the largest amount ever 
spent to launch a product aimed specifically at blacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The failure of any community to avail itself of the resources  
of the Internet will limit its ability to succeed in the new 
millennium,'' Johnson said. ``BET is bringing its media channels, 
content and brand resources together with those of our partners to 
create an online destination that will educate, enrich, empower and 
entertain African Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new site, which will launch in November, will offer a  
variety of news, entertainment, finance and free messaging 
services. It will also sell items aimed at black buyers including 
clothes, books, music and gifts. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
