<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles' Asher Dislocates Ankle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jamie Asher, the Philadelphia Eagles'  
starting tight end, dislocated his left ankle Thursday night on the 
sixth play of the team's first exhibition game against Baltimore 
and is out indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	Asher was signed to a $4.1 million, three-year contract to  
solidify the second-most important position in coach Andy Reid's 
new offense. His injury is a huge blow to the team's rebuilding 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Asher was blocking on the Eagles' sixth offensive play when he  
went down clutching his leg. Teammates gathered around as he was 
loaded onto a cart. He raised his helmet to a cheering crowd, a 
look of pain on his face, as he was driven off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, coaching his first game Thursday night, has preached that  
his West Coast offense cannot function without a pass-catching 
tight end. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Eagles had five tight ends who caught only 33  
passes for 287 yards. Two of them, Jason Dunn and Kaseem Sinceno, 
finished the season on injured reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles have four other tight ends on the roster: Chris  
Fontenot, Jed Weaver, Andrew Jordan and Sinceno. 
</P>
<P>
	Asher caught 28 passes for 294 yards in nine games for the  
Washington Redskins. He started seven games and was leading the 
team in receptions before a loose piece of cartilage in his knee 
gave him problems. Eventually, surgery was required. 
</P>
<P>
	Several months earlier, Asher had a graft performed to increase  
the amount of cartilage in his knee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
