<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ken Harvey Retires From Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Four-time Pro Bowl linebacker Ken Harvey of  
the Washington Redskins retired Thursday after 11 seasons, unable 
to come back from an injury to his right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's come to a point in my life where my mind's there, but my  
body can't go as much as I want it to,'' said Harvey, 34, who was 
under contract through the 2002 season. ``When that time came, it 
was time for me to make this decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know your body, and when it comes to a point where you  
wake up and your knees are sore -- it's time to say goodbye. Even 
though someone else might think you look good, you just know it 
doesn't feel like it used to feel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey was a starter in three of the four Pro Bowls he played in  
from 1994-97. The 12th overall pick by the Arizona Cardinals in the 
1988 draft, he came to Washington as a free agent in the spring of 
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	That autumn, he became the first Redskin to lead the NFC in  
sacks with 13.5 and only the fourth linebacker in NFL history to 
lead the conference in sacks. The mark set a club record for most 
sacks in a season by a linebacker, eclipsing Monte Coleman's record 
of 10.5 set in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you put together character, athletic ability, heart and  
willingness to compete no matter what the circumstance, Ken Harvey 
is the best that I've been around,'' Redskins coach Norv Turner 
said. ``It's easy to say that; He's done some things here that no 
one will ever appreciate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be missed dearly by me and by his teammates. But  
he's going out on his own terms. He's doing what he believes it 
right. And I'm happy that he's able to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harvey echoed that sentiment.  
</P>
<P>
	``I have no regrets,'' he said. ``I would rather walk away  
knowing that I couldn't give to the team than to be on the team 
just faking it. My whole thing has always been to contribute 
something to the team, and I wouldn't want to be a player who just 
hung on to make it to the playoffs.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
