<HEADLINE> Pippen Wants Trade to L.A. Lakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Scott Pippen wants the Houston Rockets to trade  
him to the Los Angeles Lakers so he can be reunited with his former 
coach Phil Jackson, and the forward's agent says the team is 
looking into the request. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue of the Lakers has been talked about,'' Sexton told  
the Houston Chronicle. ``There have been discussions with the two 
clubs. They told us that the Rockets have some distance between the 
offer and what the Rockets would be willing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Citing an unidentified source, the newspaper reported that  
Pippen told Rockets official Robert Barr to attempt to trade him to 
the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Barr resigned Wednesday and would not comment about discussions  
with players. The source, however, said that Barr's departure as 
vice president of basktball affairs would intensify Pippen's 
interest in leaving the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston television station KRIV also reported that Pippen wants  
to be a Laker. The station cited sources close to Pippen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockets reportedly have turned down the Lakers' offer of  
forwards Glen Rice and Robert Horry for Pippen. There would have to 
be additional adjustments made to the offer to offset the 
$14,795,000 that Pippen counts against the salary cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, who was not available for comment, won six championships  
playing for Jackson with the Chicago Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	This past season was the forward's first in Houston. He has four  
seasons remaining on his contract with the Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He and Phil Jackson have an extremely close relationship from  
11 years working together day in and day out,'' Sexton said. 
``Scottie is an attractive piece of the puzzle for a lot of teams, 
but it probably would not be an issue if Phil Jackson was not 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not anything against the Rockets or any coaches with the  
Rockets' staff. It's just about the very close and unusual 
relationship with Phil Jackson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said he and Pippen have discussed  
the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scottie and I talked about a lot of things and I listened to  
him and asked for his ideas,'' he said. ``I don't want to get into 
what exactly we said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sexton said Tomjanovich had assured Pippen the Rockets would  
move to a more up-tempo style that better suits the perennial 
All-Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Pippen, acquired in a sign-and-trade agreement with the Bulls in  
January, averaged 14.5 points per game this past season, his lowest 
since his rookie year, and he made a career-low 43.2 percent of his 
shots. 
</P>
<P>
	He also averaged 6.5 rebounds and 5.9 assists and was named to  
the NBA All-Defensive first team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be lying if I told you Scottie was not extremely  
frustrated playing in that system last season,'' Sexton said. ``I 
don't think he could make it another year like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``But they did say they would play a more up-tempo game with  
more movement and motion, running up and down the floor. Now, you 
have one of the best players in the game throwing in entry 
passes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
