<HEADLINE> Vikings Return High-Scoring Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings return the  
highest-scoring offense in NFL history, with the exception of 
injured third receiver Jake Reed, and the New York Giants are 
hurting at cornerback. 
</P>
<P>
	That combination could prove explosive Friday night at the  
Metrodome when both teams begin their exhibition schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	After Vikings starting quarterback Randall Cunningham puts in  
his work, he'll give way to backup Jeff George, intent on 
resurrecting his career, then rookie Daunte Culpepper, the 
franchise's future, and finally Todd Bouman, who had a good season 
in NFL Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defensively, they will be a challenge,'' said Giants coach Jim  
Fassel, who will miss the game because he will be visiting his 
ailing mother in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a little nicked up at the corner and a little nicked up  
here and there. This is a team that set a scoring record last year. 
I want to see us play solid defensively and hold them down if we 
can and not give up big plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants don't have their top cornerbacks to counter the  
Vikings, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Sehorn, who sat out last year with a knee injury and  
watched the Giants go from NFC East champs to 8-8, is out with a 
torn hamstring and Conrad Hamilton hurt an ankle in a scrimmage 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to come out as a defense on fire,'' said Jeremy  
Lincoln, who will start at corner with Phillippi Sparks. ``We're in 
front of a national audience (ESPN) and Dennis Green will try to 
put the ball up a little bit. We know this team likes to light up 
the scoreboard. Even when they weren't great, when I played against 
them in Chicago, they didn't run that much. They'd just air it, 
lights out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Green said the starters won't play more than a couple series and  
that all his quarterbacks will get equal playing time. He's eager 
to see his backups, especially Culpepper. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anybody that has watched practice likes him a lot. I  
said a long time ago I thought he was the best player in the draft. 
He'll have a chance to show exactly how good he is in the next four 
preseason games before he takes his role of waiting to play,'' 
Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very smart player. He's probably on the field working  
right now because he's always the last guy to leave the field. He's 
very athletic. He throws a good deep ball that's easy to catch. He 
can run the ball a la Randall Cunningham and he brings a lot of 
enthusiasm and talent to the ball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Culpepper, the record-setting quarterback from Central Florida,  
said he didn't know what to expect Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I don't know. I've never played in an NFL game yet. I'm  
pretty sure it's going to be loud, it's going to be crazy and it's 
going to be pretty intense,'' he said. ``That's what I'm looking 
for. That's why I play the game. I thrive on those kinds of 
situations. I want to be in that type of environment.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
