<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Won't Help Cotton Prices / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- The lingering heat wave killing cotton crops  
in the South won't be enough to help raise cotton prices for 
growers in the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Lavis, executive vice president of the Arizona Cotton  
Growers Association, said even with the Southern woes, prices will 
remain low because of a global cotton glut. 
</P>
<P>
	China, in particular, is producing an abundance of the fiber,  
keeping prices down, and 90 percent of Arizona's crop goes to Asian 
buyers. Cotton is selling for 51 cents a pound or 52 cents a pound, 
significantly off its peak of 85 cents a pound earlier this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still too early to tell how strong the Arizona crop will  
be, growers said, because it won't be harvested until at least next 
month. The harvest usually continues from September to January. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers in the East have been hammered by the heat wave because  
it has been accompanied by a lack of rain, but Arizona farmers are 
far less dependent on rain because of irrigation systems across the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Arizona growers are worried that too much rain has fallen  
lately, making temperatures too cool and conditions too humid. 
Prolonged wetness can make cotton rot. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather has been kind of crazy. We really need the warmth  
during the day and the coolness in the evening to produce good 
cotton,'' said Kevin Rogers of the Rogers Brothers Partnership, a 
family farming operation with 1,000 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETER, Minn. (AP) -- Fish and trees are becoming viable  
alternatives for some Minnesota farmers who are tired of trying to 
make corn and soybeans profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10 members of the Minnesota House Agriculture Policy  
Committee heard testimony this week on how African Tilapia fish and 
poplar trees were helping some farmers out of an agriculture slump. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an opportunity to further diversify,'' said Richard Hagen  
of Olivia, who spoke on behalf of the MinAqua Fisheries Cooperative 
in Renville County. 
</P>
<P>
	Tilapia fish operations use the heated wastewater of a sugar  
beet processing plant to warm the pools where the tropical perch 
are produced, Hagen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, about 1.5 million pounds of the fish raised in  
Minnesota are sold live and unprocessed. 
</P>
<P>
	And with about 24 million pounds of fish imported into the  
United States annually, Hagen said Minnesota can make its mark in 
Tilapia production and reduce the need for the United States to 
import the fish. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, John Krantz, a forestry official with the Department  
of Natural Resources, said Minnesota farmers can help meet paper 
and wood production needs by growing hybrid poplar trees. 
</P>
<P>
	With aspen becoming an increasingly popular source of wood  
sheets used in housing construction, Krantz said the state's 5.3 
million acres of the tree will be exhausted in 45 to 50 years. 
Poplar trees, with shorter harvest times, could fill the void, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But program development coordinator Debbie Letosky, of the  
Minnesota Agro-Forestry Cooperative, acknowledged that some people 
may be hesitant to get into poplar farming because it takes about 
10 to 12 years to see potential profits. She said the Legislature 
could make tree farming more attractive by providing financial 
incentives. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
