<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diet Drug Maker Said Misled Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- With a Barbie doll as a prop, a  
lawyer accused one of the makers of the fen-phen diet drug 
combination of pushing an unattainable ideal of thinness on 
millions of Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is, most women don't look like that,'' Esther  
Berezofsky said Wednesday at the beginning of the first 
class-action lawsuit over the use of fen-phen to go to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sad thing is that many people desperately try and in many  
ways that is what (American Home Products) preyed upon,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs' lawyers said American Home marketed its half of the  
weight-loss cocktail to doctors so that millions of Americans would 
take it to lose a few pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Peter Bleakley said the company only  
recommended the Pondimin and Redux pills for the obese. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were not designed or promoted ... to make people like  
this,'' Bleakley told jurors, picking up the Barbie doll. 
</P>
<P>
	Madison-based American Home -- which made fenfluramine and a  
chemical lookalike marketed under the brand names Redux and 
Pondimin -- faces more than 4,000 lawsuits nationwide by people who 
say they suffer heart and lung problems because of the pills. 
</P>
<P>
	This lawsuit is different because it seeks medical checkups  
rather than financial damages for illnesses already suffered. 
American Home could be forced to pay more than $1 billion over the 
next decade to 94,000 healthy people who took the pills for at 
least three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not here for money. We're here for monitoring,''  
Berezofsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 6 million Americans took either fenfluramine, which was  
sold under the brand name Pondimin, or the lookalike, 
dexfenfluramine, sold under the name Redux, to lose weight. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products removed the drug from the market shortly  
after learning of the risk of heart-valve disease in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The other half of fen-phen, phentermine, was never associated  
with that damage when taken alone and is still on the market. Both 
drugs make the brain trick the stomach into feeling full. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers representing three New Jersey women who lead the lawsuit  
said the company knew years before the drug was taken off the 
market that it was linked to heart valve disease and pulmonary 
hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Saul Weiss produced e-mails between employees at  
American Home's Wyeth-Ayerst subsidiary in Pennsylvania that 
discussed changing a label that stated that four people using the 
drug had developed pulmonary hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1995, the company knew of 180 such cases, Weiss said.  
</P>
<P>
	However, Bleakley cited a study that said long-term users of  
Pondimin and Redux had a 1-in-20,000 chance of developing pulmonary 
hypertension. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the patients had as much chance of being struck and  
killed by lightning, and said the people suing in this lawsuit were 
even less at risk, because most only took the drug for a few 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the Food and Drug Administration knew for years of  
several cases of pulmonary hypertension in people taking the diet 
pills, but let the drug remain on the market. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
