<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks soared Thursday as insurance and  
technology shares made strong gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Insurance index gained 2.7 percent on a round of solid  
results. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dutch-based Aegon rose 2.40 euros to 79.30 euros, helping  
Amsterdam's AEX index to close up 2.1 percent to 553.31. First-half 
results were better than expected, and the company also said it 
will buy the British life insurance operations of Guardian Royal 
Exchange from Sun Life and Provincial Holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance companies are heavily invested in bonds, so if  
European government bonds have peaked, after rising an average one 
percentage point this year, insurance companies will benefit, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the sector, Sun Life shares rose 22.5 pence to  
452.75 pence in London, after the company reported a 32 percent 
gain in their first-half operating profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology shares were also among the best performers, following  
gains in New York on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among European bourses, London's FTSE 100 index of blue-chip  
shares rallied 2.3 percent to 6,153.30, with mining group Billiton 
soaring 13 percent on speculation that Anglo American may be 
preparing a bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies rallied 5.78  
points, or 2.0 percent, to close at 299.69, the highest since Aug. 
3, when it closed at 300.70. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 6.71 points at 
312.54. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index rose 89.05 points to 
3640.44, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed up 80.17 points at 
3589.49. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 2.1 percent to 5,127.43, as  
chemical group Bayer rose 2.10 euros to 43.10 euros, after 
announcing a more optimistic full-year outlook than before. 
France's CAC-40 index of most actively traded stocks closed up 
96.71 points, or 2.3 percent, at 4,365.66. The Swiss Market Index 
closed up 1.8 percent at 6,806.10. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
