<DOCNO> APW19990812.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 08:19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Japan OKs New Wiretapping Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Parliament today gave Japanese police new powers to  
use wiretaps against organized crime, overcoming a grab bag of 
opposition stalling tactics, one of which had lawmakers walking 
very slowly to cast their ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	The 142-99 vote in the upper house followed the powerful lower  
house's approval of the anti-crime package on June 1 and gives 
Japanese police surveillance powers similar to those enjoyed by 
investigators in other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will apply these laws appropriately and effectively and  
with determined intention we will deal squarely with organized 
crime,'' Justice Minister Takao Jinnouchi said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The wiretapping provision is to take effect within a year.  
</P>
<P>
	The decision came after a marathon 21-hour parliamentary session  
in which opposition lawmakers used a barrage of procedural attacks 
to block a vote backed by the governing coalition led by the 
Liberal Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	The wiretapping law is similar to those in other countries. But  
many Japanese, remembering secret police brutality during World War 
II and crackdowns on radical students and labor unions in the 1950s 
and 1960s, have long been reluctant to hand police greater powers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot but feel the sense of danger that people's freedom  
and privacy are being violated,'' the national Asahi newspaper said 
in an editorial today. 
</P>
<P>
	The public, however, has been demanding more aggressive police  
action against potentially subversive groups since a doomsday 
religious cult attacked Tokyo subways with nerve gas in March 1995, 
killing 12 and injuring thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	After a no-confidence motion against Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi  
failed Wednesday, opposition members paralyzed parliament through 
the night with a filibuster and other go-slow tactics. The measure 
finally passed this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Left-leaning parties have long opposed police wiretaps, fearing  
they could be used to attack leftists and other critics of the 
government, and they had vowed to do what they could to delay the 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	After an all-night, on-and-off session, three opposition parties  
submitted censure motions against the ministers of finance, trade, 
health and education, and the chief cabinet secretary. The motions 
failed. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition lawmakers also delayed a motion to vote on the  
package by staging a ``cow walk,'' in which members walk 
excruciatingly slowly -- or almost not at all -- to place their 
ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have long sought the power to wiretap, saying it would  
strengthen their hand against the yakuza, Japan's organized crime 
syndicates. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other bills in the package would stiffen penalties for  
organized crime and increase protections for witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The wiretap bill, which has already been changed to appease  
critics, requires police to seek court permission for each wiretap, 
which could be used only in cases of murder or smuggling of drugs, 
weapons or people. 
</P>
<P>
	Debate over the measure has inflamed passions on both sides.  
When an upper house committee approved the measure earlier this 
week, opposition lawmakers rushed the chairman's podium, knocking 
over desks and microphones. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Obuchi's coalition easily squashed the  
no-confidence motion in the lower house. Another 
opposition-sponsored censure motion against Obuchi was also 
rejected by a vote of 140-77 in the upper house early today, said 
Ichiro Kouchi, a spokesman for the chamber. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
