<DOCNO> APW19990812.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 17:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Center To Be Closed 6 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Delta Center, declared structurally  
sound Thursday despite shattered windows and holes in the roof, is 
going on the injured list for about six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8-year-old arena, home to the NBA's Utah Jazz and WNBA's  
Utah Starzz, took a direct hit when a tornado churned through 
downtown Salt Lake on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Miller, owner of the Jazz and the Delta Center, estimated  
damage at just under $5 million. He said insurance would cover 
repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19,911-seat facility had holes in its roof, broken windows  
and drenched floors. There was water damage to carpets and 
ceilings, mostly in the arena's upper-level suites and club rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	As cleanup progressed, Miller said the place looked presentable.  
</P>
<P>
	``To see this building now, as opposed to 24 hours ago, is day  
and night,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hardest hit corner was on the club level, six floors up,  
where crumbled ceiling tiles littered the carpet and jagged shards 
of glass poked in from metal window frames. 
</P>
<P>
	In a triangular room, 75 feet wide on its long side, light  
fixtures dangled at chest level from what used to be a ceiling. 
Sunlight came through 20-foot holes in the roof, shining on twisted 
heating ducts. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 green seats on the mezzanine were nicked by falling  
debris and the Starzz court was declared playable despite a 
half-inch dent and visible water damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of water on the floor, a lot from rain but the  
bulk from the fire extinguishing system,'' Miller said. ``One of 
those pipes broke, and it puts a lot of water out in a hurry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tiny bits of shattered glass were everywhere on the concourse,  
remnants of roughly 400 exterior glass panels, each costing $1,000, 
that were blown out by the twister. The building has about 800 
panels. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, in the 25-foot high loading dock, massive aluminum  
roller doors lay in cluttered piles. Changing air pressure from the 
tornado blew them off their hinges and 100 feet down a corridor. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we would have had a concert crew unloading a truck, there  
would have been a lot of fatalities,'' Delta Center general manager 
Scott Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the damage, no serious injuries were reported, and that  
left Miller thankful and gloating. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Delta Center was designed to withstand much more than the  
tornado threw at it yesterday,'' he said. ``We're pleased with how 
well the building actually came through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said complete repairs will take at least six weeks, but  
Miller hopes ``to have it functional'' in time for an Aug. 20 
concert by country singer Neil McCoy, a benefit for charities 
designated by Jazz forward Karl Malone. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have it fully restored is going to take longer,'' Miller  
admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake City is also host city for the 2002 Winter Olympics.  
The Delta Center will be the venue for the figure skating and 
short-track speed skating. 
</P>
<P>
	The twister upstaged an announcement that the Mormon Church  
plans to lend an undeveloped downtown block for the medals 
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The site, just northeast of the Delta Center, is where one man  
died when the tornado shredded a cluster of soft plastic and 
aluminum tents that housed exhibits for an outdoor retailers 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado struck at 12:55 p.m. MDT, about the time the church  
announcement was released. Salt Lake Organizing Committee president 
Mitt Romney tried to stop the fax machines, but it was too late. 
</P>
<P>
	``We obviously would have not had any (announcement) at all,  
given this tragedy,'' Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The church property was SLOC's first choice, Romney said. He  
approached Mormon leaders months ago about donating use of the 
site, along with money for stages and fences. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of the gift was unknown, but Olympic organizers  
budgeted $5 million for rent and construction. Romney has proposed 
concert stages and hospitality tents surrounding the medals podium. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of what I would envision for that block would be in  
memoriam to anyone who lost their life there,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The Starzz have moved their last two home games, Friday against  
Phoenix and Aug. 21 against Los Angeles, to the Dee Events Center 
on the Weber State campus in Ogden, 33 miles to the north. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
