<HEADLINE> Military Engine Plant Leaving Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Jet engine maker Pratt &AMP; Whitney  
will move its military engine operations from Florida to 
Connecticut and relocate other operations, cutting about 1,500 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to moving the military business from West Palm  
Beach, Fla., to its headquarters here, Pratt, a subsidiary of 
United Technologies Corp., said today that it would move its 
manufacturing operation from North Haven, Conn., to the East 
Hartford plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves are part of a restructuring scheduled to be completed  
by 2000. Pratt has been hit hard by the decline in demand for its 
military engines, including powerplants for the F-15 and F-16 
fighters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made considerable progress transforming Pratt into a  
lean organization, reducing costs and improving our ability to 
respond to customers,'' said Pratt president Louis R. Chenevert. 
``However, we see continuing competitive pressures which make it 
critical that we eliminate excess floor space and more closely 
match our cost structure to changing business conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 of the positions to be cut are salaried positions,  
the company said. It was not immediately clear how many of the job 
cuts would involve layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Pratt said it would offer transfers to Connecticut to most of  
the military engine employees in Florida, including moving 
assistance. Employees whose jobs are being cut or who decide 
against moving will receive severance packages and help finding a 
new job, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after the move is complete, Pratt will have about 1,000  
employees in Florida to operate engine test facilities and the 
Space Propulsion business there. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Air Force has warned that the movement of the  
engine operations could imperil Pratt's multi-billion dollar 
contracts for the F-22 and Joint Strike Fighter programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The restructuring is not expected to affect Pratt plants in  
Cheshire, Conn.; North Berwick, Maine; or Columbus, Ga.; nor does 
it involve Pratt &AMP; Whitney Canada, which has taken restructuring 
actions independently. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides jet engines, Pratt &AMP; Whitney also designs, manufactures  
and services, space propulsion systems and industrial gas turbines. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of United Technologies were up $1.12 1/2 to $64.31 1/4 in late  
morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
