<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BET Launches Web Site for Blacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The owner of the leading black cable TV network  
is launching an ambitious Web site aimed at luring more black 
Americans online, a move to narrow the ``digital divide'' that has 
left use of the Internet among blacks well below whites. 
</P>
<P>
	BET.com, which will be launched in November by BET Holdings, is  
getting $35 million in backing from Microsoft Corp. and three major 
media companies, as well as cooperation from the NAACP and the 
United Negro College Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Johnson, the chairman and founder of BET Holdings, wants  
to create the leading online destination for blacks, a ``portal'' 
that Web surfers can use as their home base to jump to other sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet as a revolution has economic as well as social  
implications,'' Johnson said. ``It's being instantly informed of 
information that people are going to find interesting. If you're 
not a part of that, you lose out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new venture will expand on a Web site that BET launched four  
years ago with Microsoft called www.msbet.com. BET Holdings will 
control a majority of the new venture, and the rest will be held by 
Microsoft, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., USA Networks Inc., and 
AT&AMP;T's Liberty Media Corp. Liberty also owns a minority stake in 
BET. 
</P>
<P>
	The new site will offer a variety of news, entertainment,  
finance and free messaging services. It will also sell items aimed 
at black buyers including clothes, books, music and gifts. 
</P>
<P>
	By enlisting help from leaders of the black community, BET is  
hoping to reverse a trend that has skewed Internet usage to a 
predominantly white audience. A study by the Commerce Dept. found 
that just 11.7 percent of black households use the Internet, 
compared with 32.4 percent of white households and 12.9 percent of 
Hispanic ones. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP president Kweisi Mfume, who participated in the  
announcement of the Web site, said he hopes the venture will 
provide a central location for blacks to look for information about 
education and social issues. He said the NAACP would likely 
cooperate by providing information to the site, but details have 
yet to be worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The social implications are that we will be able to empower a  
whole group of individuals that still lags behind in access to 
technology and to the World Wide Web,'' Mfume said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson acknowledged that there remains a ``cultural block''  
that has kept many black Americans from going out and buying 
computers to get on the Internet. ``The bottleneck is in the mind, 
because the buying power is there. We need to send a message that 
it's in your interest to change that mindset and get your kids on 
the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is hoping to parlay his company's ability to penetrate  
black homes into success at building an online destination for a 
minority group, a goal that has so far proved elusive. 
</P>
<P>
	Other sites aimed at particular minority audiences such as  
www.netnoir.com for blacks and www.latinolink.com for Hispanics 
have had only limited success. ``None of them are knocking the 
doors down,'' says Jupiter Communications analyst David Card. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cultural or demographic sites just haven't paid off yet,''  
Card said. ``In order to get people back you need to be in front of 
their face all the time, but I'm somewhat optimistic because BET 
has succeeded in doing that in TV.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BET has established itself as the main cable network catering to  
black audiences, and reaches 57 million households. In addition to 
its main BET network, BET Holdings also operates three other cable 
networks, three magazines and book publishing operations. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent study from Forrester Research suggested that use of the  
Internet by blacks, while low, is increasing. Black use of the 
Internet is accelerating faster than any other ethnic group, the 
study found. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lamar Odom Signs With Clippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lamar Odom is so self-assured that he spoke  
of becoming the NBA's top rookie before the ink on his first 
contract was dry. 
</P>
<P>
	And he did so without so much as a touch of arrogance.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a rookie who hasn't proven himself yet. I've got to work  
on every aspect of my game,'' Odom said Thursday, minutes after 
signing a three-year, $7.8 million contract with the Los Angeles 
Clippers. ``On Monday, I'm going to get right in the gym, starting 
my campaign for rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If every rookie isn't talking like that, then something's  
wrong. I might not end up as rookie of the year. Maybe I'll end up 
as one of the best seventh men in the league. There's something I'm 
going to bring this team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clippers feel exactly the same way about the fourth overall  
selection in this summer's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very likable person,'' Clippers vice president of  
basketball operations Elgin Baylor said. ``What I visualize him 
doing is making other players better because of his ability to pass 
the basketball, create for the other people. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited about having a player like that, who has such a  
great feel, such a great understanding for the game. He certainly 
has the potential to be one of the better players in the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-9 Odom will be paid $2.4 million in his first season,  
$2.6 million in 2000-2001 and $2.8 million in 2001-2002. The 
Clippers hold a club option for $3.5 million in 2002-2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm officially in the NBA -- my lifetime dream,'' said Odom,  
who averaged 17.6 points, 9.4 rebounds and 3.8 assists for Rhode 
Island last year in his only season of college basketball. ``This 
is the opportunity of a lifetime for anybody. The ball is rolling, 
finally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Odom figures to play small forward for the Clippers, perhaps  
teaming on a front line with third-year forward Maurice Taylor and 
second-year center Michael Olowokandi, the first overall selection 
in last year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the sky's the limit for this team,'' Odom said. ``I  
think it's time for Los Angeles to have two great teams; hopefully, 
I can bring something special to this city, this team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Bulls weren't always the best team in the NBA. I'm not  
saying I'm Michael Jordan; it's got to start somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Odom, who turns 20 on Nov. 6, admits he's had ups and downs. He  
attended three high schools during his senior year, began his 
college career at UNLV, but didn't play, and wound up leaving Rhode 
Island after one season. 
</P>
<P>
	Even then, he changed his mind twice, first declaring himself  
eligible for the draft, then changing his mind, and finally 
changing his mind yet again. 
</P>
<P>
	In the weeks leading up to the draft, many felt he'd be the  
first overall selection. However, he fell to fourth, much to the 
delight of the Clippers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has doubts,'' Odom said in the team's offices at the  
Los Angeles Sports Arena, not far from the Staples Center, where 
the Clippers and Lakers will play this season. ``People go through 
adversity to reach the mountaintop, to look down at the doubters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've been through a lot. I have a great organization  
around me. When I come in, I see smiles, hugs, handshakes. I get a 
great feeling from everyone here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
