<HEADLINE> Aussie Coal Miners May Strike Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Coal miners in Australia will strike  
for 24 hours from midnight Thursday night in a move that could cost 
the industry nearly $20 million in lost production. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike was called Thursday by the Construction, Forestry,  
Mining and Energy Union, which is campaigning for 125 workers who 
were recently dismissed from the Oakdale mine in New South Wales 
state to receive their entitlements of more than $3.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike will affect 20,000 coal miners in about 100 mines,  
mostly in New South Wales and Queensland states. The coal industry 
is worth about $6.5 billion to the Australian economy each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Maher, the union's mining and energy division president,  
said the strike is drastic because the federal government hasn't 
fixed the problem for the workers, who were dismissed suddenly two 
months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers and the union have been negotiating with the  
government over their unpaid entitlements. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government offers tea and sympathy but no real action and  
we've had enough of it,'' Maher said in a radio interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith said the strike  
would achieve nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think problems are settled by industrial action, this  
is just a bloody-minded attack for political purposes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oakdale mine, southwest of Sydney, folded in June, leaving  
125 employees out of work. 
</P>
<P>
	Anger over the miners' plight and the wider issue of security of  
workers' entitlements in the event of corporate collapses has 
brewed since. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure of a meeting on Tuesday involving government  
ministers, union and worker representatives to agree on a bailout 
plan led the miners' union to call Thursday's action. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
