<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wilkes Booth Home Being Auctioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEL AIR, Md. (AP) -- To the dismay of preservationists, the  
childhood home of presidential assassin John Wilkes Booth is to be 
auctioned. 
</P>
<P>
	``There would be a huge public outcry if it were bulldozed,''  
said Gary Sloan, executive director of the Preservation Association 
for Tudor Hall Inc. ``It's become the legacy of the Booth family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Preservationists are concerned because although the home is  
listed on national and state registers of historic places, an 
easement has not been placed on the property to prevent its 
demolition. 
</P>
<P>
	The four bedroom brick home about 20 miles northeast of  
Baltimore, known as Tudor Hall, is scheduled to be sold Oct. 16. It 
is worth an estimated $225,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The husband and wife that owned the house, Howard and Dorothy  
Fox, died this spring. Their heirs are selling the property, 
confirmed their lawyer, Robert G. Cassilly. They decided to auction 
the property after a deal to sell the home to Harford Community 
College fell through and county officials expressed no interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The house was built as a country retreat for John Wilkes Booth's  
father, Junius Brutus Booth, a Shakespearean actor who moved to 
Baltimore from England in 1821. 
</P>
<P>
	While John Wilkes Booth is known primarily for the assassination  
of Abraham Lincoln, he was also an acclaimed Shakespearean actor, 
and his brother Edwin Booth, was one of the most highly respected 
actors of his time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
