<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar slid against the yen Friday after the  
Japanese government said an economic growth spurt in the first 
three months of the year was actually greater than initially 
thought. Tokyo share prices fell moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.77 yen at midday, down 0.91 yen from late  
Thursday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 115.62 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 82.93 points,  
or 0.48 percent, to 17,340.04 at the end of the morning trading. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 211.81 points, or 1.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Economic Planning Agency announced Japan's economy grew 2.0  
percent during the January-March period, slightly higher than the 
1.9 percent growth it initially reported in June. 
</P>
<P>
	If the growth pace set in the last quarter were to continue, GDP  
would expand 8.1 percent this year, the EPA said. That was up from 
the 7.9 percent announced in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has recently strengthened against the dollar amid  
optimism that the economy is showing signs of emerging from a 
prolonged downturn. Friday's announcement was likely to enhance 
such beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 122.57 yen, down  
from 123.36 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices fell on selling sparked by the  
yen's renewed rise against the dollar. Investors are worried about 
the impact of a stronger yen on corporate earnings, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, and reduces the dollar-denominated earnings 
of exporting companies when translated into yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average gained 1.59  
points to 10,789.39 at Thursday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 1.03 points, or 0.07 percent, to 1,437.41. 
The TOPIX closed up 17.80 points, or 1.25 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8450 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8250 percent, driving 
its price down to 99.61 yen from 99.78 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
