<HEADLINE> Dollar, Gold Mixed in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0624 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0661 Wednesday. Later, in afternoon trading in New York, 
the euro traded at $1.0631. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,  
included 115.86 Japanese yen, up from 115.17; 1.5071 Swiss francs, 
up from 1.5020; 1.4848 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4924. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6086, down from $1.6108.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading in New York, the dollar bought 115.69 yen,  
and the pound was worth $1.6072. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8410 German marks, up from 1.8346; 
6.1743 French francs, up from 6.1529; 2.0743 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0671; 1,822.54 Italian lire, up from 1,816.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $260.30 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$257.80 on Wednesday. In Zurich the bid price was $260.25, up from 
$257.45. Gold rose $3.70 in Hong Kong to $260.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.38 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.33. 
  	   	
</P>
