<DOCNO> APW19990812.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 12:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alcan Won't Rule Out Reynolds Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Alcan Aluminium Ltd. president and chief  
executive Jacques Bougie said Alcan isn't ruling out the 
possibility of making a bid for Reynolds Metals Co. following 
yesterday's $5.6 billion offer for Reynolds by Alcoa Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked at a news conference here about the possibility of a  
counterbid for Reynolds, Bougie said, ``We exclude no options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bougie declined to comment further on the Rnolds situation  
however, saying he wanted to focus his comments on Alcan's planned 
three-way merger with Pechiney S.A. and Alusuisse-Lonza Holding AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Bougie did dismiss as far-fetched a theory that Alcoa had  
announced its bid merely as a ploy to complicate antitrust 
regulatory clearance for Alcan's three-way merger. He said he 
believes Alcoa is serious about wanting to acquire Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Alcan had been rumored as a possible suitor  
for Reynolds. Some analysts Wednesday characterized Alcoa's offer 
for Reynolds as a low-ball bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Reynolds initially rose Thursday, before declining on  
profit-taking, as investors speculated that either the $65 per 
share offer would be increased or a another bid would emerge. 
</P>
<P>
	In early afternoon trading, shares were down 25 cents to $65,  
well off the high of $67.25, on the New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
