<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fund-Raiser Huang Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Democratic fund-raiser John Huang  
pleaded guilty Thursday to conspiracy for violating campaign 
finance laws and was sentenced to one year of probation and a 
$10,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The plea and sentence were expected but had been delayed by an  
effort to have Huang, who has been cooperating, testify before 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Richard Paez said he expected Huang to  
continue cooperating with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``These matters should not be taken lightly. I expect that you  
will cooperate with everyone in all these matters,'' Paez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang's lawyer, Ty Cobb, said his client would appear before  
Congress if called. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your honor, I'm very sad and embarrassed by my mistakes that  
have brought disrepute to my family and my community,'' Huang told 
the judge. ``I'm glad the court has given me the opportunity to 
serve my community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, a former executive of the Jakarta-based Lippo Group, was  
the Democrats' chief fund-raiser for the Asian-American community 
in 1996. He brought in $1.6 million in questionable donations that 
later were returned. 
</P>
<P>
	He was only accused of an illegal $2,500 donation to the  
campaign committee of Los Angeles mayoral candidate Michael Woo in 
1993, and an illegal $5,000 donation to California Victory Fund '94 
that was shared by Sen. Dianne Feinstein's re-election committee, 
the Democratic senatorial campaign committee and the state 
Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang could have been sentenced to prison for five years.  
</P>
<P>
	Cobb said it was clear from government documents that ``although  
Mr. Huang did not play a minor role, he was not the main leader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Daniel O'Brien does not suspect Huang of  
involvement in espionage. However, the government left open the 
possibility that he could be called as a witness in espionage 
probes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., the chairman of the House Committee on  
Government Reform, last month pressed U.S. Attorney General Janet 
Reno to seek postponement of sentencing for both Huang and 
fund-raiser Charlie Trie because they had not testified before 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The government was granted a six-week delay to assess Trie's  
cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie has pleaded guilty to two counts involving campaign finance  
violations and pledged to cooperate in the investigation. 
Prosecutors have recommended three years' probation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
