<HEADLINE> Mass. Barricaded Homeowner Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A man who barricaded himself on his 14-acre estate  
for nine months in a fight over whether he had to repay a $1.6 
million bank loan has been sentenced to four months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sweeney, who was captured in February 1998 by six marshals  
after they broke a window to get in, was convicted of contempt of 
court in a nonjury trial in April. He had ignored a federal order 
to vacate his home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sickened by the court and its actions,'' Sweeney said,  
vowing to appeal. ``Is it over? No way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials say they own the estate because Sweeney and  
his wife, Rhetta, defaulted on their 1987 bank loan, which had been 
taken over by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney, 59, was evicted but refused to leave the estate, which  
once belonged to his great-grandfather, a secretary of the Navy, 
postmaster general and ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also said the Sweeneys owed $1.4 million in taxes  
in addition to the loan payments; the Sweeneys said they had been 
swindled by the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, anti-government militia members allied themselves  
with the Sweeneys and patrolled the estate, 20 miles outside 
Boston. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
