<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American, Pilots To Continue Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines and the leaders of  
its pilots union will return to the bargaining table early next 
week to try to settle an issue that led to a pilots' sickout 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have been arguing for months over how American  
should absorb lower-paid pilots from Reno Air, which American's 
parent company bought in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Baker, American's executive vice president of operations,  
said Wednesday that American has agreed to a request by mediator 
George Nicolau to meet next week with representatives of the Allied 
Pilots Association. 
</P>
<P>
	But Baker repeated that the airline will go ahead with the  
completion of the merger on Aug. 31 even if there is no deal with 
the pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Union spokesman Gregg Overman said leaders are hopeful they can  
reach a deal on Monday. The union's board has scheduled a meeting 
Tuesday, during which it could vote to ratify any agreement that 
had been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9,500-member union opposes American's use of about 300 Reno  
pilots who are paid roughly half what American pilots make. The 
union has demanded that Reno pilots' pay be raised to American's 
levels retroactive to December and that about 1,900 American pilots 
be promoted into higher-paying jobs over the next 15 months. 
</P>
<P>
	American has said the union's demands would greatly increase the  
cost of the Reno acquisition, and it prefers to raise the new 
pilots' pay as they are retrained to fly American jets. 
</P>
<P>
	The impasse led to a sickout by about a quarter of American's  
pilots in February. The airline said about 6,700 flights were 
canceled, costing it $225 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicolau, the mediator, gave both sides a proposal to settle the  
dispute last month. American approved the proposal, but the union's 
directors made several changes that American rejected. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
