<DOCNO> APW19990812.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 10:00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Pleads for Tolerance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno today deplored  
``our culture of violence'' and called on the country to act now to 
combat racial intolerance, bigotry and gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno told her weekly news conference that, although the  
investigation is still under way, the shootings at a Jewish 
community center in Los Angeles this week ``appear to have been 
motivated by hate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A suspect, Buford O. Furrow Jr., 37, told investigators as he  
surrendered that ``he wanted this to be a wake-up call to America 
to kill Jews,'' according to an FBI official, who requested 
anonymity. Furrow is charged with attempted murder of five people, 
including three boys, who were shot and wounded at the Jewish 
center, and with the murder of an Hispanic postal carrier nearby 
soon afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hate crimes represent an attack not just on individual  
victims,'' Reno said, ``but also on the victims' communities. They 
tear at the very fabric of a people's life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called for a response from schools, religious institutions,  
civic organizations and ``each one of us as individuals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We must decide now, as a nation, whether we are going to allow  
our culture of violence to continue on into the next millennium, or 
whether we are going to start into the new era with a commitment to 
tolerance and to peaceful resolution of our disputes,'' Reno said. 
``We must act now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We must do more to teach our children tolerance, and make sure  
that they learn to accept people regardless of their race, 
religion, nationality or sexual orientation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called on Congress to enact the administration's proposal to  
expand federal authority to prosecute hate crimes and its gun 
control measures ``to keep dangerous firearms out of the hands of 
criminals, children and others who should not have them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow also was charged Wednesday with the federal crime of  
illegal possession of a gun, based on his earlier felony conviction 
in Washington state. Federal law bars felons from owning guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``For four months since the tragedy in Littleton, Colo., the  
administration and Congress have debated over how to reform our gun 
laws,'' Reno said, citing the deadly attack by two well-armed 
students on a Colorado high school. ``Yet we have not been able to 
pass gun safety measures that even most gun owners support. ... And 
anyone can still walk into a gun show and buy a high-powered, 
dangerous weapon without even having to establish their identity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She called for passage of the Senate version of a juvenile  
justice bill when Congress returns next month. The Senate bill 
contains administration-backed provisions to extend background 
checks to gun buyers at gun shows and adds violent juveniles to 
those banned for life from owning guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also has proposed a three-day cooling-off  
period before a gun can be purchased, that every gun be sold with a 
triggerlock and criminal penalties for adults who let children get 
hold of guns and use them for violence. 
</P>
<P>
	And Reno renewed her appeal for serious study by states and the  
federal government of ``the possibility of requiring the licensing 
of all handguns'' so that prospective owners who have to 
demonstrate they ``know how to safely and lawfully use them.'' The 
administration has not formally backed such a proposal though 
President Clinton has spoken favorably about licensing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
