<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Prices Fall / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grains and soybeans futures prices plummeted in  
trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade on bearish crop 
production reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants hoping for a late rally were disappointed  
when the Board of Trade closed an hour early Thursday after a power 
outage affecting the downtown Loop area threatened to expand. The 
Board of Trade said Project A electronic trading in all markets 
would be shut down Thursday night and reopen at 9 a.m. EDT Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The price drop was in reaction to a surprising crop production  
report from the U.S. Agriculture Department. USDA estimated the 
1999-00 corn crop at 9.56 billion bushels, far above the average 
trade guess. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA supply/demand report showed a lower-than-expected cut  
to U.S. soybean production. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneficial overnight rains in the Midwest that were expected to  
last until Friday also weighed on prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report was definitely bigger than the trade was looking  
for,'' Don Roose of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. said of the 
production figures. ``You got hit with two things today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices were lower in sympathy with corn and soybeans,  
despite some bullish production news. 
</P>
<P>
	CBOT chief executive officer Thomas R. Donovan made the decision  
to close the markets at 2 p.m. EDT after speaking to Commonwealth 
Edison CEO John Rowe, said CBOT spokesman Bret Gallaway. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Donovan wanted to ensure an orderly shut down, avoiding  
the potential chaos if power failed with as many as 5,000 traders 
on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous disruption of trading,'' Gallaway said.  
``The last minutes of trading are often some of the busiest trading 
of the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problems were blamed on the failures of two power  
transmission cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 8 1/2 cents to $2.80 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 12 cents to $2.23 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
2 1/2 cents to $1.16 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 30 cents to 
$4.56 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were lower and feeder cattle futures higher  
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were mostly 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .22 cent to 65.50 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .28 cent to 77.40 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .08 cent to 54.45 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
fell .93 cent to 56.82 cents a pound. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
