<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Turn Mixed / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with the blue-chips  
making the most aggressive push to extend Wednesday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 23.12 at 10,810.92, adding to Wednesday's 132.65-point gain. The 
Dow rose as much as 62 points earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.45 at 1,304.38, and the  
Nasdaq composite index was down 4.56 at 2,560.42. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries about higher interest rates, which have held the market  
down for nearly three weeks, continued to rattle investors today. 
The latest evidence that the Federal Reserve may raise rates in an 
effort to stave off inflation came from a stronger-than-expected 
report on retail sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that retail sales rose 0.7  
percent in July, boosted by a big gain in automotive sales. Strong 
consumer spending could suggest to the Fed that the booming economy 
is overheating, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	But without automobiles and seasonal goods like air  
conditioners, the retail sales increase was quite modest, noted 
Robert G. Smith, chief executive officer of Smith Affiliated 
Capital in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really kind of a bland number,'' he said. ``But there's  
a lot of anxiety right now about every new domestic economic 
indicator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts believe the Fed will be more interested in the  
producer price index, due for release on Friday. That index is a 
measure of inflation pressures at the wholesale level, or before 
reaching consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Caterpillar rose 2 5/8 to 61 7/8, helping buoy the Dow after Goldman  
Sachs added the company to its list of recommended stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online extended its gains from the previous session,  
rising 15/16 to 93 5/16. AOL shares rose 7 3/8 on Wednesday after 
company executives held an upbeat conference call with analysts and 
major investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 231.84 million shares 
at late morning, behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.12 at 612.34, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.77 at 779.14. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
