<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Local Governments Hire More Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State and local governments are hiring more  
workers, the Census Bureau reports. 
</P>
<P>
	There were 14.5 million workers employed by local and state  
governments across the nation as of March, 1998, up from 14.2 
million a year earlier, according to tabulations for the 50 states 
and the District of Columbia released Wednesday by the bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	That included 10.5 million people working for local governments  
and 3.9 million for state governments. 
</P>
<P>
	The boost in workers raised payrolls for March 1998 to $43  
billion, up from $39 billion a year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Employment figures are given for full-time equivalent workers,  
that is combining full and part time employees and calculating the 
number of full-time jobs done. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, education was the largest area for state and local  
government workers with 5.7 million elementary and secondary school 
workers, up from 5.5 million, and 1.7 million higher education 
employees, up from 1.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	There were 941,280 people employed in state and local hospitals,  
down from 984,375 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Police accounted for 817,941 employees in 1998, up from 798,424  
while fire protection accounted for 281,922, up from 277,152 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial administration kept 363,049 state and local employees  
busy in 1998, up from 360,724 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	And there were 530,097 street and highway workers last year,  
down from 530,577 a year earlier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
