<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Probes Biological Clock Genes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Genes that control the biological clock of  
fruit flies also affect whether those flies become addicted to 
cocaine, says a surprising new study that suggests these internal 
clocks -- humans have them, too -- might have still other 
undiscovered roles in the body. 
</P>
<P>
	It's unclear what the cocaine discovery might mean for human  
drug addiction, although scientists have used fruit flies as 
potential models to study the biology behind drug abuse. The hope 
is that the insect studies ultimately will point the way toward 
better drug treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	University of Virginia researchers studied the ``sensitization''  
of fruit flies to cocaine, giving repeated doses to produce 
increasingly severe responses -- in flies, problems with flying. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers report Friday in the journal Science that genes  
that control fruit flies' internal circadian rhythms also 
determined whether they become sensitized to cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	They found that normal fruit flies do become sensitized, but  
flies that lacked any of four genes that play a role in the flies' 
biological clocks did not become sensitized, despite repeated 
cocaine dosings. 
</P>
<P>
	Those genes may regulate an enzyme that appears important in  
determining whether cocaine sensitization occurs, the researchers 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anderson Works Out at Falcons Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Jamal Anderson took the field in his  
familiar 32 jersey Thursday afternoon, but it wasn't the same field 
taken by his Atlanta Falcons teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	While coach Dan Reeves led the Falcons in a hour-long  
walk-through session in preparation for their first exhibition game 
Friday night against Detroit, Anderson jogged and sprinted on a 
neighboring field the day after signing a five-year, $32 million 
contract and ending a two-week holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, the two rode off together in a golf cart, clearly  
happy that Wednesday's four-hour negotiating session brought the 
NFL's No. 2 rusher to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson called Reeves his ``captain, oh my captain'' and ``el  
presidente.'' Reeves insisted there was only one president on the 
team, and it wasn't him. 
</P>
<P>
	He also challenged reporters to ``ask him (Jamal) a serious  
question and see if you get a serious answer.'' Anderson, who 
gained 1,846 yards last season, will not play in Friday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how long it will be before he's ready to play in  
a game situation,'' Reeves said. ``It might be next week (Aug. 20 
vs. Baltimore) or maybe the following week. Right now we need all 
the reps we can get for the younger players, so we'll let Jamal do 
a lot of conditioning work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson insisted that conditioning ``is nothing without the  
pads'' and then joked that ``I'm sure come Monday I'll probably 
pass out. I hope he (Reeves) doesn't kill me, but I'm anticipating 
the worst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons will go with regular starter Chris Chandler at  
quarterback against Detroit, then switch to newcomer Danny Kanell 
early on. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's good in the first series, he might come out then,''  
Reeves said about Chandler, who was fourth in league passing 
ratings last season. ``Or he might go another series. But basically 
we'll be looking at Danny this week and Tony (Graziani) next 
week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kanell, acquired during the offseason from the New York Giants,  
``has an extremely quick release, sees the field well, and is 
extremely smart,'' Reeves said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he still has those years in another system that he has to  
forget. The key to any quarterback being successful is to be fully 
comfortable with the system he's in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves said the big questions in Friday's game will be in the  
secondary and at wide receiver, where injuries have dogged the team 
during training camp. Reserve cornerbacks Michael Booker and Elijah 
Williams and first-team receiver Chris Calloway will not play, and 
wideout Tim Dwight is questionable after missing Thursday's 
walk-through. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game is an opportunity for a lot of guys to perform. It's  
a good test,'' Reeves said. ``We'll get a chance to evaluate 
everyone. I hope we go out and execute well and start to be the 
type of team that we were last year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
