<DOCNO> APW19990812.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 16:28:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Tries Again To Enter U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan started a new drive Thursday to  
rejoin the United Nations, an effort that could escalate tensions 
between the island and an already angry China. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid for U.N. membership has become an annual ritual, but  
this year's plea by Taiwan was fine-tuned to reflect President Lee 
Teng-hui's recent declaration that the island is its own state. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest effort was likely to provoke a hostile reaction from  
China, which has threatened to reunite Taiwan with the Chinese 
mainland through force. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Taiwanese said they held little hope that this time  
they will succeed. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Foreign Minister David Lee told reporters the bid will  
probably be crushed by China, which has resolutely objected to the 
island's participation in the United Nations. China considers 
Taiwan a renegade province. 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen of Taiwan's diplomatic allies -- most of them small, poor  
nations in Africa, Latin America and the South Pacific -- filed a 
draft resolution with the U.N. secretariat on Wednesday asking that 
Taiwan's lack of representation be discussed by the General 
Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan has long sought recognition as a state, but President Lee  
made the call more explicit by announcing July 9 that Taiwan's 
relations with China should be designated as ``state-to-state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's statement discarded earlier, more ambiguous  
language about Taiwan's relations with China, from which Taiwan 
separated 50 years ago after a civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	Beijing has lashed back furiously at what it characterizes as a  
dangerous step toward a formal declaration of independence -- a 
declaration China says would lead to war. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington has called for both sides to calm down. The United  
States does not recognize Taiwan, but it is bound by law to treat 
the island's security as a matter of concern. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear whether Washington would help fight off a Chinese  
attack, though the United States has moved warships into the area 
during previous standoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan would like to see China take a ``rational'' approach to  
Taiwan's quest for representation in the world body, but wasn't 
holding its breath, David Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everyone is very clear that this endeavor, I'm afraid,  
won't achieve any immediate results, but we've always felt that no 
one can predict international change,'' the deputy foreign minister 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan walked out of the United Nations in 1971, just before  
other members voted to give its old seat to the People's Republic 
of China. By seeking to rejoin, Taiwan is only demanding its rights 
and doesn't want to ``pick a fight,'' David Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	An explanatory memorandum accompanying President Lee's  
resolution to the U.N. points out Taiwan's efforts at international 
humanitarian relief, saying it has sent 10,000 experts overseas 
through the years to help countries in trouble, while providing 
$150 million in disaster aid over the past several years. 
</P>
<P>
	It also referred to a $300 million aid package promised to  
Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
