<DOCNO> APW19990812.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 13:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Williams, Collins Debut Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- At first glance, the matchup between Ricky Williams  
and Cecil ``the Diesel'' Collins hardly looks even. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams rushed for an NCAA-record 6,279 yards and 72 touchdowns  
before winning the Heisman Trophy. Collins rushed for 713 yards and 
four touchdowns before going to jail. 
</P>
<P>
	But the rookie running backs will share the spotlight in their  
NFL debuts Friday night when the New Orleans Saints face the Miami 
Dolphins in a preseason game. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, the fifth player taken in the April draft, is expected  
to rejuvenate a Saints franchise that hasn't been to the playoffs 
in seven years. Collins, the 134th player drafted, is the latest 
candidate to rejuvenate the Dolphins' perennially moribund ground 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Both will see limited action in the exhibition opener. Williams  
will play no more than 1 1/2 quarters, Collins perhaps even less. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait to finally get out there in a stadium and get my  
first NFL experience,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ditto for Collins, who has shown so far in training camp that  
the Dolphins gambled wisely when they drafted him in the fifth 
round. He slipped that far only because drug and legal problems 
limited him to six games in college at Louisiana State and McNeese 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've proved a lot since day one,'' Collins said.  
``It's been a long road for me. The more repetitions I get, the 
more comfortable I feel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dolphins fans are so desperate for a productive running back  
that they're still buzzing about Collins' performance in a 
scrimmage last week, when he rushed for a grand total of 22 yards 
in four carries. Coach Jimmy Johnson's comments have fueled the 
hype. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good back. He doesn't give you a whole to tackle -- just  
shoulder pads, knees and elbows,'' Johnson said. ``He tends to put 
a smile on a lot of people's faces, other than the opponents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams has also received rave reviews from teammates and  
Saints coach Mike Ditka, who traded all of his draft choices for 
the chance to pick Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more I watch him, the more I'm amazed,'' Ditka said.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he stays healthy, there's no doubt in my mind he may be one  
of the best running backs ever to play the game,'' quarterback 
Billy Joe Hobert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saints owner Tom Benson has said he expects the Saints to make  
the playoffs, a lofty goal for a franchise with just four 
postseason games in their history -- all losses. 
</P>
<P>
	On the day of the draft, Johnson poked fun at Ditka for the  
trade that netted Williams. But this week, Johnson admitted he 
might swap an entire draft for one player under the right 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we were desperate for a quarterback, yes, I'd trade a draft  
for a quarterback,'' Johnson said. ``I would have traded a draft 
for Troy Aikman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether I would have paid an entire draft for Emmitt Smith --  
maybe. Emmitt has turned into a Hall of Fame player, but I don't 
know that I knew that back when I drafted him. There are key 
players you would probably pay a draft for, but very few.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Would Johnson trade the players he drafted this year for  
Williams? That question may be easier to answer after watching 
Williams and Collins play Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
