<HEADLINE> Denver Mayor Urges Gun Control March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Mayor Wellington Webb, president of the U.S.  
mayor's conference, called on mayors and police chiefs Thursday to 
march on Congress to press for gun control to stop an epidemic of 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	This week's attack on a Jewish Center in Los Angeles shows gun  
control ``is more important than tax cuts,'' Webb told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	It's time, he said, for ``Congress to respond to the wishes of  
the American public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webb clashed with the National Rifle Association after the  
Columbine massacre in nearby Littleton, urging the group to move 
its national convention from Denver. When the group went ahead with 
the meeting, Webb marched with protesters outside the meeting site. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Thursday, Webb called on mayors and police  
chiefs to head for Washington on Sept. 9 ``to urge their local 
congresspersons to support responsible and effective gun control 
legislation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor said he expected ``a substantial number'' to heed his  
call. He said he picked Sept. 9 to coincide with the return of many 
of the country's schoolchildren to school. 
  	   	
