<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs Buys Thai Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The New York investment bank Goldman  
Sachs was the most successful bidder at the last auction held by 
Thailand to liquidate the holdings of failed finance companies, the 
agency announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Sector Restructuring Authority, set up two years  
ago to liquidate the failed institutions, said Thursday it sold 30 
of 35 loan packages for an average of 23 percent of outstanding 
principal value in Wednesday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	They were valued at a combined $3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	The FRA is responsible for the liquidation of 56 finance  
companies closed by the government after the economic collapse of 
mid-1997, which grew into the Asian crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	FRA chairman Amaret Sila-on said that with new investors, the  
assets that have been sold ``can be productively serviced, creating 
thousands of jobs, providing new life to viable projects and 
accelerating Thailand's economic recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. unit ASO 1 paid $547 million for its  
purchases. Goldman Sachs, in partnerships with other firms, was a 
big buyer in two previous auctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other winning bidders were Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. unit  
Global Thai. Winning Thai firms were Kiatnakin Finance PCL, 
National Finance PCL, and The Pavilion Fund, affiliated with the CP 
Group. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
