<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Parents Key to Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While politicians have focused on Hollywood  
and Washington to make schools safer, a national education forum 
broadcast by satellite put the spotlight on parents Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents listen to their children frequently and carefully when  
they are young; we urge all parents to talk with their children 
just a much or more when they are high school students,'' said 
Education Secretary Richard W. Riley. 
</P>
<P>
	Answering viewer calls, Riley and Attorney General Janet Reno  
also put forth recommended policy changes they said would enhance 
the safety of children. 
</P>
<P>
	But the national forum in the wake of the April shootings at  
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., was intended to focus on 
parents. President Clinton echoed the theme, saying in videotaped 
remarks that ``no influence on a child is more important'' than 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to take a position and begin to parent again,''  
Virginia Markell, president of the National Parent Teacher 
Association, said at the Thursday night forum. 
</P>
<P>
	Betty Baumgartner, who was in the studio audience, said children  
need more than metal detectors, adding that the children in her 
Methodist youth group in Fairfax County often tell her things they 
won't tell their parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``You need to have a relationship in order for the young people  
to really share what's going on in their lives. (Violence) comes 
down to dealing with conflicts,'' said Baumgartner. 
</P>
<P>
	Also fresh in the country's consciousness are the shootings of  
day-traders in Atlanta and the attacks on young children and their 
caretakers at a Jewish community center in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the incidents were ``another compelling argument  
for the passage of hate-crimes legislation and common-sense gun 
laws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 90-minute program, ``Safe Schools, Safe Students: What  
Parents Can Do,'' was being televised from the Freedom Forum's 
Newseum in Arlington, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past two years, a series of school shootings has  
prompted increased school security and efforts to identify and help 
troubled children. 
</P>
<P>
	Those efforts took on added urgency following the April 20  
shootings at Columbine. Two students wearing black trenchcoats 
gunned down 12 classmates and a teacher before shooting themselves. 
Copycat threats and shootings that followed in schools nationwide 
has led to tightened security. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we prepare for the start of a new school year, we must do  
all we can to ensure that schools remain safe,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Education Department is offering parents free safety guides  
it has published for schools. And since 1992, the department has 
held monthly satellite town meetings and special events such as the 
school safety program. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, the forums are broadcast to roughly 400 to 500 TV  
stations across the country -- mostly local cable-access channels, 
public television affiliates, and Channel One, the 
advertising-supported news show beamed into 12,000 schools. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
