<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Streaking Mystics Eye Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A year ago, the Washington Mystics couldn't  
wait for their humbling inaugural WNBA season to end. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, riding a franchise-record five-game winning streak, the  
team that limped to a forgettable 3-27 record in 1998 is eyeing the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mystics (11-17), who have four games left and are within  
reach of the Eastern Conference's final playoff spot, have made a 
stunning turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really do believe that we are going to win,'' coach Nancy  
Darsch said. ``We do believe that when it's a tight game that we'll 
find a way to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mystics made the most of a bad situation following their  
dismal debut last summer. Those losses yielded the top pick in the 
WNBA draft, which they used to select forward Chamique Holdsclaw, 
who led Tennessee to three consecutive NCAA titles from 1996-98. 
</P>
<P>
	By teaming Holdsclaw with guard Nikki McCray, the league's  
fourth-leading scorer last year, Washington got what it lacked in 
its rookie season: the ability to score from the perimeter or from 
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Darsch, the team's third coach in two years, quickly gutted the  
Mystics and remade the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four players from the inaugural season remain on the  
roster. Holdsclaw led a group of newcomers that included several 
refugees from the defunct American Basketball League. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with Holdsclaw and McCray leading the way, no one expected  
such a rebound from a team that didn't win back-to-back games for 
the first time until July. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only a few people left from last year, so this is  
pretty much a new start,'' said Holdsclaw, who has averaged 21.2 
points and 8.4 rebounds during the five-game streak. ``This team 
goes into every game as underdogs and we go out and play that 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCray, who has averaged 20.4 points and hit 12 of 27 3-pointers  
during the resurgence, said opponents err if they assume the 
Mystics boast only two offensive weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest difference is that we have system now that allows  
everybody to shoot the ball. ... It's not always just me and 
Chamique scoring,'' McCray said. ``And we actually have better 
players here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdover center Murriel Page leads the WNBA in field goal  
percentage. Newcomer Andrea Nagy, a point guard with ABL 
experience, is a ballhandler who can run the floor. The bench is 
stronger and deeper and players are willing to accept specific 
roles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's more committed,'' Holdsclaw said. ``We're playing  
with passion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The five-game streak includes victories over three teams in  
front of the Mystics in the East -- Detroit, Orlando and 
division-leading New York, which has dropped three games to 
Washington this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other victories came against last-place Cleveland, including  
an Aug. 8 win in which the Mystics held the Rockers to 45 points, a 
WNBA low this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to finish strong and finish on a high, whatever  
that may be -- if that's the playoffs or not,'' Darsch said. 
``There's too many factors involved right now to put must-win 
pressure on ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Mystics are suddenly growing accustomed to winning.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to shoot ourselves in the foot,'' McCray said.  
``We want to finish this season strong.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catfish Still in Critical Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter remained in  
critical condition after regaining consciousness three days after 
hitting his head on concrete steps at his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter, 53, who pitched in the majors 15 years and earned five  
World Series rings, was conscious, alert and responding to doctors' 
commands today, a hospital spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of Hertford, the tight-knit Perquimans County  
community where Hunter lives, anxiously awaited word on changes in 
his condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing you learn about this place, this area, is how much  
baseball means around here,'' said Steve Lane, who owns an Internet 
service and who moved to Hertford from Providence, R.I. ``People 
here look at him and think of how much he's meant to this 
community, and it's like everyone wants to change places with 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said Hunter, diagnosed last year with Lou Gehrig's  
disease -- a gradual, irreversible deterioration of the muscles -- 
suffered brain bruising. He likely will require rehabilitation 
because he already was weakened by the disease, amyotrophic lateral 
sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it would be premature to even think about that,'' said Dr.  
Paul Cunningham, a trauma physician and professor of surgery at the 
East Carolina University School of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``His prognosis is still somewhat guarded. We're being hopeful  
as we can be, but we're taking things one day at a time,'' said 
Cunningham. He said no surgery was planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital spokesman Doug Boyd said Hunter regained consciousness  
Wednesday after being unconscious much of Tuesday. He began 
responding to commands -- ``wiggle your toes and that sort of 
thing,'' Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Helen Hunter and other relatives, gathered in the hospital ICU,  
declined to talk to the media. ``The family is very private right 
now,'' Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter left Hertford to play for the Kansas City Athletics in  
1965 and moved with the club to Oakland in 1968. He became the 
first multimillionaire baseball player when he signed with the 
Yankees in 1974. Beginning in 1971, Hunter strung together five 
straight, 20-victory seasons and won the Cy Young Award in 1974. He 
retired from the Yankees in 1979 and returned to Hertford, where he 
easily returned to life on his 400-acre farm. 
</P>
<P>
	``To show you what kind of guy he was and always has been, I  
remember in 1976, I was in high school and it was the year of the 
baseball strike,'' said Russell Lassiter, owner of Carolina Trophy 
&AMP; Engraving. ``Jimmy stayed here and came out and pitched batting 
practice for us. Here was the guy who was the best in the business 
out pitching baseball practice to a bunch of high school kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``And it was just like he was one of us.''  
</P>
<P>
	A diabetic who required thrice-daily insulin injections, Hunter  
announced last fall he had ALS, a neurological disease that 
interferes with signals the brain sends to muscles, causing the 
muscles to degenerate over time. There is no cure. 
</P>
<P>
	ALS has robbed Hunter of use of his right arm and diminished his  
upper-body strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter fell Sunday while climbing steps to his home after saying  
goodbye to a friend. He was taken first to an Edenton hospital, 
then transferred early Monday to the Greenville hospital, which 
serves the East Carolina medical school. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had some bad knocks before, but this is the worst,'' said  
Tommy Harrell, who lives next door to the Hunters. ``The only thing 
people can do right now is pray for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Keith Vaughan, minister of The Hertford Baptist Church,  
said the church received calls from people in several states who 
said they were praying for the former pitching great. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Helen asked for prayers, that was a very sincere  
request,'' Vaughan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hunter issued a statement Wednesday expressing gratitude  
for Hunter's friends and fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outpouring of love and support for us and for Jimmy is a  
tremendous encouragement to us,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people have asked what they can do. The greatest thing  
you can do for us at this time is to pray for Jimmy and all the 
thousands who suffer from ALS.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
