<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tragedy Gets Blanket TV Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The shooting at a Jewish Center in Los Angeles  
had all the elements of a TV news thriller -- panicky parents 
worried about their children and a massive police search for a 
gunman who had slipped away. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the cable news networks blanketed the story, giving  
rise to concerns about encouraging copycats and the possibility of 
unwittingly helping the suspect before he was captured. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN, Fox News Channel and MSNBC went into crisis mode upon first  
word of the attack, which came Tuesday on a slow news afternoon. 
The networks are driven by intense competitiveness and the 
knowledge their ratings soar during big news stories. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something that is simply natural for the cable  
operators to do,'' said Marvin Kalb, director of the Joan 
Shorenstein Center on Press and Politics at Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeated incidents of gun violence this year have made it a  
topic of concern to many Americans and justified the extensive 
coverage, said John Moody, Fox News Channel vice president for 
news. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Fox News Channel probably would not have pre-empted its  
prime-time programming for the story if suspect Buford O'Neal 
Furrow had not still been at large, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN felt it was an important story but tried not to ignore other  
news, said Sid Bedingfield, executive vice president of CNN USA. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk of encouraging copycats ``is something we're concerned  
about,'' Bedingfield said. ``But on the other hand, you can't not 
cover the story. You can try to cover it responsibly and with 
perspective. But I don't think it helps to ignore the story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frequently during coverage, the news networks showed footage of  
police searching the neighborhood and a hotel where they believed 
Furrow might be hiding. 
</P>
<P>
	The president of National Information Officers Association said  
he was concerned broadcasters in Los Angeles went too far when 
there was a chance the suspect was watching TV. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may expose a weakness or may expose an officer to a suspect  
who may decide to go out in a blaze of glory,'' said Don Kelly, a 
Baton Rouge, La. police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles TV reporters, in comments aired over the images,  
said they were taking care not to show police activity that could 
endanger officers. But there were discrepancies: One station said 
it was withholding the number of the hotel room where the gunman 
was mistakenly thought to be holed up, another station reported it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedingfield said CNN frequently broke away from live shots that  
it thought might show too much. ``It's tough to do,'' he said, 
``and we weren't always entirely successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moody said he didn't believe showing police officers surrounding  
a hotel put the officers in danger, even if the suspect was 
watching. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
