<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. GOP Leaders Flock to Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Republican leaders in Illinois flocked  
to the side of GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush on 
Thursday as he made several campaign stops en route to Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of state officials endorsed Bush, the governor of Texas,  
during a Statehouse rally. Gov. George Ryan put his powerful 
campaign apparatus in Bush's corner. ``Without question, he is the 
best candidate available,'' Ryan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Govs. James R. Thompson and Jim Edgar gave their support,  
too -- along with the attorney general, lieutenant governor, state 
treasurer and a flock of legislators. 
</P>
<P>
	The first official votes in the presidential race won't be taken  
for months, and Bush has offered few details to flesh out his theme 
of ``prosperity with a purpose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Thompson said there is no reason for GOP leaders to wait.  
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me there is such a great gulf between Bush as a  
candidate and all the rest of the Republican candidates that it 
would be defying common sense, I think, to take that alternative,'' 
Thompson said. Others in the crowded field for the Republican 
nomination include Lamar Alexander, Dan Quayle, Pat Buchanan, Gary 
Bauer Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes. Bush is competing against 
them in the Iowa straw poll Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush made sure to discuss farm issues during his 20-minute  
speech to several hundred people in the Illinois' Capitol rotunda. 
He condemned any diplomatic policy of withholding food from other 
countries, stressed the importance of free trade and called for 
emergency aid to struggling farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, he reassured farmers that despite coming  
from an oil state, he supports the alternative fuel ethanol. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Bush told Missouri farmers that his  
``compassionate conservatism'' would offer money but no miracles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty simple logic,'' he said. ``If we rely upon people  
elsewhere to provide us food, we've got a national security risk. 
The next president has got to make sure agriculture is viewed as a 
mainstay of national policy, not a stepchild.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
