<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 14:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Talks Expected To Succeed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rising economic tensions between the United  
States and its major trading partners will not prevent the 
successful launch of a new round of global trade talks later this 
year, the Clinton administration said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Susan Esserman, who is leading  
the U.S. team preparing for the negotiations, conceded that serious 
differences remain over negotiating goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is pushing for a limited agenda focusing on  
tariff cuts on manufactured goods, agriculture and services while 
Europe wants more areas covered. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks, a follow-up to the 1986-93 Uruguay Round of trade  
liberalization, are scheduled to start in December at a meeting of 
the 134-member World Trade Organization in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``America, as the world's largest exporter, has much to gain  
from a new round of negotiations,'' Esserman told a group of 
reporters Thursday. She insisted that differences over the items to 
be discussed would be resolved before the Seattle meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Some trade analysts were not as optimistic, given growing  
protectionist sentiments in this country triggered by record trade 
deficits and rising trade tensions between the United States and 
its major trading partners, Europe and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is deep disagreement between the United States, the  
European Union, Japan and the developing nations over what ought to 
be included in the next round,'' said Gary Hufbauer, a trade expert 
at the Institute of International Economics, a Washington think 
tank. ``I don't see a smooth road ahead at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hufbauer said that part of the problem was growing foreign  
unhappiness with the administration's objections to including U.S. 
trade barriers in such areas as America's restrictive anti-dumping 
laws and high protections for textiles and apparel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The administration, in an effort to pre-empt U.S. opponents,  
has been taking things off the table that other countries want,'' 
Hufbauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Esserman said the administration would block any effort to  
include anti-dumping regulations as part of the upcoming 
discussions. The administration has used these regulations, which 
allow higher tariffs for U.S. industries threatened by imports, as 
the primary mechanism to provide relief for U.S. steelmakers in the 
wake of the Asian currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite differences, Esserman said consensus was forming around  
U.S. efforts to limit the upcoming round of talks to three years, 
preventing a repeat of the Uruguay Round, which dragged on for 
nearly eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Two areas of negotiations -- agriculture and services -- are part  
of the so-called built-in agenda, meaning that countries agreed as 
part of the Uruguay package to re-open talks in those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Esserman noted a recent agreement among trade ministers of the  
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation Forum, made up of the United 
States and other Pacific Rim nations, that the new talks also 
should aim to further cut tariffs on manufactured goods. 
</P>
<P>
	More progress could come in outlining the goals for the talks  
when President Clinton meets with other APEC leaders in New Zealand 
in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also is expected to have discussions with Chinese  
President Jiang Zemin while at APEC. Esserman refused to speculate 
on whether the two leaders would be able to strike a final 
market-opening trade agreement that would clear the way for China's 
membership in the WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	The two countries came close to a deal in April. Since then,  
discussions have broken off because of China's unhappiness with the 
mistaken NATO bombing of its embassy in Yugoslavia. A final 
agreement by lowering Chinese barriers would represent a boon for 
U.S. businesses and farmers hoping to break into the world's 
largest market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Mondesi Apologizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Raul Mondesi apparently regrets his outburst  
against the Los Angeles Dodgers' management. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after demanding a trade during a profanity-filled tirade,  
the outfielder was back in the lineup Thursday and the team issued 
a statement in which Mondesi apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of his anger Wednesday was directed at manager Davey  
Johnson and general manager Kevin Malone. Mondesi didn't speak with 
reporters Thursday, choosing to let the statement speak for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to apologize to Kevin Malone, Davey Johnson, my  
teammates and, most importantly, to Dodger fans for the comments I 
made yesterday,'' the statement said. ``In what has been a 
frustrating season, I let my emotions get the best of me. 
</P>
<P>
	'' I am thankful the fans in Los Angeles have stood behind me  
throughout my career and I will continue to play hard for the 
Dodgers. I am truly sorry this has been a distraction for my 
teammates and the organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His attitude was much different Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of all this,'' Mondesi said then. ``I told my agent  
to get me ... out of here as soon as possible. I can't take this 
anymore. I've had to deal with this all year. I told them to trade 
me because I don't want to ... be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mondesi said he was no longer willing play for Johnson  
and Malone, referring to both with profanities, he went 1-for-5 
Thursday in a 10-5 win over Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Under contract through 2001, Mondesi had stressed that Malone  
had better move him soon because he no longer considers himself a 
member of the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``They try to put all of our problems on me,'' Mondesi said.  
``They're trying to say that all this ... is my fault. That's the 
way they feel, fine. Just get me out of here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tirade was in response to Mondesi being benched for the  
second straight day Wednesday after arriving late to the team 
stretching session Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old was used as a pinch hitter against the Expos on  
Tuesday and Wednesday nights, and remained in Wednesday night's 
game after grounding out in the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi entered June hitting .286 with an NL-leading 18 homers  
and 44 RBIs but has slumped to a .248 average with 24 homers and 67 
RBIs. During one stretch in June and July, Mondesi went 112 at-bats 
without a homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi was the 1994 NL Rookie of the Year, and has won two Gold  
Gloves. In 1997, he became the only player in Dodgers history to 
hit at least 30 home runs with at least 30 stolen bases during a 
single season. 
</P>
<P>
	He is earning $8.5 million this season, and is owed $9.5 million  
next year and $11 million in 2001, the final guaranteed year of his 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone did not accompany the Dodgers on their road trip, which  
ended Thursday. When informed of Mondesi's comments, he expressed 
disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone declined to comment on Mondesi's future with the  
ballclub, although he intimated that enough is enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been a lot of things that have happened with Raul  
this season, and we've tried to be supportive and help him through 
them,'' Malone said. ``Everyone has worked very hard to help Raul, 
but we really don't know what else to do at this point. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're committed to bringing a winning team back to the fans of  
Los Angeles, and this isn't about individuals. We need to make this 
into a team of 25 guys who are all on the same page trying to win. 
Anyone who isn't on the same page isn't going to be here. Sometimes 
you have to make hard decisions, and we're prepared to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Moorad, Mondesi's agent, was on vacation, but released a  
statement through his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``Raul and I have talked at length about his frustration,''  
Moorad said. ``It was our hope that these issues would not come to 
a head during the season. I'm sure the Dodgers will do what they 
believe is in the best interest of the organization during the 
offseason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson made it clear that as far as he's concerned, the matter  
has been resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Mondy, a lot of times, gets some bad advice and he's  
very emotional,'' Johnson said Thursday. ``He's probably got a lot 
on his plate. We've turned the page. I don't have a doghouse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
