<HEADLINE> Barry Sanders Spotted in Detroit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- There's been a Barry Sanders sighting in  
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Free Press reported today that Barry Sanders was  
spotted at Detroit Metropolitan Airport shortly after 8 p.m. 
Wednesday getting off a Delta flight from Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	But the recently retired running back's father, William Sanders,  
said he hasn't heard from his son yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to call him,'' he told the newspaper, ``because  
he knows I want to talk to him. He's probably going to call me. I'm 
just going to play it by ear. I know he's back now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams Sanders and a friend, Allen Hughes, who happens to be  
in the Detroit Lions' front office as director of security, spent a 
couple of days together in Wichita where the elder Sanders now 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
	And, every once in a while, the two men even talked about Barry  
Sanders, who quit the Lions and football, and went to Europe for a 
vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hughes, who has been a guest in the family home since  
Monday, said he never pressured the elder Sanders to try to get his 
son to come back to the team. He did not have to -- Sanders had 
already promised his friend even before the visit that he would do 
anything he could to do that. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes told The Associated Press he came to visit in response to  
a long-standing invitation -- and not at the urging of the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not down here to try to convince anyone,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said he did not even tell anyone he was coming, except  
for one coach who he told so he wouldn't be considered absent 
without leave. He said he decided to take a few days off during 
training camp and planned to stay in Wichita another day or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has not been instructed as far as I know by anybody here,''  
Schmidt told the Free Press. ``It was a matter of him letting 
people know Mr. Sanders wanted him to come out, and what's the 
harm? It just makes sense to do it. Jocko has a relationship with a 
lot of players and their families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lions publicist Bill Keenist said Wednesday that Hughes was  
visiting Sanders as a Lions official, but would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he advised his son not to quit three years  
ago when he was considering it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This time he didn't ask me, he just quit,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said his son called to tell him about his decision to  
retire only so that he heard it directly from him rather than the 
news media. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was disenchanted with the direction the team was going. He  
was tired of losing,'' Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders announced his retirement July 28, the day before  
the team reported to training camp at Saginaw Valley State 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sanders said his desire to quit football outweighed  
his desire to play. When camp opened July 29, Sanders was in 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders quit needing just 1,458 yards to break Walter  
Payton's career rushing record. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
