<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 09:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- What constitutes religion? And who decides?  
Those are among the intriguing questions raised by the long-running 
struggle between gay activists and the Boy Scouts of America, in 
which some of the nation's biggest church bodies are participants. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 4, the New Jersey Supreme Court ruled that the scouts  
violated state anti-discrimination law by excluding avowed 
homosexuals from leadership positions. The case involved an 
assistant scoutmaster ousted because he was co-leader of a gay and 
lesbian group at Rutgers University. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ruled that the government's interest in ending  
discrimination outweighs the scouts' constitutional claim of 
freedom of association, that a private group is free to decide whom 
to include and exclude from membership. The decision produced 
predictable hallelujahs from gay-rights supporters and lamentations 
among cultural conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the way, the court plunged into some murky religious  
matters, including many churches' traditional opposition to 
same-sex behavior and their right to use scouts in youth work. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, New Jersey amended its Law Against Discrimination to  
forbid exclusion based on sexual orientation. The law covers any 
``place of public accommodation,'' from stores and restaurants to 
hospitals and schools. Other states have similar statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The law exempts ``distinctly private'' groups and the  
educational facilities of ``a bona fide religious or sectarian 
institution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The justices decided the BSA does not qualify as ``private''  
because it's too big and does public recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
	More troubling for some churches was the court's holding that  
the BSA is not religious enough to be exempt. The scouts, according 
to the ruling, do not ``endorse any specific set of moral 
beliefs,'' which the scouts dispute, or ``espouse any one 
religion,'' which they acknowledge. The ruling noted that the 
organization boasts of ``close association'' with ``virtually all 
religious bodies'' in America. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court may eventually need to settle these  
issues. Only last year, California's Supreme Court defined the BSA 
as a private club that can legally bar not only homosexual leaders 
but atheists, whom the scouts said violated their religious 
principles. 
</P>
<P>
	In the New Jersey case, religions were arrayed on both sides.  
The justices cited a brief against the BSA, filed by the Episcopal 
Church's diocese of Newark, and Unitarian Universalists, Quakers, 
Reform Jews and Reconstructionist Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	These groups said the anti-gay policy was disingenuous because  
the scouts welcome as troop sponsors some churches with liberal 
views on homosexuality. For instance, ``many openly lesbian and gay 
persons have been ordained as priests in the Episcopal Church.'' 
(True, though the Episcopalians' stated policy against same-sex 
behavior went unmentioned). 
</P>
<P>
	A radically different view is held by the scouting liaison  
offices within the Mormon, Roman Catholic and United Methodist 
churches. These are the BSA's top three religious backers, 
sponsoring 51,700 troops and other units with nearly 1.2 million 
scouts. They filed a legal brief in the case along with a fourth 
large denomination, the Lutheran Church -- Missouri Synod. 
</P>
<P>
	These churches contended that though the BSA is non-sectarian  
and interfaith, it is also dedicated to ``inculcating religious and 
moral beliefs, such as duty to God'' under the Boy Scout oath. The 
scouts hand out awards for boys' religious activity. Many churches 
consider scouting as part of their youth ministries. In Mormonism, 
it is a virtual department of the church. 
</P>
<P>
	Forcing the Boy Scouts to appoint gay leaders, the brief argued,  
puts churches in an ``untenable position'' if they sponsor troops 
and oppose homosexual conduct. Religious freedom is at stake, the 
churches said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever scouting's status, religious rights aren't what they  
used to be. At one time, U.S. Supreme Court doctrine held that the 
government needed a ``compelling'' reason before it could impose 
any substantial burden on the First Amendment guarantee of free 
exercise of religion. The Supreme Court tossed out its strict 
standard in 1990. Congress re-imposed it in 1993, but the Supreme 
Court invalidated that law four years later. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, an unusually broad alliance of 80 denominations and  
religious organizations is making another bid to revive the strict 
standard, through the Religious Liberty Protection Act, which 
passed the House last month and is awaiting Senate action. 
</P>
<P>
	Could employers or landlords use religious claims to  
discriminate against homosexuals under the legislation? An 
amendment to bar that was defeated by a 55 percent majority in the 
House, and some proponents fear a similar amendment in the Senate 
would kill the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	If the courts can require the BSA to embrace homosexuality,  
could churches some day face the same demand? The Washington 
lobbyist for the Southern Baptist Convention, Will Dodson, said 
that's a ``tremendous threat'' in light of the New Jersey ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	But a spokesman for Human Rights Campaign, a major homosexual  
lobby, says the movement has no interest in seeking legal limits on 
internal church policies. And Mark Chopko, chief counsel for the 
U.S. Catholic Conference, doubts the New Jersey case ``will have 
great implications for religious bodies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another seasoned First Amendment lawyer, Marc Stern of the  
American Jewish Congress, is not so sure. ``This is part of a 
growing judicial trend to be impatient with blatant discrimination 
against gays,'' he said. ``And it's not clear whether notions of 
church autonomy are sufficiently strong to withstand that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
