<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 05:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Stumps for GOP Tax Cut Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELGIN, Ill. (AP) -- Taking the battle over a proposed $792  
billion tax cut to the public, House Speaker Dennis Hastert urged 
taxpayers to support the GOP plan or else watch Democrats use the 
money ``to make government bigger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now is the time to take advantage of a projected federal  
government surplus, Hastert told about 150 blue-collar and 
management employees gathered Wednesday inside the ITW Shakeproof 
auto parts plant in this northwest Chicago suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should be able to make the decisions on how you spend  
those dollars. Whether it's for your kids' education, whether it's 
to save, whether it's to invest, or you know, if you decided to 
take a vacation, that's your business,'' Hastert said. ``It's not 
some bureaucrat in Washington that should make that decision for 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert chose the plant in his congressional district to jump  
start a grassroots push for the GOP tax package approved by the 
House and Senate last week on a largely partisan roll call. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders decided not to send the measure to the White House  
until after lawmakers return from their August recess for fear that 
President Clinton would veto it and dominate the public-relations 
war in Congress' absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, they have dispatched members to their districts to  
spread the message. Hastert plans a 10-day, seven-state trip next 
week to stump for Republican congressional candidates and the tax 
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	His message seemed to strike a chord with many in the factory,  
who applauded repeatedly. 
</P>
<P>
	``The working people are the ones that made the excess, so why  
not give the money back instead of letting the government waste 
it?'' asked Pat Williams, a 36-year veteran of the plant who 
nevertheless was skeptical that she would ever see the benefits of 
the plan. ``It's never quite what they promise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether he worried the tax cut could jeopardize federal  
government programs down the line, 29-year plant veteran Gary 
Miller replied: ``That's later. We can deal with the problems 
later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert warned the workers not to believe Clinton, who argues  
the government surplus Republicans want to tap is needed to pay for 
Medicare, farm programs and other spending critical to voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``He sees the surplus as a great opportunity to make government  
bigger,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who has said he would veto the tax bill, has indicated  
he does not want a confrontation with Republicans over spending 
this fall, and Hastert said, ``We're ready to sit down and talk 
with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the public TV program ``Nightly Business  
Report,'' Clinton said Wednesday there was room to negotiate a tax 
cut only after the budget priorities he has laid out have been 
addressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``My position is send me a Medicare proposal; let's figure out  
what we've got to spend on other things, and what we've got to do 
to pay the debt down, and let's give the rest back to the 
taxpayers,'' Clinton said. ``Then I will be very flexible about how 
we do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP bill includes a 1 percent reduction in all income-tax  
rates, an easing of the tax paid by many married couples, a capital 
gains tax cut, elimination of the inheritance tax on large estates 
and a slew of tax breaks for businesses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
