<HEADLINE> Red Hat Continues To Sizzle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Shares of Red Hat Inc. continued to sizzle  
Thursday, closing 40 percent higher on its second day of public 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-year-old vendor of Linux operating software went on the  
block Wednesday, and soared 300 percent above its $14 offer price, 
closing at $52.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Red Hat shares 
closed Thursday at $72.62 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's performance was the biggest price leap in at least  
two weeks among IPOs, which recently have hit a wall of investor 
nervousness about small, money-losing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat's share price Wednesday gave the Durham, N.C.-based  
company a market value of $3.8 billion -- even though Red Hat had 
sales of just $11 million and lost money last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat is the first Linux-only company to go public. Linux is  
an eight-year-old computer operating system that is a favorite of 
tech types because of its stability. Recently, it has become a 
player in the server market, used to manage the computers that run 
large networks. 
</P>
<P>
	While Linux software can be downloaded free over the Internet,  
Red Hat Linux 6.0 -- which includes a manual and some extra software 
tools -- sells for $79.95. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
