<HEADLINE> Mass. Barricaded Homeowner Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A man who barricaded himself on his 14-acre estate  
for nine months in a fight over whether he had to repay a bank loan 
was sentenced Thursday to four months in prison for contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sweeney, 59, was arrested peacefully in February 1998. His  
ancestral home that once belonged to his great-grandfather -- a 
secretary of the Navy, postmaster general and U.S. ambassador -- was 
sold at auction after he defaulted on the $1.6 million loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sickened by the court and its actions,'' Sweeney said  
after the sentencing. ``Is it over? No way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney will remain free pending appeal. He was convicted of  
contempt of court in a nonjury trial in April after ignoring a 
federal order to vacate his home because he defaulted on the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	The battle has attracted the interest of activists who claim  
they were swindled by the federal government, along with a handful 
of antigovernment volunteers who helped guard the estate during the 
standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweeney claims his refusal to leave his property wasn't illegal  
because the federal eviction order wasn't properly served. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
