<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citadel To Dump Boneyard Sign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Say goodbye to The Boneyard.  
</P>
<P>
	Citadel's athletic department will end one of the school's more  
recent traditions when it takes down the ``Welcome To The 
Boneyard'' sign behind one end zone at Johnson Hagood Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer's dig beneath part of the stadium for the remains of  
the crew of the Confederate submarine Hunley hit a little too close 
to home, athletic director Walt Nadzak said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want to be seen as insensitive or disrespectful,''  
he said. ``I think most people will understand that we don't want 
to offend anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers are sprucing up the place for The Citadel's home opener  
Sept. 11 against Delaware. Before they finish, Nadzak said, the 
sign will come down. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Hurteau of The Citadel's Brigadier Foundation said he  
mentioned to Nadzak that the school didn't need the obvious jokes 
anticipated when a wartime cemetery sits atop your Boneyard. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are so quick to criticize us anyway,'' Hurteau said.  
``We don't need to give them anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sign went up before the 1988 season when Citadel coach  
Charlie Taaffe brought the wishbone offense to the Bulldogs. As the 
team used it to run to three NCAA Division I-AA playoff spots and 
run past high-powered opponents like South Carolina, Navy, Arkansas 
and Army, a ceremony grew up. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was Spike's Boneyard,'' Citadel coach Don Powers said.  
The mascot, a snarling Bulldog, would tack up a new bone every time 
The Citadel beat an opponent for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pretty proud of getting to put South Carolina or  
Arkansas up there,'' Powers said. 
</P>
<P>
	For a month this summer, scientists, archeologists, researchers  
and equipment converged at the stadium to excavate beneath a room 
where Citadel boosters and alumni enjoy lunch before games. 
</P>
<P>
	They discovered 27 Confederate dead, including four thought to  
be part of the Hunley's crew. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Glenn McConnell, R-Charleston, instrumental in the recovery  
effort, said possibly two to four Confederate soldiers remain under 
light poles and support beams. A cemetery of widows and children 
may be located there, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Memorial Stadium, later renamed Johnson Hagood Stadium, was  
built by the city in 1947 as the home field for The Citadel and 
several Charleston high schools. A monument to the soldiers was 
moved to Magnolia Cemetery, and the contractor also was asked to 
move the graves. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials don't know why the contractor moved only the  
headstones, leaving 39 soldiers in the ground. The stadium was 
given to The Citadel in 1963, and it wasn't until 1990 that 
historians realized several Confederate sailors were underneath. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathon Leader, deputy state archaeologist for the state  
Institute of Archeology and Anthropology, said it was ``absolutely 
great they did this. I just hope they don't lose their connection 
to the wishbone, which has accomplished great things in football.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 14:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kmart Reports Higher Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Kmart Corp., the nation's third-largest retailer,  
said its operating profits jumped 44 percent in the second quarter, 
thanks to stronger sales at its discount department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart reported profits of $134 million, or 26 cents a share,  
excluding a one-time charge of $230 million related to the 
bankruptcy of Builders Square. In the second-quarter last year, 
Kmart had profits of $93 million, or 19 cents a share, excluding 
non-recurring charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were a penny a share higher than Wall Street  
expectations, according to a survey of analysts by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Including the charge, Kmart lost $96 million, or 15 cents a  
share, for the 13 weeks ended July 29, compared with a gain of $80 
million, or 16 cents a share, in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased with our second quarter performance,'' said  
Kmart Chairman and CEO Floyd Hall. ``In terms of sales growth, 
expense ratios and operating performance, this is the best second 
quarter and first half Kmart has achieved since 1993.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in the quarter totaled $8.8 billion, up 8 percent from  
$8.1 billion in the year-ago period. Sales at Kmart stores open at 
least one year were up 5.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart's stock rose 37 1/2 cents to $14.31 1/4 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart said that leases to 110 former Builders Square locations  
may become Kmart's responsibility under deals Kmart made when it 
sold the company. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, Kmart lost $29 million, or 1  
cent a share, compared with net income of $127 million, or 26 cents 
a share, for the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues were $16.9 billion vs. $15.6 billion.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
