<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Security High at Jewish Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Jewish leaders around the nation boosted security measures and  
worried about copycat crimes following the shooting attack by a 
white supremacist on a group of children in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't feel like an isolated incident, it feels like  
somehow a little bit of a wave,'' Rabbi Shea Hecht of the National 
Committee for the Furtherance of Jewish Education in New York said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack reminded Bill Coleman of Akiba-Schechter Jewish Day  
School in Chicago of the string of shootings in the Midwest last 
month. The shooter, a white supremacist, targeted blacks, Jews and 
Asians, and killed two people before turning the gun on himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Five people were injured in Tuesday's attack at the North Valley  
Jewish Community Center, including three young children and a 
teen-ager. 
</P>
<P>
	Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., 37, turned himself in Wednesday in Las  
Vegas and told authorities he wanted the attack to be a ``wake-up 
call to America to kill Jews,'' said an FBI source, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish leaders said most of their community centers and schools  
step up security when major crimes occur. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things happen to the Jewish community anywhere in the  
world, as a Jew, it makes your hair stand on end,'' said Rabbi Brad 
Bloom of Temple B'nai Israel in Sacramento, Calif., one of three 
synagogues damaged by arsonists in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The Anti-Defamation League in San Francisco sponsored seminars  
on security for religious groups. Tight security runs counter to 
the way religious people operate, said Jonathan Bernstein, director 
of the league's Central Pacific region. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to open their institutions to anyone who wants to  
come in,'' Bernstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	North Valley in suburban Grenada Hills remained closed  
Wednesday, guarded by police and security officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents and children nevertheless resumed their preschool and  
day-care classes, assembling next door at St. Andrews and St. 
Charles Episcopal Church. Children were sheltered there on Tuesday 
after the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Some parents who ordinarily would have dropped their children  
off and left decided to stay for the day's activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good because my father's here,'' said 10-year-old Abby  
Dreyfuss. Her dad, Jonathan Dreyfuss, said he was confident she 
would be protected. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people here are very good people and I'm sure they'll take  
the steps necessary to make this place safe,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nina Lieberman Giladi, an associate vice president of the  
organization that runs the center, said it was important for the 
children to return so they could see that their friends are all 
right. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to see each other face to face,'' said Ms. Giladi,  
whose 5-year-old son saw two bleeding victims. ``He wanted to talk 
about his friends, talk about what happened, talk about why this 
man did this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another father, J. Eliad, said his daughter saw the gunman.  
</P>
<P>
	``She told me the bad guy came here and shot everybody,'' he  
said. ``It's very hard to deal with the questions that she asks 
you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
