<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 08:30:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meeting With Jewish Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton was to discuss the Los  
Angeles Jewish center shootings with a delegation of American 
Jewish leaders at the White House, a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The private, late afternoon meeting today was scheduled before  
Tuesday's shootings, but hate crimes will be on the agenda, 
spokesman Barry Toiv said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toiv did not comment on whether the president believes the  
woundings of five people at the Jewish center was a hate crime. The 
suspected gunman, Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., told the FBI he 
intended the shootings as ``a wake-up call to America to kill 
Jews.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno said today the ``shootings appear to  
have been motivated by hate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hate crimes represent an attack not just on individual  
victims, but also on the victims' communities. They tear at the 
very fabric of a people's life,'' she said at her weekly briefing 
for reporters at the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno renewed the Clinton administration's commitment to stiffer  
gun control, and then went further. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we must seriously explore the possibility of  
requiring the licensing of all handguns,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is common sense, pure common sense, to ensure that guns are  
only in the hands of those who know how to safely and lawfully use 
them and have the capacity and the willingness to do so,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toiv would not address Reno's remarks.  
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Clinton said it is ``deeply disturbing'' to think  
the shootings were motivated by religious hatred. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only hope that this latest incident will intensify our  
resolve to make America a safer place, and a place of healing 
across the lines that divide us,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton last week reiterated his appeal to Congress to pass a  
hate crimes bill that would make it easier for the Justice 
Department to investigate and prosecute such offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved the measure last month and added it to a  
still pending spending bill. The House Judiciary Committee held a 
hearing on the measure last week. Critics say a federal law is 
unnecessary since states prosecute hate crimes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
