<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Booms Alters Economic Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The continued success of the American economy  
is rewriting the rules about economic expansion, unemployment and 
inflation, President Clinton says. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you really get in trouble trying to predict what's  
going to happen in the global economy where already we've defied 
all the predictions,'' Clinton said in an interview for a 
syndicated business program on public broadcasting stations. 
</P>
<P>
	When he took office, the standard rule was that a couple of  
consecutive quarters of low unemployment meant inflation would 
follow, Clinton noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the threat of inflation remains a bugaboo, the  
sustained economic expansion of the past five years has not brought 
significant price increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that the laws are being rewritten,'' Clinton said in  
the ``Nightly Business Report'' interview. The interview was taped 
at the White House on Wednesday for broadcast Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, that doesn't mean that the laws of economics have been  
repealed,'' Clinton said. ``It just means that our ability to 
predict is not as great as it would have been in a more stable 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said it is unrealistic to expect the stock market to  
repeat its stratospheric rise of recent years -- to a Dow Jones 
average about three times what it was when he took office in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're just not going to have that every five years,'' Clinton  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he is not worried about small losses in the market,  
as long as what he called the ``fundamentals'' are in order: a 
government commitment to pay down debt, make long-term investments 
and expand markets while remaining fiscally responsible. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
