<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- The son of G. Gordon Liddy, the former  
Watergate burglar turned radio host, is considering a run for an 
Arizona congressional seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phoenix attorney said this week he is ``testing the waters''  
after some Republican Party members expressed concern about the 
GOP's ability to retain the seat the incumbent Rep. Matt Salmon 
plans to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came to me and I've agreed to look at it,'' Liddy told  
The Tribune, a newspaper serving suburban Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Liddy met Tuesday with Salmon in what Tribune sources described  
as a courtesy call and chance to get Salmon's assessment of the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon has been helping another Republican, Goldwater Institute  
executive director Jeff Flake, by arranging ``meet and greet'' 
sessions between Flake and potential donors in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a pretty darn good field, but there's always room  
for more. Kind of like Jell-O,'' Salmon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon's congressional district includes Tempe, west Mesa and  
parts of Scottsdale, Chandler and Phoenix. It has a Republican 
majority, so competition is likely to be fiercest among the GOP 
hopefuls. Liddy lives outside the 1st Congressional District, but 
residency is not required to run for office. 
</P>
<P>
	Liddy moved to Scottsdale about a year ago after three years as  
deputy counsel with the Republican National Committee. But the 
37-year-old concedes his father's notoriety could both help and 
hurt him. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Alabama's Republican presidential straw  
poll, advertised as ``The Bellwether of the South'' and the first 
up after Iowa's, may simply be an indicator of how little interest 
presidential candidates have in Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no presidential candidate has committed to appear at the  
GOP's Alabama straw poll Aug. 28 in Birmingham, and several of the 
top names already have said they aren't coming -- Texas Gov. George 
W. Bush, former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole, publisher Steve 
Forbes, Arizona Sen. John McCain and conservative activist Gary 
Bauer. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for Bush and Dole said the candidates are  
participating in the Iowa straw poll Saturday because it is a 
political tradition, but aren't going to any others. 
</P>
<P>
	``The straw polls don't generate delegates. They are not the  
most efficient way to campaign,'' Dole spokeswoman Chris Hawes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, state GOP Chairman Winton Blount and members of  
the party staff are going to Iowa this weekend to try to stir up 
interest among the candidates and national media, party executive 
director Chris Neeley said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if no candidates show up, the party will go ahead with the  
straw poll for 3,000 people because it will produce money and 
membership lists for the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Blount announced Alabama's first straw poll in March, calling it  
``the South's first stop in the road to the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not working out that way, in part because Iowa has  
become a make-or-break event for some candidates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
