<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Owner, but Penguins Sign Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins don't have a new owner  
yet, but are quickly getting most of their unsigned players under 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Ian Moran was the latest to reach terms, signing a  
two-year contract worth $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Robert Lang reached terms this week on a contract worth  
$1.95 million and forward Alexei Kovalev signed for $4.6 over two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins general manager Craig Patrick is operating under a $30  
million player personnel budget drawn up by Mario Lemieux, who has 
yet to close on his purchase of the bankrupt team. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick earlier signed defenseman Jiri Slegr to a $2.3 million,  
two-year contract and defenseman Sven Butenschon to a $385,000, 
one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Matthew Barnaby was awarded a $1 million salary Thursday  
after taking his case to arbitration. Center Martin Straka is to 
appear before an arbitrator Saturday in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Three restricted free agents are unsigned: defenseman Darius  
Kasparaitis, forward Kip Miller and center Jan Hrdina. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
