<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steeler's Stewart Relearns Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The fullback and tight end stay on the field  
more, the backup wide receivers come on the field less. First down 
isn't always a Jerome Bettis carry. Third down isn't automatically 
a pass. 
</P>
<P>
	This new Pittsburgh Steelers offense is much different to  
quarterback Kordell Stewart, who is spending training camp learning 
his third offense in four years -- and learning why everything went 
so wrong last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The first glimpse of how well Stewart is assimilating new  
offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride's system will come when the 
player formerly known as Slash plays the first quarter Friday night 
against the Chicago Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Stewart himself doesn't know what to expect -- either from  
himself or Steelers fans, who grew increasingly agitated as Stewart 
failed to lead a single touchdown drive during a winless final 
month of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's No. 10 jersey was by far the Steelers' biggest selling  
merchandise item a year ago, but those sales have nose dived as 
dramatically as his quarterback rating did last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what the response is going to be,'' Stewart said.  
``Hopefully, it will be positive, but I have no idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart likes that he is throwing the deep pass much more than  
he did a year ago, when coordinator Ray Sherman never did seem 
comfortable running a system left over from the Chan Gailey days. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Steelers coach Bill Cowher is letting Gilbride  
install his own system, rather than asking him to adapt to an 
offense that was already in place. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do have more options with his offense,'' Stewart said. ``It  
is more open than it was last year. As far as the actual routes in 
the passing game, that is something I like more. You give guys more 
of an opportunity to get open. As opposed to two, now there are 
three or four trying to get open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there are no more than three receivers on the field at any  
time. Gilbride has scrapped the third-down offense that often 
called for Bettis, the team's most reliable weapon, and tight end 
Mark Bruener to come off the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Learning a new offense always takes time, but Stewart seems to  
be grasping it quickly, Cowher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can all see what it is going to be,'' Cowher said.  
</P>
<P>
	Even if Stewart doesn't always see it every day.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some days I go out and I hit the passes,'' Stewart said.  
``Then, all of a sudden, you have your off days. The main thing I 
want to work on is being consistent. If I can get the consistency 
level up to par, I think that is when we will be OK as a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart often seemed agitated and confused in training camp a  
year ago, but has displayed no such signs this summer. Cowher has 
noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make sure we expedite this process as quickly as  
possible without any undue pressures on him,'' Cowher said. ``From 
a standpoint of direction, this is a direction we all need to go. 
That is a very positive sign.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
