<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Expects Better Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia expects a better harvest this year compared  
to last year's drought-reduced crop, but still plans to import 8.9 
million to 9.5 million tons of feed grain, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's grain harvest of 53 million tons was the lowest in  
decades, prompting Russia to seek food aid from the United States 
and the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	First Deputy Agriculture Minister Anatoly Mikhalev said at a  
news conference Thursday that Russia wouldn't have to import grain 
for human consumption this year, and the harvest was expected to 
reach around 66 million tons. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent analysts have previously forecast this year's grain  
harvest as only marginally better at 56 million tons as a result of 
a cold snap in May followed by weeks of drought in June and July. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, locusts have hit central Russia and Siberia,  
devastating crops there. 
</P>
<P>
	Another problem which may affect the harvest is a sharp rise in  
gasoline prices and fuel shortages in some regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting Prime Minister Vladimir Putin ordered Cabinet members  
Thursday to take urgent steps to provide farms with sufficient 
fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We responded inefficiently to fuel price hikes,'' Putin said.  
``We must harvest grain, otherwise we will be forced to buy it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
