<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Cup Squabbling Continues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- Whoever first described Tom Lehman as  
golf's version of Everyman had no idea just how accurate he was. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so sick of this,'' Lehman said, ``I could just barf.''  
</P>
<P>
	Anybody within a par-5 of the PGA Championship on Thursday had  
to feel pretty much the same way. The squabbling over how to spend 
profits from next month's Ryder Cup continued so loud for so long 
it threatened to give charity a bad name. 
</P>
<P>
	And it disrupted the final major of the golfing season as surely  
as the lightning that crackled over the horizon in late afternoon 
and forced a 47-minute delay of the opening round. 
</P>
<P>
	On this day, at least, it didn't matter whose side you were on.  
The battle pitting the PGA of America and Ryder Cup captain Ben 
Crenshaw against a dissident faction within his own team has 
degenerated into one of those fights where it's a shame that 
somebody has to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days ago, Jim Awtrey, chief executive of the PGA of America,  
emerged from a closed-door meeting with Crenshaw and the team and 
boasted that ``everybody was on the same page.'' So naturally, a 
day later, Crenshaw ripped it to shreds. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you can't show up and play for your country and this is  
not reward enough,'' Gentle Ben thundered, ``that's when my heart 
bleeds for the game of golf. It's sick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And then, in an impetuous moment, Crenshaw raised the ante by  
identifying the dissidents at Tuesday's failed peacemaking session 
-- David Duval, Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara and Phil Mickelson. The 
last name was the only surprise; the first three had staked out 
their positions publicly for a while now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said 10 words, maybe 20 words,'' Duval said. ``Then I sat  
and listened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't back down from his assertion, first made in Golf  
Digest magazine, that the players should be able to direct some of 
the $17 million in profits from the Ryder Cup to charities of their 
choice. But Duval did admit that characterizing the event as an 
exhibition might have been a poor choice of words. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, though, didn't back down from anything he'd said. Just  
the opposite. Asked why he kept referring to the Ryder Cup as an 
exhibition, he fixed his questioner calmly and asked a question of 
his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is there a winner's check?''  
</P>
<P>
	Though Crenshaw was clearly winning in the court of public  
opinion, it must have occurred to him sometime around the middle of 
the afternoon that this was how ``Mutiny on the Bounty'' got 
started. So he tried to eat his words before the players made him 
walk the plank. 
</P>
<P>
	``I misspoke,'' Crenshaw said.  
</P>
<P>
	That was almost certainly a misstatement itself. What he  
probably meant to say was that he should have kept his mouth shut. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was frustrated,'' Crenshaw went on. ``It was my mistake. I'm  
from a different generation. The Ryder Cup means quite a lot of a 
lot of us. I want to continue to see that from both sides of the 
Atlantic. I probably got upset because I felt people weren't as 
excited about it as I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is a generation gap, to be sure, but it is less about age  
and more about an event that has grown from a sparsely attended, 
money-losing animal in Crenshaw's heyday to an overhyped, 
pressure-packed cash cow today. 
</P>
<P>
	The money has swelled to the point where the PGA, a  
not-for-profit operation, has gone out of its way to stress how 
responsibly those profits are distributed -- without offering to 
show anybody the books. The players, meanwhile, talk less about 
flag and country than they do about charitable tax write-offs. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting each other to stake out the higher ground, they've only  
succeeded in raising the gutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Awtrey griped about magazine reports the Ryder Cup would bring  
in gross revenues of $63 million and a $17 million profit for the 
PGA, but has done nothing to disprove them. Included in that 
operating budget are administrative costs of about $40 million, and 
you'd almost certainly lose money betting there aren't performance 
bonuses tucked somewhere inside. 
</P>
<P>
	The dissidents, meanwhile, have promised to donate any proceeds  
they receive to charity. But that overlooks the considerable 
write-offs people in their tax brackets covet. And then there's the 
question of the donations themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	For playing in the President's Cup, an event similar to the  
Ryder Cup, the PGA Tour donated $100,000 to charity on behalf of 
each player who made the team. O'Meara directed a share of his to 
the Lake Highland Preparatory School, which at least one of his 
children just happens to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	There is more than enough time to get the lawyers and  
accountants together to slug it out before the Ryder Cup actually 
begins. At the moment, the behavior on both sides is headed down 
such an unseemly road it makes you wish they would just shut up and 
play -- a suggestion that Lehman, still hoping to make the Ryder Cup 
team, offered at the end of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should all be ashamed of ourselves,'' he said, ``to bring  
this up now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
