<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To OK Autogrill-Marriott Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Italy's Autogrill, which controls Europe's  
largest restaurant group catering to travelers, said Thursday that 
U.S. antitrust authorities had pledged to approve its planned 
purchase of Host Marriott Services Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Autogrill SpA last month offered to buyout Host Marriott for the  
equivalent of $529 million in cash, at $15.75 a share. Host 
Marriott's board unanimously approved the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Antitrust authorities said they have no plans to oppose the  
acquisition and will formally approve the deal shortly, Autogrill 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethesda-based Host Marriott, a major presence in U.S. airports,  
is the U.S. leader in restaurant concessions, operating in almost 
200 locations. It has concessions in 18 of the nation's 20 largest 
airports and has the rights to the Burger King, Pizza Hut and 
Starbucks brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Autogrill, controlled by the apparel retailer Benetton, said the  
merger of the two companies would make it the world's biggest 
restaurant operator catering to travelers. It would have activities 
in North America, Europe, Australia and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Autogrill has 652 restaurants and bars in Europe. It recently  
won the rights to use the Burger King brand in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	It plans to operate in five main areas: highway restaurants,  
airports, shopping centers, railway stations and quick-service 
urban outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the combined sales of the two groups reached an  
equivalent of over $2.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Autogrill said that Host Marriott shareholders have until Aug.  
26 to tender their shares. The Italian company said that its offer 
is conditional based on the tendering of at least two-thirds of 
Host Marriott's shares. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
