<DOCNO> APW19990812.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Market Hit by Supply Glut / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices of long-term Treasury bonds tumbled and  
yields rose to a 22-month high Thursday after a fresh infusion of 
30-year securities glutted the market, dragging down demand for 
bonds already in circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Aggravating the price action, the Chicago Board of Trade was  
forced to shut down early because of a power outage, triggering a 
last-minute wave of selling. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 23/32  
point, or $7.19 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 6.27 percent, the highest since 
Oct. 28, 1997, when it closed at 6.28 percent. On Wednesday, the 
yield closed at 6.21 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices tumbled as the U.S. government brought $10 billion in new  
30-year bonds to market, meeting tepid demand from investors. The 
30-year auction saw weaker sales than a $12 billion sale of 10-year 
notes on Wednesday and a $15 billion sale of five-year notes on 
Tuesday. Still, it fared better than the last 30-year auction six 
months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader secondary market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities ranged from unchanged to 1/32 point lower, and 
intermediate maturities ranged from 1/16 lower to 1/4 point lower, 
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.76 percent with a  
discount of 4.64 percent, down 0.13 percentage point from late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.06 percent while the discount was 4.86  
percent, down 0.03 percentage point. One-year yields were 5.20 
percent with a discount of 4.94 percent, up 0.02 percentage point 
from late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.13 percent from 4.94 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 28/32 to 113 19/32. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.82 percent from 5.76 percent on Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Liberty Mutual To Cut 1,500 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Liberty Mutual Group plans to cut 1,500 jobs and  
reduce expenses by more than $150 million by the first quarter in 
2000 as it realigns its commercial insurance operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Mutual president and chief executive officer Edmund F.  
Kelly blamed the cuts on industrywide stagnation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commercial property and casualty industry has been in a  
prolonged period of price deflation,'' Kelly said Thursday. 
``Industrywide results have been extremely poor, and there is no 
sign of relief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reorganization will create a single account business unit  
from the Wausau Insurance Companies, which Liberty owns, and 
Liberty Mutual. The new unit will operate under the Liberty name. 
Integrated Disability Management will also operate under the 
Liberty name. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston-based Liberty Mutual sells workers' compensation  
insurance and international financial services. The company employs 
37,000 people in more than 900 offices worldwide, including 2,963 
people in Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	A Liberty Mutual spokesman declined to say where the jobs would  
be cut, and referred questions to Wausau Insurance in Wausau, Wis. 
A Wausau spokesman couldn't immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Liberty Mutual has more than $50 billion in consolidated assets,  
$61 billion in assets under management, and $11 billion in 
consolidated revenue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
