<DOCNO> APW19990812.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 14:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Byrne, Stronach Settle Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Thoroughbred trainer Pat Byrne has settled  
a lawsuit that charged owner Frank Stronach with fraud and breach 
of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne will receive most of the $84,000 in unpaid training fees  
he sought from Stronach, Lexington lawyer Laura D'Angelo said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the lawsuit, filed last month in Fayette Circuit Court in  
Lexington, Byrne had sought up to $384,000 in damages -- the 
training fees plus a $300,000 contract termination fee that he said 
Stronach tried to avoid paying. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was in both parties' best interests to try to come  
to a resolution, as opposed to going forward with litigation,'' 
D'Angelo said. 
</P>
<P>
	In January 1998, Byrne gave up his public stable, including 1997  
Horse of the Year Favorite Trick and champion 2-year-old filly 
Countess Diana, to train exclusively for Stronach, the Canadian 
industrialist who last year bought Santa Anita racetrack in 
Arcadia, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	But the relationship quickly soured. Byrne's lawsuit alleged  
that Stronach repeatedly failed to live up to the terms of their 
contract by sending many of his top horses to another trainer in 
New York and by failing to give Byrne a promised chance to select 
which 2-year-olds he wanted to train. 
</P>
<P>
	By November, when Byrne trained Stronach's Awesome Again to a  
victory in the Breeder's Cup Classic, the suit alleged that the 
trainer had only 15 horses in his stable, down from a high of 35. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne also charged that Stronach put off informing him that he  
wanted to terminate their contract until January to avoid paying 
the $300,000 termination fee. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the suit, Stronach then proposed a new contract  
under which Byrne would train 12-15 of his horses and would be 
allowed to reopen a public stable. Byrne agreed to the deal, but 
Stronach allegedly never sent him any horses. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached on Thursday at his barn in Saratoga, N.Y., Byrne  
referred all questions about the settlement to D'Angelo. 
</P>
<P>
	Since splitting with Stronach earlier this year, Byrne has  
rebuilt his public stable. It now includes 40 horses, three of whom 
have won at the Saratoga meet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:41:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Utah Tornadoes Rare, Not Impossible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tornadoes can form anywhere if the right atmospheric conditions  
exist -- from the Midwest to the Rockies and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether they touch down in Kansas or downtown Salt Lake City,  
twisters need several ingredients found only in large 
thunderstorms: Warm, moist air near the ground, cool air aloft and 
winds that speed up and change direction. 
</P>
<P>
	Some regions of the United States are more vulnerable.  
</P>
<P>
	The Midwest is in an area where warm, wet air from the Gulf of  
Mexico collides with the fast-moving and cooler winds from the 
Rocky Mountains or Canada. Twisters are most likely to occur there 
in the spring and summer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, meteorologists in Salt Lake City watched the same  
conditions develop over their state. A severe thunderstorm watch 
was issued at 12:48 p.m.; the twister touched down about seven 
minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw what was going on,'' said David Toronto, a  
meteorologist for the National Weather Service. ``But to look at it 
and say there's a tornado and it's going to hit downtown -- we 
didn't have that information because of the rapid development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It remained on the ground for about five minutes, he said. The  
tornado was classified as an F2 tornado -- one with wind speeds 
between 113 and 157 mph. Its wind speed was probably on the low end 
of that range, forecasters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes are rare in Utah. Thirty-two have been reported in the  
last 25 years, said Tim Shy, a researcher at the University of 
Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Oklahoma recorded 1,326 over the same 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Downtown areas also offer no special protection, he said. There  
just happen to be more rural than densely urbanized areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes we get a `Wizard of Oz' mentality that they occur in  
the middle of nowhere,'' Shy said. ``There have been enough 
counter-examples here recently, as Oklahoma City, Nashville and 
downtown Miami got hit in the last few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether a tornado strikes a building or a barn, the most  
dangerous aspect is the debris carried by high winds. Researchers 
have discounted theories that pressure differences cause structures 
to explode. 
</P>
<P>
	``The damage comes from wind and flying debris, and we saw that  
downtown today,'' Toronto said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 07:41:01 </DATE_TIME>
