<DOCNO> APW19990812.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 17:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxer Wants Probe of Wholesale Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sen. Barbara Boxer said Thursday she would  
ask the Federal Trade Commission to investigate whether big oil 
refiners are trying to drive small independent gasoline stations 
out of business by overcharging them. 
</P>
<P>
	Boxer wants the commission to investigate a run-up in the  
wholesale price of so-called ``unbranded'' gasoline -- fuel that is 
sold to independent dealers after the needs of company-owned 
stations and franchise holders are met. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks wholesale unbranded fuel has cost more than  
``branded'' gasoline, or that sold under a refiner's brand, Boxer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a conference call with reporters, she said she suspects oil  
companies are overcharging independents in an attempt to corner the 
retail market. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very suspicious that we have a higher price at the  
wholesale level for unbranded gasoline and these (independents) 
will be run out of business,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of independent dealers operating in California has  
fallen in recent years from around 2,000 to about 200, Boxer said. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Atlantic Richfield Co. said the high price for  
unbranded was a result of a decline in gasoline stocks caused by a 
series of refinery breakdowns along the West Coast. Less gasoline 
is left for sale in the unbranded market after companies' dealers 
are supplied, said spokesman Richard Verches. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are confident they will find there is no collusion and gas  
prices truly are a function of the marketplace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically branded gasoline costs more than unbranded. That's  
because branded fuel often includes special additives and is 
accorded higher retail value because of consumer regard for the 
brand name. 
</P>
<P>
	The average wholesale price for unbranded this week was $1.10  
per gallon, compared to $1.07 for branded, according to figures 
gathered by Boxer's staff from the California Energy Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Such price inversions are rare, but have occurred before when  
gasoline was scarce, said analyst Trilby Lundberg of the Lundberg 
Survey. A similar inversion occurred during the Gulf War, when some 
independents were nearly driven out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unbranded can, in scarce conditions, cost more than the  
branded gallon. We're going into our fifth month of supply 
tightness,'' Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is more severe in California, because of the state's  
more strict pollution rules, said Jay McKeeman, executive vice 
president of the 400-member California Independent Oil Marketers 
Association in Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a result of California fuel policy and the  
ability to make the California formulation of gasoline,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``In essence, we've created a situation where only the major oil  
companies can produce this material,'' he said. ``Number two, 
California is isolated from other fuel markets logistically and by 
this fuel formulation, so it's not real easy to get alternative 
supplies into California.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Hurts Trade Show Retailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Buddies Mark Tilles and Rich DiLeo drove  
11 hours from California, sleeping in their car, to make it to the 
world's largest trade show for outdoor retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The fledgling businessmen, who make hot dog holders and fly  
swatters, hoped the convention would be their big break. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the two stood outside a yellow police line near a  
flattened tent Thursday and watched a bulldozer carry away debris 
left by Wednesday's deadly tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Salt Palace Convention Center, meanwhile, hundreds of  
other exhibitors were setting up their booths, preparing for the 
opening of the show, delayed until Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going on with the show, and we're losing our stuff,''  
DiLeo grumbled. ``This is a show that could make or break a small 
company. These are potentially million-dollar contracts for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Outdoor Retailers Market, held twice a year in Salt Lake  
City for the past four years, allows manufacturers of everything 
from fishing poles to kayaks to peddle their goods to stores. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, 860 exhibitors had reserved 2,550 booths and 17,000  
retailers and visitors were expected. The tented pavilion held 700 
booths. Organizers didn't know how many were damaged by the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibitors were given 20 minutes Thursday afternoon to rush into  
the tent and gather and mark their property so emergency workers 
could remove it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It went great for us,'' said DiLeo, despite a television and  
videocassette recorder that bounced on the asphalt. Much of their 
merchandise escaped water damage and was, for the most part, where 
it they had left it Wednesday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Tilles, DiLeo and other exhibitors had been setting up their  
booths in the pavilion when the tornado hit downtown. Ventilating 
ducts in the pavilion began slamming against the ceiling and the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran to the door, and the entire crowd was behind us,''  
DiLeo said. ``The tornado was right out there -- you could see all 
these things churning in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiLeo and Tilles latched onto each other and grabbed a pole.  
Other exhibitors grabbed one another in desperate bear hugs, trying 
to fight the force of the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was over, DiLeo managed to grab a few newspaper articles  
about his product -- a patented fly swatter called the Buzzwacket. 
</P>
<P>
	Tilles left empty-handed, 1,600 samples of his Cowboy Hank's Hot  
Dog Holders still inside the tent. 
</P>
<P>
	The only person killed in the storm, Allen Crandy of Las Vegas,  
was struck in the head by debris. He had been inspecting booths in 
the pavilion. 
</P>
<P>
	Tilles, of El Cerrito, Calif., first released his product a year  
ago, selling to vendors here and there. DiLeo, from Berkeley, 
Calif., began marketing his fly swatter in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	For both men, the convention was a chance to break into a bigger  
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Many exhibitors whose booths were not damaged offered to share  
space with those who weren't so lucky. It will mean less space, but 
it is better than the alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to hurt, but we're not going to let this keep us  
down,'' said DiLeo. ``We didn't come this far to have a tornado 
take us out.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 18:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PGA Championship Glance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A look at the first round of the 81st PGA Championship, played  
on the 7,401-yard, par-72 Medinah Country Club: 
</P>
<P>
	LEADING: Sergio Garcia with a 6-under 66.  
</P>
<P>
	TRAILING: Jay Haas, Mike Weir and J.P. Hayes, two shots back.  
</P>
<P>
	LURKING: David Duval and Tiger Woods at 70, along with Tom  
Lehman and Nick Price. How's that for a scary foursome? 
</P>
<P>
	WORTH NOTING: Garcia, at 19 years, seven months and 27 days, is  
the youngest player to lead the PGA Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	KEY STATISTIC: Garcia had three birdies on the last five holes.  
That's one less than the next group back had all day. 
</P>
<P>
	QUOTEWORTHY: ``He rips it. If I swung that hard they'd have to  
pick me up in 14 different pieces and put me back together'' -- 
three-time U.S. Open champ Hale Irwin on Garcia, his playing 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	SUPER GROUP: Garcia, Irwin and Phil Mickelson.  
</P>
<P>
	OH, BABY: Amanda Brynn Mickelson, born the day after daddy lost  
the U.S. Open by one shot to Payne Stewart, slept through his 
birdie on the 18th hole. Mickelson finished with an even-par 72. 
</P>
<P>
	RAIN, RAIN, GO AWAY: With rain falling throughout the day at  
Medinah, golfers donned rain suits and popped their umbrellas. Play 
was suspended for 47 minutes late in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	SUPER SUB: First alternate Jerry Kelly, who learned an hour  
before he teed off that he was a starter, shot a 3-under 69. 
</P>
<P>
	TELEVISION: Friday, 1-7 p.m. EDT, TNT.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
