<DOCNO> APW19990812.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 08:45:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Plans Push Against Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian jets and helicopters attacked  
Islamic rebels in southern Russia for a sixth day today, and a 
general said a ``massive operation'' would be launched soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian forces have been using their superior firepower to  
hammer away at the militants in the Caucasus Mountain region of 
Dagestan. But ground troops have been reluctant to fight the 
separatist rebels, who are holding several villages. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Anatoly Kornukov, the commander-in-chief of Russia's  
airborne forces, said Russia had launched 200 sorties against the 
rebels since the fighting began, and the ``best-trained contingent 
of airborne and special-purpose troops'' were being airlifted to 
the region. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels say they remain well-entrenched and claim a  
helicopter shot down Wednesday was the eighth Russian aircraft they 
have hit since the fighting began last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians acknowledged losing a helicopter Wednesday, saying  
one soldier was killed and nine were wounded. Three of the wounded 
were generals in the Interior Ministry. Moscow says it has lost 
only three helicopters in the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	A Russian Defense Ministry official, Gaidar Gadzhiev, said some  
militants were attempting to flee the region after coming under 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The military has been making the same claim for several days,  
yet the rebels continue to put up strong resistance in several 
villages in the Botlikh region near Dagestan's border with 
Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Dagestani Interior Ministry, eight rebels were  
killed Thursday, while Russian forces suffered no losses. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, President Boris Yeltsin met acting Prime Minister  
Vladimir Putin in the Kremlin and said he was confident the rebels 
would be subdued. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall be able to overcome this problem gradually, without  
haste, just as it was planned,'' Yeltsin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin, who was appointed to the job Monday, has promised swift  
action, saying the insurgents will be crushed within two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult to win a clear victory over guerrilla groups,  
but we will do everything to free the villages and wipe out the 
gunmen,'' said Lt. Gen. Igor Zubov, the deputy interior minister. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a ``massive operation'' would begin soon, adding that  
``the territory will be fully sanitized.'' He did not give 
additional details. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Dagestan announced it would censor war coverage in  
the local media. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan's State Council, the republic's executive body, said  
all reporting on the conflict would have to be approved by the 
ministry of information before it could be published or broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dagestan fighting is the biggest challenge to Russian  
authority since the 1994-6 war with Chechnya. The rebels 
infiltrated from lawless Chechnya, which has had de facto 
independence since the end of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels are being led by two prominent commanders from the  
war in Chechnya, Shamil Basayev and Khattab, who uses only one 
name. Many of the rebels belong to the fundamentalist Wahhabi sect 
and are seeking an independent Islamic republic in the mostly 
Muslim regions of the Caucasus Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they do not appear to have broad support among ordinary  
residents in Dagestan, unlike in Chechnya, where the vast majority 
of the population supported secession from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan's moderate political and religious leaders are working  
in tandem with the Russian military, and have been recruiting 
volunteers to fight the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the number of rebels has varied widely, but a  
Russian official on Wednesday put the figure at about 1,200. 
Dagestan's Interior Ministry said 6,000 civilians had fled the 
fighting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 08:45:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
