<P>
	``It is difficult to win a clear victory over guerrilla groups,  
but we will do everything to free the villages and wipe out the 
gunmen,'' said Lt. Gen. Igor Zubov, the deputy interior minister. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a ``massive operation'' would begin soon, adding that  
``the territory will be fully sanitized.'' He did not give 
additional details. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Dagestan announced it would censor war coverage in  
the local media. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan's State Council, the republic's executive body, said  
all reporting on the conflict would have to be approved by the 
ministry of information before it could be published or broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dagestan fighting is the biggest challenge to Russian  
authority since the 1994-6 war with Chechnya. The rebels 
infiltrated from lawless Chechnya, which has had de facto 
independence since the end of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels are being led by two prominent commanders from the  
war in Chechnya, Shamil Basayev and Khattab, who uses only one 
name. Many of the rebels belong to the fundamentalist Wahhabi sect 
and are seeking an independent Islamic republic in the mostly 
Muslim regions of the Caucasus Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	However, they do not appear to have broad support among ordinary  
residents in Dagestan, unlike in Chechnya, where the vast majority 
of the population supported secession from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan's moderate political and religious leaders are working  
in tandem with the Russian military, and have been recruiting 
volunteers to fight the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the number of rebels has varied widely, but a  
Russian official on Wednesday put the figure at about 1,200. 
Dagestan's Interior Ministry said 6,000 civilians had fled the 
fighting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 22:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barney Loses Lawsuit Over Lookalikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Sorry, Barney.  
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled Wednesday against Lyons Partnership, which  
licenses Barney products and had accused Morris Costumes of renting 
and selling purple, Barneylike animal costumes under different 
names. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons sought an injunction preventing Morris Costumes from  
renting or selling the costumes, as well as $300,000 for 
infringement of its copyright. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Graham Mullen ruled that a Duffy the Dragon  
costume didn't infringe on Barney's copyright but two other 
costumes did because they were more similar to Barney. But he said 
Morris Costumes didn't infringe willfully, so Lyons couldn't 
collect damages in its 1997 lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Mullen denied the injunction request, noting that Morris  
Costumes had already stopped marketing the Hillary and Purple Dino 
costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Barney is a 6-foot, grinning, green-spotted purple dinosaur who  
sings and dances for preschoolers on the top-rated PBS show 
``Barney and Friends.'' About 12 million people see the show each 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons has sued or plans to sue at least 700 costume shops and  
other retailers in 20 states, claiming copyright infringement. 
Lyons said the costumes will tarnish Barney's image if people 
wearing them are seen smoking, drinking and swearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been photographs in newspapers of a person in a  
bogus Barney costume with the head off smoking a cigarette,'' Lyons 
spokeswoman Kelly Lane has said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no beef with Barney,'' said Jay Bilas, the lawyer who  
helped represent Morris Costumes. ``But the people behind Barney 
acted like bullies.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints Add Win Experience With Clay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) -- For the past six years Willie Clay has  
been on playoff teams. Now he's with the New Orleans Saints, the 
team that last season had the NFL's worst pass defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Can Clay's streak possibly continue?  
</P>
<P>
	``I think so,'' the safety said Thursday. ``When I look at this  
team I see a strong defense that was on the field for a long time 
last year. All we need to do is get a little better and we can turn 
that 6-10 to 10-6. That's our goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clay, 5-foot-10, 200 pounds, admits another one of his streaks --  
80 consecutive starts, dating back to the end of the 1993 season 
with the Detroit Lions -- is in danger. But he is expected to push 
free safety Rob Kelly aside for the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want a fair chance and that's what the Saints promised  
me,'' Clay said. ``I've done a lot of things in this league, and I 
definitely think I'm capable of doing more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drafted by the Detroit Lions in the eighth-round in 1992, Clay  
jumped to the New England Patriots in 1996. He has 24 career 
interceptions, including two in the playoffs, and has scored four 
touchdowns. He qualified as a Pro Bowl alternate the past two 
seasons, and was a starter for the Patriots for 54 games, including 
the 1998 Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a personality contest,'' coach Mike Ditka said.  
``We've got to get better. Clay is here for that reason only, 
because we're trying to get a little better. If Willie Clay is the 
answer to making us a better football team, why wouldn't we sign 
him?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Being cut by New England was a shock, Clay said. He also  
expressed doubts that his $1.906 million salary against the 
Patriots' salary cap was the reason for the move, although that's 
what New England claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	Clay's strained relationship with Patriots' coach Pete Carroll  
was also reported to have been a factor for cutting him loose. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who knows, I just hope this turns out to be a good move for me  
and the Saints,'' said Clay, who will earn the full salary he would 
have made with New England if he meets all his incentives, 
including five interceptions and seven big plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides pushing Kelly, Clay is expected to add experience and  
leadership to the secondary. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not that I'm unhappy with anyone. He just gives us more  
experience,'' defensive coordinator Zaven Yaralian said. ``Right 
now, Sammy Knight and Rob Kelly are our starters. Do we have 
experience behind them? No. If there's a player out there who can 
improve our team, then we should try to sign them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clay practiced with the second team on Wednesday and looked  
sluggish, something both Clay and coaches blamed on his lack of 
training camp work. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's smooth,'' Ditka said. ``He knows what he's doing. I just  
watched him backpedal and do some things but I thought he looked 
pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clay, who will not play in New Orleans exhibition game against  
Miami Friday night, watched the Saints walk-through on Thursday 
from the sidelines. He remained on the field for some individual 
work that included running sprints. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be tough to learn this system, going to mean a  
lot of hard days and long nights,'' Clay said. ``But the main thing 
I need is just repetitions. If I get enough of those, I think I'll 
be ready in two weeks. That's my goal, anyway.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 22:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rockies Pitcher Astacio Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWOOD VILLAGE, Colo. (AP) -- Colorado Rockies pitcher Pedro  
Astacio was arrested Thursday when he turned himself in to police 
following an alleged altercation with his estranged wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Astacio, acquired from the Los Angeles Dodgers on Aug. 18, 1997,  
for infielder Eric Young, faced charges of third-degree assault and 
domestic violence, reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Lt. Joe Carns said a 911 call came in at 10:57 p.m.  
Wednesday. A woman said her estranged husband had been arguing with 
her and she advised him to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said he struck her in the face,'' Carns said.  
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, later identified as Astacio, had left his suburban  
house by the time officers arrived, but turned himself in about 4 
p.m. Thursday. He was taken to the Arapahoe County Jail for booking 
and to arrange bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the case would be handled by the county  
attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies had no formal statement on the situation.  
</P>
<P>
	Astacio is 12-9 with a 4.88 ERA and leads the team in victories.  
He ranks fourth in the NL with 149 strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Astacio pitched the entire 1998 season in the Rockies rotation  
without missing an assignment, and set a personal best with 34 
starts and topped 200 innings for the third straight season. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ninth in the NL with a career-best and club-record 170  
strikeouts and became one of only three pitchers in Rockies history 
to win 13 games in a season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990812.0317 </DOCNO>
