<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 15:56:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Focuses on Islamic Uprising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Facing criticism that Russia hasn't acted quickly  
enough to quash an Islamic rebellion in the south, President Boris 
Yeltsin promised on Thursday that the militants would be wiped out 
steadily but ``without haste.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's acting prime minister, Vladimir Putin, was chastised  
Wednesday by members of Russia's upper house of parliament, who 
said Russia should act more resolutely to stamp out the rebels who 
invaded several villages in the Caucasus region of Dagestan last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers warned that the hostilities in Dagestan resemble  
those at the onset of Russia's botched war in the breakaway 
republic of Chechnya in 1994-96. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin said he was confident the rebels would be defeated,  
though he admitted that ``along with Chechnya, (Dagestan) is the 
most difficult region.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall be able to overcome this problem gradually, without  
haste, just as it was planned,'' Yeltsin said before his meeting 
with Sergei Shoigu, minister for emergency situations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Russian aircraft again fired on Islamic rebels, and  
more troops and weapons were sent to southern Russia. The militants 
maintained their hold on several villages. 
</P>
<P>
	Shoigu said his ministry was preparing to start relief  
operations in Dagestan once the fighting had stopped, but the 
conflict so far has shown few signs of abating. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin dismissed media reports that the Kremlin may use the  
fighting to introduce emergency measures, which in turn could 
result in the postponement of December's parliamentary elections. 
Yeltsin's allies are not expected to fare well in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Putin admitted that a state of emergency was a  
possibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may talk about the introduction of a state of emergency  
when it's necessary,'' he said after meeting at the upper house, 
the Federation Council. Under Russian law, the Federation Council 
must approve the call for a state of emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, most political factions appeared ready to approve  
Putin as prime minister in a vote Monday, despite their anger over 
the abrupt Cabinet reshuffle -- the fourth in 17 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin met with leaders from the ultranationalist Liberal  
Democratic Party on Thursday, telling them he did not plan to make 
any major rearrangements in the Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	If parliament rejects Putin's nomination three times, Yeltsin  
would be required to disband the legislature. But the Communists 
and other hard-liners who dominate parliament do not appear 
interested in a confrontation with Yeltsin as elections draw near. 
</P>
<P>
	Most observers believe the current political shakeup is part of  
a Kremlin effort to undermine a political alliance led by Moscow 
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, a leading presidential candidate who teamed up 
last week with a bloc of powerful regional governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's inner circle is believed to be vying to preserve its  
grip on power after the presidential election, after which Yeltsin 
is required to step down. Luzhkov almost certainly would not give 
Yeltsin's entourage the influence it wants if he were elected. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
